<FIRST>u i AM-Uruguay-Torture 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay-Torture, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0782,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Awards Torture Victim $47 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS final 3 grafs 8-10 `In April...is jailed.'' to CORRECT
general's name to Carlos Suarez Mason. Also Suarez Mason never paid sum.
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ordered the Defense
Ministry to pay $47 million to an electrician tortured during
Uruguay's 1972-85 military dictatorship, a newspaper reported
Thursday.
   A government spokesman said the Defense Ministry will appeal the
order.
   The victim, who was not identified by name, was held without
charge from January 1976 to May 1977, the weekly Busqueda reported.
   His injuries were not described, but the newspaper quoted Civil
Court Judge Carlos Berlangieri as saying in his ruling that they
prevent the man from returning to work. The report did not say what
day the ruling was made.
   A crackdown on leftist subversion was a major feature of the
military government which oversaw a return to civilian rule on March
1, 1985.
   Under military rule, about 150 suspected leftists were killed _
compared to at least 8,961 in neighboring Argentina during its junta
of 1976-83 _ and several thousand were arrested and tortured.
   Lawyers said they know of no precedent in Uruguay for the huge
award.
   In April 1988, the San Francisco District Court ordered fugitive
Argentine Gen. Carlos Suarez Mason to pay $21 million to Horacio
Martinez Baca, who was tortured on the general's orders during the
1976-83 dictatorship.
   That is believed to be the largest federal civil award for a
civil rights abuse.
   The cashiered general, however, never paid the sum. He was
extradited to Argentina, where he was convicted of murder and still
is jailed.
</TEXT>
