<FIRST>u a AM-Boeing-Engines     06-15 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Engines,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Orders Grounding of Some 737-400s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on Wednesday
ordered airlines to ground some Boeing 737-400 jetliners until
certain engines that have been operated at high thrust are modified
or replaced.
   The emergency airworthiness directive, distributed by telegram,
comes after Britain's Civil Aviation Authority ordered 12 of the new
twinjets grounded following two incidents of trouble with their
CFM56-3C engines.
   The same model of engine was on a British Midlands 737-400 that
crashed in January, killing 47 people. The cause of that crash has
not been determined.
   Boeing Co. and the engines' manufacturer, CFM International,
issued their own advisory Tuesday, urging airlines to ground the
jets until the engines are replaced or have their thrust capacities
reduced.
   The sole U.S. operator of 737-400s, Piedmont Airlines, already
has replaced engines on the affected planes, a spokesman said.
   The FAA's order requires airlines to immediately remove from
service all fan blades and disks on CFM56-series engines that have
been operated at 23,500 pounds of thrust. The agency also said, as
did Boeing and CFM International, that all CFM56-3C engines on
737-400s should be modified to operate at a maximum 22,000 pounds
thrust.
   The CFM56-3C was designed with higher thrust to provide more
power for the 737-400, a ``stretched'' version of the widely used
737-300. The 737-400, which carries 146 passengers, went into
service last year.
   The FAA said CFM56-3B engines, which are rated at up to 22,000
pounds thrust and used on both the 737-400 and smaller 737-300, have
had excellent reliability with no fan blade failures in a cumulative
6 million flight hours.
   Boeing spokesman Craig Martin said the FAA order affects 28
planes with the 3C engines, all outside the United States.
   In addition to the British order, West Germany on Tuesday ordered
engines checked in the four 737-400s used in that country.
   Last Friday, a Dan Air 737-400 with the 3C engines carrying 100
charter passengers to Minorca returned to London's Gatwick Airport
after developing severe vibration in one engine.
   On Sunday, a British Midlands 737-400 with the same engines
flying from London's Heathrow Airport to Belfast, Northern Ireland,
with 80 people aboard made an emergency landing at East Midlands
airport after a problem developed in one engine.
   In both cases, the airlines reported turbofan blades had been
damaged.
   In the January British Midlands crash, the pilot reported that
one engine had failed in flight, but investigators later found the
plane's remaining good engine had then been shut down before an
emergency landing was attempted.
   The investigation of that crash has not been completed.
   CFM International is a joint venture of General Electric Co. of
the United States and SNECMA of France.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
