<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe     06-15 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Office Probed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials are investigating an
auditor's report that $1 million is missing from a rent-subsidy
account in the Denver regional office of the Department of Housing
and Urban Development, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post, quoting unidentified HUD officials and other
sources, said in its Thursday editions that case had been turned
over to the Justice Department.
   Mary Brunette, an aide to HUD Secretary Jack Kemp, told the
newspaper that auditors from HUD's Office of Finance and Accounting
will travel to Colorado next week to review cash accounts at the
office, one of about 80 branch offices nationwide that are being
audited.
   She was also quoted as saying that HUD has hired an outside
consultant _ Washington, D.C.-based Irving Burton Associates _ to
review accounts inside HUD headquarters.
   An accountant was suspended without pay from the office on June
4, she said.
   HUD had earlier disclosed that nationwide audits would begin
Thursday to reconcile property sales accounts at HUD's regional
offices.
   A HUD spokesman Wednesday night said he had no comment on the
Denver case report. But Jack Flynn said, ``The secretary has ordered
reviews of these offices across the country for that kind of thing.''
</TEXT>
