<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China-Tourism     06-15 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Tourism,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourism Near Standstill in China; Hotels, Shops Deserted</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY CHENAULT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two armed soldiers stand guard at the entrance to
a hotel in central Beijing, watching as soldiers come and go from
the lobby once bustling with travelers.
   ``Troops are staying here. You don't want to stay here,'' a man
whispers to a foreigner asking if Chongwenmen Hotel is open.
   At a nearby restaurant, employees in the darkened building
shrugged Wednesday when asked if the business will reopen.
   ``We don't have any foreigners,'' one man said as he and two
other employees sat idle at Maxim's restaurant. ``We need foreign
people to make money. Now, we have no work.''
   The violent crackdown on China's pro-democracy movement 11 days
ago has prompted an exodus of foreigners, bringing tourism to a near
standstill.
   While some city residents try to get on with their lives, workers
at shops, markets and hotels seek to overcome the potentially grave
economic prospects facing businesses that depend on tourism.
   A vendor of Mao Tse-tung memorabilia responds bitterly when asked
about business:
   ``Americans don't like us. They say China is bad. They don't like
(senior Chinese leader) Deng Xiaoping so they leave China and others
leave, too.
   ``Now, no one buys my things, so I sleep or listen to the radio.''
   Before the turmoil, the market near a foreign diplomatic compound
was filled with people browsing or trying to strike a deal. Now,
hopeful vendors carefully display silk items, hand-carved
knickknacks and Western-style clothing. But the market appears
abandoned.
   Another man responds to a question about business by spreading
his arms and making a noise to imitate a plane taking off.
   Managers at some tourist hotels gave dire reports.
   ``We could not go on like this for very long,'' said Rudolph
Staudinger, manager of the two-year-old Shangrila Hotel. ``We have
not paid back the bank loan.''
   He said staff members will be paid for staying home while
business is slow.
   But he added, ``Some of our regular customers, some who left
because of safety concerns, are planning to return. Those are good
signs.''
   He said 100 of the hotel's 780 rooms were occupied Tuesday, many
by businessmen who travel to China frequently.
   At Jianguo Hotel, now one of the journalist enclaves in the city,
manager Peter Hierzi said he may offer free breakfast, tea,
cocktails and newspapers to attract guests. For now, the hotel is
encouraging employees to take vacation time.
   When demonstrators flooded Tiananmen Square last month, the
landmark Beijing Hotel offered prime views of the square and the
Forbidden City, the former seat of emperors that is a prime tourist
attraction.
   Now the grand building is nearly deserted. Cafes and souvenir
shops are dark. From time to time the telephone rings, but goes
unanswered.
   The Friendship Store has reopened. But customers are scarce at
China's largest shopping center for overseas tourists.
   Store manager Li Hengmao told the official Xinhua news agency
that the store sold $28,000 worth of goods when it reopened Monday.
The store did a daily turnover of $405,000 this time last year, the
report said.
   Two tourists from Holland were buying a suitcase to carry things
they had bought. They planned to leave China today, cutting their
trip short on advice from the Dutch Embassy.
   ``There's so much we wanted to see, but it isn't comfortable here
so we're leaving,'' one said. They planned a quick trip to the
Forbidden City.
   China Daily newspaper reported 3,688 visitors _ one-tenth the
usual number _toured the Forbidden City when it opened Tuesday for
the first time since martial law was imposed May 20.
   Buses and subways also have started operating again in Beijing,
and the state tourist service is encouraging foreign travelers to
continue seeing China.
   But few offices of the China International Travel Service are
open. Previously, it offered tours to some of the most famous sites
around Beijing, including the Great Wall, the Ming Tombs and the
Summer Palace. Now, travelers are given directions and told to take
a taxi.
   In some ways, the tourist drought could make travel in China
easier for those still interested in seeing the vast country.
   At Beijing railway station on Wednesday, a foreigner could buy a
ticket for a train leaving for Shanghai later in the day.
Previously, a three- to five-day wait was common.
   A China International Travel Service employee told an inquiring
foreigner:
   ``I think that if you were at the Great Wall today, you would
have it all to yourself. Anywhere you go there would be no crowds.
It is a good time to see China.''
</TEXT>
