<FIRST>u w AM-Aspin-Budget     06-15 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aspin-Budget,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Head Now Backing Pentagon Weapons Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee says he is now trying to push through the Pentagon's
reduced weapons-buying budget without change, according to an
interview report.
   In Thursday editions of The Washington Post, Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., was quoted as saying that members normally would re-arrange
the weapons requests to add or boost spending for weapons bought in
home districts.
   ``This time it's different,'' Aspin was quoted as saying.
   Some members have told him of plans to propose restoration of
$6.8 billion in weapons spending to the $10 billion in proposed cuts
announced by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney in April, Aspin said.
   But he said he knew of only about $1 billion in possible cuts
that could be made to offset those additions without cutting other
weapons programs.
   ``Somebody else is going to have to lose what they already have
in the budget if these add-ons are approved,'' Aspin was quoted as
saying.
   In an atmosphere clouded by scandals among the Democratic
leadership, many committee members ``think a vote for the Cheney
budget will look like a good-government vote,'' Aspin was quoted as
saying.
   Among cuts proposed by Cheney are the dropping of the Marine
Corps' planned V-22 Osprey vertical take-off troop-carrying
aircraft, cancellation of an attack submarine, deferral of some
purchases of the Navy's F-A-18 fighter, cancellation of the F-15E
Air Force fighter and the F-14D Navy fighter.
   Next Tueday, a subcommittee of Aspin's committee is to start
consideration of the procurement section of the Pentagon's $300
billion authorization bill for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
