<FIRST>r i PM-Guatemala-Rights     06-15 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guatemala-Rights,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guatemala Government Rejects Charges of Rights Abuse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The civilian-led government has denied
charges by Amnesty International that it has allowed the army and
police to operate death squads.
   The London-based international human rights organization released
a report Wednesday that says 222 people have disappeared in
political violence since President Vinicio Cerezo took office in
1986.
   Cerezo, a centrist Christian Democrat who took over as the first
civilian leader in 20 years, took power with a pledge to end
political killings, intimidation, and other abuses of previous
military governments.
   The Foreign Ministry, responding to Amnesty's charges, said
Wednesday: ``There are no death squads as Amnesty International so
irresponsibly declares.''
   ``The government of Guatemala respects human rights,'' it said.
   However, the ministry added, ``The fact that isolated cases of
violence against human rights exist does not constitute a
governmental policy. They are occasional acts that still escape the
control of the state's reorganized security forces.''
   In its report, Amnesty said such violence had at first decreased
under Cerezo's government. However, it went on, ``Although the
number of abuses decreased initially, there has been a resurgence of
abductions, `disappearances' and extra-judicial executions in the
past 18 months.''
   Amnesty said people viewed by the government as left-wing _
peasants, union members, clergy, academics and students _ have been
singled out by death squads.
   Amnesty International spokeswoman Tracey Ulltveit-Moe said Cerezo
himself was apparently not directly involved in the death squads.
But she said his government had failed to investigate the killings.
</TEXT>
