<DOCNO> AP890615-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Cambodia     06-15 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Cambodia,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress `a Brick Wall' on Aid to Cambodian Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is pursuing covert aid
to the non-communist forces opposing the Vietnamese-backed
government in Cambodia despite unlikely odds on Capitol Hill of
receiving funds.
   A senior administration official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Wednesday the State Department realized it was
engaged in ``more than an uphill battle.''
   ``It's doubtful we'll get the increased assistance,'' the
official said.
   Members of Congress say they fear military aid, covert or
otherwise, could wind up in the hands of the communist Khmer Rouge.
The Khmer Rouge, also fighting the Phnom Penh government, gained
notoriety for the brutality of its regime from 1975 to 1978 when
more than 1 million people died under Pol Pot.
   The Soviet-armed Vietnamese forces invaded in 1978 and ousted the
Khmer Rouge, setting up the current government.
   The administration is seeking the covert aid to strengthen the
hand of Prince Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's former ruler, in
negotiations with the Cambodian government and the Khmer Rouge, the
official said.
   The official said the administration's program to gain covert
assistance was dealt a setback after it was reported last month in
The New York Times. The Times reported the administration would seek
congressional backing for a covert program to supply rifles and
other weapons to the non-communist resistance.
   The administration had hoped to have more time to make its case,
the official said.
   Robert M. Kimmitt, undersecretary of state for political affairs,
has been visiting with members from the various committees that
would have to approve such aid this past week, ``but he's been
running into a brick wall,'' the official said.
   The official said there were not very many ``open minds'' on the
subject.
   In any case, the department intends to continue to make its case.
   ``We still have to make the effort,'' the official said.
   On Monday, Kimmit testified before a Senate Foreign Relations
subcommittee that the administration believes strengthening the
non-communist resistance will help achieve a peaceful political
solution and prevent the return of the Khmer Rouge.
   Kimmit did not mention the covert aid plan in his appearance, but
he said the administration would continue to make clear that
continued support for the non-communists would depend upon their
distancing themselves from the Khmer Rouge.
   Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., who is the author of a House bill to
authorize overt military aid, testified that U.S. aid should be
increased from the $7 million now planned to as much as $30 million.
   Solarz argued that the aid would strengthen the hand of the
non-communist resistance and help prevent another holocaust.
   In Geneva on Wednesday, two senior State Department officials met
with Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach to discuss the
refugee problem in Indochina, and the Cambodian situation was also
discussed.
   Robert Funseth, the senior deputy assistant secretary for refugee
affairs and deputy assistant secretary David Lambertson, ``stressed
that there must be a negotiated comprehensive settlement'' of the
conflict and that Sinahouk must play ``an essential role in any
transition government that is agreed upon,'' the State Department
said in a written statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
