<DOCNO> AP890615-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0316EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Smoking     06-15 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smoking,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Switching to Low-Nicotine Cigarettes Doesn't Stop Heart Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who smoke low-nicotine cigarettes face about
four times the usual risk of heart attacks, just like those who use
ordinary brands, a study released today concludes.
   ``For smokers who wish to reduce their risk, switching to
low-yield brands is a poor alternative to quitting,'' the
researchers wrote.
   Earlier studies have already reached similar conclusions in men.
   The latest work found that women who smoke cigarettes that are
low in nicotine and carbon monoxide face about four times the usual
risk of suffering first-time non-fatal heart attacks. This is the
same as the increased risk in those who use ordinary brands.
   The study was based on a comparison of 910 women with first heart
attacks and 2,375 other hospital patients. It was conducted by Dr.
Julie R. Palmer of Boston University Medical School's Sloan
Epidemiology Unit and published in today's New England Journal of
Medicine.
   The study notes that women are more likely than men to smoke
light cigarettes, and ads for these brands imply that that they are
safe _ or at least safer.
   ``The present large study offers substantial evidence against
this claim,'' they wrote.
   Nicotine and carbon monoxide increase the risk of heart attacks.
The researchers suggest that smokers who switch to low-yield brands
manage to take in just as much of these substances by taking more
puffs or inhaling more deeply.
   The low-yield cigarettes also contain less tar. Other studies
have shown that this makes them less likely to cause cancer,
although users' cancer risk is still considerably higher than
non-smokers'.
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Neal L. Benowitz of San
Francisco General Hospital said the movement toward the low-tar and
nicotine cigarettes has been worthwhile.
   But he added, ``The benefits for any person of smoking low-yield
rather than high-yield cigarettes are small, and the benefits of
quitting are great.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
