<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich     06-15 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Uses Ethics Case to Raise Money for State Republican Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Rep. Newt Gingrich used the ethics
case against ex-Speaker Jim Wright as a Republican fund-raising
tool, concluding requests for popular pressure on the House ethics
committee with appeals for contributions.
   Gingrich made the fund-raising appeals as general chairman of
GOPAC, a tax-paying organization that tries to elect Republicans to
state legislatures and sometimes aids Republicans running for local
office.
   Wright's ethics were made a fund-raising theme because ``Wright
was hot and Newt was so tied to that,'' Kay Riddle, GOPAC's
executive director, said Wednesday.
   The first of four letters was mailed just days after the Georgia
Republican filed his formal complaint on May 26, 1988, and the last
was two weeks ago _ dated a day after Wright announced he would
resign as speaker rather than fight ethics committee charges of 69
rules violations.
   The last letter declared Wright was ``not the only corrupt
Democrat.''
   The first three Gingrich letters raised just short of $50,000,
GOPAC said, but no totals were available from the fourth appeal _
issued two weeks ago and sent to 45,000 recipients, more than twice
the total of previous mailings.
   GOPAC said it raised $1.9 million overall last year, up $500,000
from 1987.
   In his initial letter June 1, 1988, Gingrich informed 18,910
people on GOPAC's active contributor list he had just filed a
complaint against Wright, and he asked people to send enclosed post
cards to ethics committee chairman Julian Dixon, D-Calif., demanding
an investigation.
   ``Second, will you make a contribution of $50 to GOPAC today?''
he said.
   By June 30, 1988, Gingrich was able to thank 1,500 respondents to
the earlier mailing for ``helping me force'' the ethics panel to
probe Wright.
   But Gingrich told the givers that a situation had arisen that
``could result in the investigation ... turning into a charade and a
whitewash.''
   A Democratic committee member, Vic Fazio of California, had
co-hosted a $500-a-plate luncheon in which the ``drawing card ...
was none other than Jim Wright,'' Gingrich wrote. ``In plain
political terms, Rep. Fazio now `owes' the speaker,'' Gingrich said,
and asked contributors to mail postcards urging Fazio to remove
himself from the investigation.
   ``And if you possibly can, would you make a special campaign
contribution to GOPAC today?'' Gingrich asked.
   Fazio, who did not bow out of the investigation, received 12
postcards from the mailing, according to spokeswoman Laura Nichols.
She said Wright was in Sacramento for a previously scheduled
appearance and added to his schedule the Democratic fund-raiser with
Fazio.
   On April 19, two days after the ethics committee publicly
released its report detailing 69 charges against Wright, Gingrich
thanked 19,822 on GOPAC's active donor list for their past help, but
said more money was needed.
   Some 45,000 prospective contributors received a letter from
Gingrich on June 1, just after Wright announced he would leave the
House.
   ``But he's not the only corrupt Democrat,'' Gingrich wrote.
   The letter also included a request for funds.
   None of the allegations Gingrich cited in his ethics complaint
were included in the ethics panel's statement of charges against
Wright.
   In April, Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., filed an ethics complaint
against Gingrich, alleging he may have violated a rule against
keeping gifts of $100 or more from anyone with a direct interest in
legislation. The allegation concerned a 22-investor partnership that
promoted a book of which Gingrich was coauthor.
   Gingrich has denied wrongdoing, and the ethics panel has made no
announcement about an investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
