<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MediaExpulsions-Past     06-15 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Media Expulsions-Past,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalist Expulsions Have Plenty of Precedent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL ALEXANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   China's expulsion of two journalists mirrors similar actions by
the Chinese government in 1987 as well as moves by other countries
in the past three years.
   Associated Press correspondent John Pomfret and Voice of America
bureau chief Alan Pessin on Wednesday were given three days to leave
China for their coverage in the wake of the June 3-4 government
crackdown on student protests in Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   The Chinese government has said nearly 300 died, mostly soldiers.
But Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence have said the toll
could be as high as 3,000, most of them civilians.
   A reporter for Britain's Independent Television News was deported
from Shanghai last week for covering demonstrations while on a
tourist visa.
   And the VOA came under criticism for its broadcasts on
pro-democracy student demonstrations in December 1986 and January
1987 that reportedly led to the ouster of Communist Party chief Hu
Yaobang.
   Beijing claimed the VOA was seeking to ``add fuel to the fire and
create chaos in China.'' In August, China refused to grant
accreditation to VOA reporter Max Ruston.
   Two reporters, American Lawrence MacDonald of the French news
agency Agence France-Presse and Shuitsu Henmi of Japan's Kyodo News
Service, were deported from China in early 1987 in connection with
their reporting.
   In October 1987, 14 foreign reporters from the United States,
Britain, Australia, West Germany and Italy were expelled while
covering pro-independence demonstrations in the Tibetan capital,
Lhasa.
   The government claimed they failed to obtain the necessary
permission to work there. China has controlled Tibet since its
troops moved into the remote Himalayan region in 1950.
   Beijing deported correspondent John Burns of The New York Times
in July 1986 after six days of questioning on suspicion of espionage
for a motorcycle trip he took through a restricted area of central
China.
   Some countries control the news by barring journalists entirely,
and China is far from the only one to deport reporters it considers
undesirable. Among the expulsions of journalists over the last three
years:
   _ In April 1988, NBC correspondent Rick Davis was ordered to
leave Jordan for reporting it has a ``tightly controlled and at
times even repressive society.'' The action came four days after
neighboring Israel suspended the press credentials of NBC
correspondent Martin Fletcher and reporter Glenn Frankel of The
Washington Post, claiming they violated censorship rules.
   _ Three journalists were among 11 Britons ordered out of the
Soviet Union last month on spying allegations in response to
Britain's expulsion of 11 Soviets also accused of espionage.
   _ In September 1986, the Soviets expelled U.S. News and World
Report correspondent Nicholas Daniloff after he had been arrested by
the KGB and accused of spying. Washington alleged he was seized in
retaliation for the FBI's arrest on spying charges of Gennadi
Zakharov, a Soviet working at the United Nations. Daniloff was
released one day before Zakharov was given probation and told to
leave the United States.
   _ After the first of two coups hit the South Pacific island
nation of Fiji in May 1987, Australian Broadcast Corp. reporter
Travor Watson was expelled. More than 20 other foreign reporters
were detained for several hours for their reports of the ethnic
unrest.
   _ In February 1987, reporter Gerald Seib of The Wall Street
Journal was expelled from Iran after being arrested on espionage
charges. He had been among a group of foreign reporters invited into
the country to file reports on ``Iranian victories'' in the war
against Iraq.
   _ Malaysia banned the Asian edition of The Wall Street Journal in
September 1986 and expelled two of its reporters _ Americans John
Berthelsen and Raphael Pura _ for the newspaper's reporting on a
government-owned bank that officials claimed could erode public
confidence in the government.
   _ Also in September 1986, Havana-based Robert Powell of Reuters
and Noel Lorthiosis of Agence France-Presse were expelled from Cuba
for violating the ``most elemental norms of professional ethics and
respect for the dignity of Cuba.'' The action apparently was because
of stories the reporters wrote based on interviews with an official
of an independent human rights group in Cuba.
   _ In July 1986, Washington Times reporter Glenn Garvin and
free-lance photographer Sue Mullin were expelled from Nicaragua,
which claimed they had CIA links.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0352EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GephardtProfile     06-15 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gephardt Profile,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gephardt: A Rising Political Star Since Early Days in St. Louis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-House Leadership Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until last year's failed presidential bid,
Richard Gephardt had not lost an election _ and even then he was
able to retain his House seat.
   Now he's the Democrats' majority leader, elected to the No. 2
leadership post Wednesday as a ``white knight'' for a party seeking
to leave behind a full year of controversy over ethics allegations.
   ``This man always lands on his feet,'' said Rep. Mike Synar,
D-Okla., a friend and supporter. ``A lot of politicians don't wear
well. He wears better with every meeting.''
   From the time he cut his political teeth in the backroom ward
meetings of St. Louis politics, Gephardt has carried the reputation
as a rising political star.
   Now in his 12th year in Congress, Gephardt suddenly is second
only to Speaker Thomas S. Foley in the House.
   His presidential campaign, despite its lack of success, clearly
helped.
   ``He has weathered the scrutiny and investigation of the
presidential campaign and comes to this with very excellent
credentials in terms of honesty and integrity,'' said Rep. Richard
Durbin, D-Ill.
   ``We are anxious to put this whole firestorm of ethics
controversy to rest and we believe that Dick Gephardt as majority
leader will not raise any of those questions.''
   Colleagues say the job of majority leader fits Gephardt like a
hand-tailored suit. They praise his ability to forge legislative
compromises and to position himself at the leading edge of national
issues such as tax reform and trade.
   ``He is generationally attractive, popular and an issues man,''
says Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan. ``Dick knows the House and cares
about issues, and I think that's what a majority leader has to do.''
   Says Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., who for years rode to Capitol Hill
each morning with Gephardt:
   ``He can disagree and not be disagreeable.''
   Republicans aren't so sure.
   ``Gephardt is pretty well liked on the Republican side of the
aisle, but he is certainly more of a hardball player than Tom Foley
is,'' says Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla., referring to the newly
elected House speaker.
   Edwards complains of Gephardt's attacks on Republicans during the
presidential campaign and his push in the House for a retaliatory
trade policy.
   ``He tends to be a polarizer rather than a conciliator between
the parties,'' says Edwards.
   During the presidential campaign, Gephardt also drew sharp
criticism from other Democratic candidates who questioned his
convictions and switches on social and defense issues.
   In his early House years, Gephardt had sponsored anti-abortion
constitutional amendments and supported legislation to ban busing of
school children to achieve desegreation. He no longer supports
either, saying the changes were a natural evolution of his views. He
continues to oppose abortion, but considers an amendment impractical.
   Indeed, Gephardt has advocated a practical rather than
ideological approach to legislating.
   ``I believe an idea is very important but it doesn't mean
anything unless you can make it happen and bring it into reality,''
he says. ``In order to do that, sometimes you have to be willing to
change where you started.''
   Gephardt won election to the House in 1976 after serving as a St.
Louis alderman. He seemed to move on the fast track almost from the
day he arrived on Capitol Hill.
   Taken under the wing of then-Rep. Richard Bolling of Missouri,
Gephardt won a seat as a freshman on the tax-writing Ways and Means
Committee.
   He got there through a formula he has repeated throughout his
career: Eagerly volunteering for assignments, winning the respect of
his elders through hard work and eventually moving into the inner
circle and replacing the old guard.
   In 1981, Gephardt was tapped as the prime-time TV spokesman for a
Democratic alternative to President Reagan's tax cut plan. Starting
in 1985, Gephardt served as chairman of the House Democratic Caucus.
He retained the the No. 4 ranking leadership post through the end of
1988.
   ``I really tried to be a caucus chairman that brought all the
different parts of the party together, all of the different regions,
and that's the kind of leader I'll try to be,'' says Gephardt.
   ``We only have strength here if we're actually able to weld
together a consensus on some very difficult issues nd that means
you've got to have input from every corner and part of the party.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, chairman of the Budget Committee, says one of
Gephardt's finest accomplishments came in 1985 in negotiating a
compromise on the Gramm-Rudman deficit-cutting measure. It was
Gephardt, Panetta says, who helped Democrats fashion a way to soften
the blow of large cuts in social spending.
   Says Synar, ```He listens well. He is very cautious and doesn't
move in big strokes. And he tests little steps to see if everybody
is still on board. But I think the key to it is listening.''
   He says he was seriously considering another presidential run in
1992 but altered course when ethics controversies forced the
resignation of Speaker Jim Wright of Texas and Majority Whip Tony
Coelho of California.
   Suddenly, Gephardt became an obvious choice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
