<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Medicare     06-15 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislation Aims at Curbing Physician Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overhaul of the Medicare system aimed at
curbing the cost of providing health care to the elderly by putting
an unprecedented ceiling on physician reimbursements has cleared a
House subcommittee.
   The proposal also would establish a national, uniform fee
structure for physicians in the $90 billion program and protect its
33 million beneficiaries by limiting the amount doctors can charge
beyond the Medicare-approved fees.
   The physician payment plan is being considered as part of the
fiscal 1990 Medicare budget, though it would not contribute to
savings until future years.
   ``This is a broad new program and it will take three to five
years to see it fully implemented,'' said Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif.,
chairman of the House Ways and Means subcommittee on health, which
approved the bill by an 8-3 vote Wednesday.
   The action is being proposed in response to an alarming rate of
growth in Medicare payments to doctors.
   Last year, Medicare outlays to physicians totaled $24.5 billion.
This figure has been growing at more than 15 percent annually for
much of the decade, more than double the rate of inflation. Total
Medicare spending on doctors and hospitals is expected to be up
about 13 percent this year.
   The plan is being watched carefully for possible application by
private insurance companies, which are also trying to find a way to
cut health-care costs.
   Under the package, Congress would set an ``expenditure target''
beginning in fiscal 1991 that would limit payments for physician
services for Medicare beneficiaries based on total nationwide
spending the previous year. Adjustments would be made for inflation
and increases in the number of beneficiaries.
   If the target is exceeded one year, the Congress could order
cutbacks the next year. The initial target probably would be in the
range of 10 percent to 12 percent, Stark said.
   Limiting increases in physician fees paid by Medicare has not
controlled spending in the program because doctors have responded by
performing more services, according to subcommittee staff and health
officials.
   ``There's no way under the present system to control volume'' of
physician services, Stark said.
   The American Medical Association strongly opposes spending
targets as a form of health-care rationing. The group says the
government should instead spend money to evaluate procedures being
performed by physicians and develop practice guidelines they should
follow.
   The AMA, however, supports the proposed redistribution of
payments among physicians, though many within its ranks whose fees
now are reimbursed at a higher rate than other medical services
object to the plan.
   Payments to physicians would continue to increase overall, but
fees for primary care doctors _ including family practitioners and
internists _ would go up more. Fees reimbursed for medical
specialties like surgeons and ophthalmologists would go up less.
   The proposal, advanced by the Physician Payment Review Commission
set up by Congress to advise on Medicare spending for doctors, would
make the current reimbursement system more fair, but more
importantly for consumers the changes would encourage family
practice and internal physicians to continue taking Medicare
patients, said Lauren LeRoy, an official at the commission.
   The Bush administration has indicated its support for the
package, and the Senate Finance Committee has been looking at
similar reforms. The Medicare program has not seen any major changes
in the way physicians are reimbursed since it was enacted in 1965.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
