<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DeathPenalty     06-15 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Penalty,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Death Penalty Decision ``Like A Soap Opera''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drive to restore the death penalty in New
York may come down to a lawmaker's battle with cancer that caused
him to ``meditate on life.''
   This week, veteran state Sen. James Donovan, a Republican who
consistently has supported the death penalty, told his hometown
newspaper that he was ``personally opposed'' to capital punishment.
   ``I would like to see the state stop financing the killing of the
unborn as well as those convicted of capital crimes,'' Donovan, the
leader for more than a decade of the unsuccessful battle to block
New York's Medicaid financing of abortions, told the Utica
Observer-Dispatch.
   Noting that he once got to sit in New York's electric chair,
unused since 1963, the senator said it was ``barbaric, inhumane and
almost uncivilized.''
   What Donovan, 65, wouldn't tell the newspaper was how he might
vote on Gov. Mario Cuomo's latest veto of the death penalty
legislation.
   In the last four years, the Republican-controlled state Senate
has voted to override Cuomo's death penalty vetoes. But the the
Democratic-controlled Assembly has lacked the votes to override.
   This year, however, death penalty advocates in the 150-member
Assembly said they were within one vote of getting the 100 needed
for an override. And the political pressure began to build on a few
Democrats from New York City.
   Then, things began to unravel in the Senate.
   First, state Sen. Israel Ruiz, a death penalty supporter, was
convicted in February of a federal felony for lying on a bank loan
application and was thrown out of the Senate. He was considered the
42nd vote in a Senate where only 41 votes are needed for a veto
override.
   Then last month, Martin Markowitz, another death penalty
supporter in the Senate, said he wouldn't rule out a change of heart.
   ``The day we're dead is the day our positions are written in
stone,'' said Markowitz.
   Even so, Markowitz said he still expected to vote in favor of the
override.
   Now come Donovan's statements. He underwent surgery in early May
for colon cancer. His subsequent absence from the Senate has forced
a delay for weeks of an override attempt. He said he'll be back at
work Monday.
   Thirty-seven states have enacted capital punishment laws since a
1976 U.S. Supreme Court ruling allowing executions to resume.
   Dale Volker, the chief Senate sponsor of the death penalty bill,
now says he's unsure when he'll schedule the override attempt.
   ``It's like a soap opera,'' said Volker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0041 </DOCNO>
