<HEAD>Northeast Democrats Offer Coastal Protection Package</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic leaders on coastal environment
issues have introduced a legislative package to curb ocean pollution
and create a $200 million fund financed in part by polluters.
   ``The oceans are nature's greatest gift to humankind, but they
are not inexhaustible. If we treat them as a dump, they will, in
time, become a dump,'' said Rep. Gerry E. Studds, a Cape Cod
Democrat and chairman of the House subcommittee on fisheries and the
environment.
   Lawmakers said Wednesday drifting medical waste that closed East
Coast beaches last summer, coupled with the Exxon oil tanker spill
earlier this year off the Alaskan coast, has made the time ripe for
congressional action.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, Sen. John F.
Kerry, D-Mass., Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and Studds introduced
four separate measures Wednesday designed to fight coastal
pollution. Sen. John H. Chafee of Rhode Island, the top Republican
on the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee, joined the
Democrats at a news conference introducing the bills.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Congress Starts Churning Out Coins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Capitol plaza was temporarily transformed
into a mint as white-gloved legislators manned giant presses to
strike gold and silver coins commemorating the 200th anniversary of
the Congress.
   The festive ``first strike'' ceremony in a flag-bedecked tent on
Wednesday marked the first time since 1792 that U.S. coins have been
struck outside of an official mint.
   Donna Pope, director of the Mint, said the plaza was a fitting
site for a coin foundry, since the Capitol itself has proved to be a
``great white foundry'' in which Congress turned the dream of
democracy into reality.
</TEXT>
