<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-15 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0653</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A change that put teeth into the security
at the federal courthouse left one judge almost toothless.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Wiseman Jr. activated a metal
detector three times last week on his way to his courtroom and
chambers on the eighth floor of the courthouse.
   ``First I took everything from my pockets, and that didn't work.
Then I took my teeth out, and that didn't work,'' Wiseman said,
referring to his dental bridge. ``Finally, after taking my shoes
off, I made it through.''
   The judge said a metal arch support in his shoe apparently
triggered the device. He said the incident didn't bother him and
emphasized the importance of the tighter security.
   Indeed, Wiseman and other judges last month ordered that everyone
entering the sixth, seventh and eighth floors of the courthouse pass
through the metal detector. The order even applies to security and
law enforcement officers, who must leave any weapons at a security
post before entering the area.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LORIS, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There were a few bugs in the preliminaries,
but officials at a local library deemed their first bug races a
success.
   About 35 preschoolers in the Loris Branch Library's summer
reading program were told to bring their own insects to compete in
the races Wednesday.
   Organizers had planned to put race numbers on the backs of the
bugs, but that idea didn't work out, what with the contestants
squirming so much.
   ``I'm not too favorable to spiders,'' race organizer and
children's service director Janet Barwick said as she tried to stick
a number on a tiny black spider brought in a baby food jar by a
small girl.
   ``Holding bugs is not my cup of tea,'' said librarian Frances
Prince, struggling to label a cricket while bugs hopped merrily
along the library checkout counter.
   Pandemonium continued when the youngsters moved outside, where
racing circles were drawn on the parking lot.
   ``Oh, sick,'' piped up one youngster when he saw that someone had
accidentally stepped on his cricket and smashed the creature flat.
   The insects that crossed a finish line first won ribbons for
their owners.
   ``I don't know,'' said Scott Sarvis, 4, when asked if he was
happy that his cricket won a blue ribbon. ``I thought I would get a
toy.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKMULGEE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks in this Plains town say they're
nuttier than people in Georgia. And to prove the point, they plan to
bake the world's largest pecan pie.
   Rusty Milroy, co-chairman of the sixth annual Okmulgee Pecan
Festival today through Saturday, says the 40-foot diameter, 16{-ton
confection will eclipse a mark set last fall by Moultrie, Ga.
   Steel beams will support the huge pie pan north of the Council
House Square in downtown Okmulgee. Engineers were called in to make
sure the pie wouldn't crack the street.
   The gargantuan creation dwarfs Okmulgee's first giant-sized
effort, a 12-foot diameter, 3,200-pound pie in June 1986. That was
enough to gain entry in the Guinness Book of Records, but not for
long. Later that year, bakers in Albany, Ga., stirred up a pie that
weighed 600 pounds more.
   In June 1987, Okmulgee's pie pan was increased to 20.7 feet in
diameter and the pie weighed 6,300 pounds. Georgia bakers moved to
Moultrie and put together a 22-foot pie.
   Okmulgee's 24-foot, four-inch pie baked last June fell to a
Georgia pie that was 30 feet across.
   ``It is friendly competition and we are determined not to be
outdone,'' Milroy said.
   Bakers will use two new cement trucks, steam-cleaned for the
occasion, to mix ingredients for the pie before pouring it Friday
evening. The pie is expected to serve up to 22,000 people after
cooks finish the 10-hour baking process Saturday.
</TEXT>
