<FIRST>r a PM-SubmarineAccident     06-15 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Submarine Accident,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Submarine Hits Submerged Tow Cable, Sinks Tugboat, Crewman Missing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear attack submarine used in filming
``The Hunt for Red October'' accidentally snagged a tugboat, sunk it
and left one crewman missing.
   The search for the night watchman aboard the tugboat Barcona was
suspended and no rescue effort was planned today after the sinking
10 miles from shore.
   The submarine, a San Diego-based vessel with a crew of 140,
wasn't damaged and it surfaced after the accident to assist in the
search for the missing sailor, the Navy said.
   Brian Bellanger, who was keeping watch at the time of the
accident early Wednesday, was missing Wednesday night at the end of
a search by four U.S. Coast Guard vessels, two helicopters and three
Navy craft, said Coast Guard Lt. Rick Button.
   There was no immediate word on how the accident occurred and
officials said both the tug and the sub apparently were in the
correct sea lanes.
   Dan Rodriguez and Mike Lynk escaped the tug and were rescued
unhurt after the 6,900-ton USS Houston snagged the Barcona's tow
line, said Coast Guard Petty Officer 2nd Class Elizabeth Neely.
   The two scrambled onto one of two empty barges being towed by the
Barcona, owned by Long Beach-based Connelly-Pacific Marine.
   Bellanger's brother, Glenn, said: ``The water just caved in the
boat, (which) just went straight down. Mike had the wires for the
microphone, the radio, all wrapped around his neck. He said he
didn't think Brian was going to make it.
   ``We're all hoping right now that he did, but there's 450 fathoms
of water out there and that's, that's pretty deep.''
   The sub was used this week in the Paramount film production ``The
Hunt for Red October,'' based on the best-selling novel about a
runaway Soviet sub by Tom Clancy. The film stars Sean Connery and
Sam Neill. No actors were on the submarine at the time of the 4:43
a.m. accident.
   A mock Soviet sub was tied near the Coast Guard headquarters on
Terminal Island where Rodriguez and Lynk were brought. The accident
was not related to the filming, said Navy Lt. Sonja Hedley.
   The missing sailor may have gone down with the 73-foot tug, which
sank southwest of Long Beach, officials said. Parsons said Rodriguez
and Lynk, the surviving crew members, were asleep when the submarine
struck the tow cable.
   ``The tug was pulled down very rapidly,'' said Cmdr. Don Parsons,
who was heading the Coast Guard investigation. ``Everything happened
so fast. It sank in less than a minute.
   ``The survivors didn't get out until the tug was already under
water. The last time anyone saw the missing man was when he was seen
going down to the engine room.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0433EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-15 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hot Dollar Prompts Stock Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen
again today, triggering stock selling that sent the Tokyo Stock
Exchange's key index to its largest one-day loss this year.
   The dollar closed at 151.30 yen, up 3.25 yen from Wednesday's
148.05-yen close. It was the highest since Aug. 14, 1987, when the
dollar closed at 152.40.
   The dollar now has gained 10.65 yen since June 5, including a
4.90-yen jump on Monday.
   It opened today at 150.30 yen, its low for the day, and hit
151.35 yen at one point.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 489.90 points, or 1.47
percent, this year's largest one-day loss, and closed at 32,913.09.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told reporters the dollar's
surge resulted mainly from speculative buying by Japanese investors.
He said it had nothing to do with fundamental elements in the U.S.
and Japanese economies.
   ``We must stop (the dollar's further rise) by using every means
available,'' Murayama said, expressing concern that the higher
dollar could bring inflationary pressure in Japan.
   ``We'll take resolute measures under the established system of
cooperation with other countries,'' he said.
   But there is no immediate need to call a meeting of finance
chiefs of the Group of Seven leading industrial countries before the
group's scheduled summit in Paris in mid-July, Murayama said.
   The Bank of Japan reportedly continued to sell dollars in efforts
to check the U.S. currency's rise, although the central bank does
not comment on its monetary activities.
   ``The BOJ intervention didn't work at all,'' said a Bank of Tokyo
analyst, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Everybody was just
buying as the dollar rose, trying to get on the bandwagon.''
   Traders said, however, there was some dollar-selling to take
profits.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa Bank said, ``No matter how often the
Japanese side says the dollar should stay lower, it has small
influence because the United States ... doesn't make any moves.
Japanese market players have taken this as an indication that the
United States is allowing the dollar's surge for the moment.''
   He said investors were aggressively buying dollars, anticipating
improved U.S. trade figures for April, due to be announced later
today in Washington.
   On the stock exchange, Daiwa Securities dealer Kenji Ishizuka
said share prices were lower across the board, mainly because of the
dollar's surge against the yen.
   ``In addition to the major discouragement due to the yen's
plunge, many Japanese investors avoided buying while awaiting
release of the U.S. trade report later tonight,'' he said.
   Ishizuka said a narrowing of the U.S. trade deficit would promote
a further rise by the dollar, which could further discourage stock
investment.
   Some investment trust companies intermittently bought cheaper
issues for profit-taking, but it could not stop the index's fall, he
said.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 650
million shares, up from 450 million the previous day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
