<FIRST>r a PM-ThompsonExecution     06-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thompson Execution,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Condemned Killer Wants Nothing to Halt His Execution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM GARDNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Condemned killer William Paul Thompson remained
adamant that he would rather die for killing a Reno transient than
spend any more time on death row.
   Thompson appeared nervous and wiped away tears during a 10-minute
hearing Wednesday before District Court Judge Deborah Agosti. The
judge questioned him extensively before ruling that Thompson
understood his options and rejected them intentionally.
   ``Do you voluntarily submit to the execution of the death penalty
... at 2 a.m. June 19?'' Agosti asked.
   ``Yes ma'am,'' Thompson replied.
   When the judge reminded him he could appeal at any time before
his execution by lethal injection, he replied, ``I won't, but thank
you.''
   Deputy Washoe County District Attorney Gary Hatlestad added that
other parties could intervene on his behalf, particularly the
American Civil Liberties Union. Thompson replied, ``I don't want no
part of the ACLU.''
   At the conclusion of the hearing, Thompson struggled with his
shackles to shake hands with Hatlestad and whisper, ``God bless
you.''
   ACLU representative Richard Siegel, who did not attend the
hearing, said it was unlikely his group would try to intervene in
the case. ``We probably cannot succeed without some cooperation at
some stage from the person,'' he said.
   Assistant U.S. Public Defender Pat Flanagan also said he had no
standing to intervene unless directed by the court or requested by
Thompson.
   Thompson, 52, has spent more than half of his life behind bars
and was convicted of killing Randy Waldron in 1984 by shooting him
four times in the head. He subsequently pleaded guilty to the
murders of two brothers in Placer County, Calif.
   His attorney, Dave McElhinney, said Thompson told him in a letter
late last month that ``one way or the other he was going to spend
the rest of his life in prison ... and he feels enough is enough.''
   Also next week, Sean Patrick Flanagan is scheduled to die June 23
for the Las Vegas killings of two men he thought were homosexuals.
Flanagan also has said he wants no more appeals of his sentence.
</TEXT>
