<FIRST>r a PM-BaseballCard     06-15 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baseball Card,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stolen Baseball Card Turns Out to Be a Fake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURG, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare baseball card stolen from a
14-year-old boy and estimated to be worth about $100,000 has turned
out to be a fake.
   The stolen card, originally thought to be a 1910 Honus Wagner
tobacco card, lacked the tobacco stamp that would have indicated it
was an original, said Detective Phil White of the Contra Costa
County Sheriff's Department.
   Rene Montoya, who still hasn't recovered the card, was shown a
replica on Tuesday and identified it as ``exactly the same card
stolen from him,'' White said.
   ``Up until yesterday we had no way of determining if the card was
authentic or a replica,'' said White. ``We didn't even know a
replica existed, not being specialists in that field. We had nothing
to compare it with.''
   The boy's grandfather gave him the card six years ago. Rene put
it in the family Bible for safekeeping after seeing a television
program that discussed the value of authentic cards and hoped it
would finance his college education.
   His family never had the card appraised but assumed it was one of
only 10 to 20 authentic Wagner cards that experts believe exist
today.
   On May 24, an acquaintance of Montoya asked the boy whether he
could photograph the card and then he grabbed it and fled.
   Wagner, who played shortstop for Pittsburgh, joined Babe Ruth and
Ty Cobb as one of the first players inducted into the Hall of Fame.
Wagner bought up many of the cards himself because he did not
approve of youngsters having to buy cigarettes to obtain his picture.
   White said the boy's family was unaware the card was a replica
when they reported it stolen.
   ``They're still upset the card was stolen from the boy but are
somewhat relieved they hadn't lost so much money,'' White said.
   Police are still seeking the thief, even though its value is $10
at most.
</TEXT>
