<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-15 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
after an overnight surge in Asia. Gold prices slipped.
   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar was bid sharply higher
on expectations of a narrowing of the U.S. trade deficit from
March's $8.9 billion.
   The U.S. Trade Department was scheduled to announce April's trade
figures later today.
   Dealers said banks scrambled to buy dollars early in the session
but that activity had calmed by late morning. No major movement was
expected until after the trade report.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen, closing up 3.25
yen at 151.30, its highest level since August 1987. The dollar now
has gained 10.65 yen since June 5.
   Later, it London, it was quoted at 151.15 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _2.0405 West German marks, up from 2.0290
   _1.7655 Swiss francs, up from 1.7525
   _6.9210 French francs, up from 6.8690
   _2.2973 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2805
   _1,475.75 Italian lire, up from 1,464.50
   _1.2015 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1993
   The dollar rose against the pound. It cost $1.5060 to buy one
pound, compared with $1.5143 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $360.15 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $361.75. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $360.40, from $361.25 late Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 83 cents to close at a bid of
$361.57.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.22 a troy ounce,
down from Wednesday's $5.23.
</TEXT>
