<HEAD>Man Arrested for Trying to Sell Soap as Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEESVILLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Johnson's first mistake was claiming
less than a nickel's worth of soap was $200 worth of cocaine, police
said. His second mistake was trying to sell it to an undercover
officer.
   Johnson, 37, of Leesville, allegedly tried to sell five soap
chips he said were cocaine to an undercover agent for $40 each, said
Sheriff Frankie Howard.
   The undercover officer said during the exchange Johnson leaned
inside his police car, which is unmarked but has a rack of police
radios.
   ``He asked me what I was looking for and I told him cocaine
rocks,'' the officer said.
   Johnson then produced the soap chips, the agent said.
   Johnson, who apparently realized the buyer was an undercover
officer when one of the radios broke the silence, tried to run, but
was caught by the officer.
   Johnson was being held Wednesday in the Vernon Parish Jail on
$5,500 bond. He was charged with distribution of a false controlled
substance.
