<FIRST>r i PM-China-ForeignPress     06-15 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Foreign Press,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Journalist in China: `Always Wondering Who is Watching Us'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY CHENAULT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign reporters covering the military crackdown
on dissent are finding their job increasingly more difficult. People
willing to talk are becoming more scarce and police and soldiers are
now to be feared.
   On American journalist said reporting under martial law
restrictions ``has us always wondering who is watching us.''
   A British reporter said reporters know the risks of going out
into the streets now, ``but the job we're doing is really too
important to worry about what might happen.''
   Chinese authorities expelled two American reporters on Wednesday,
and the Independent Television News in Britain said ITN reporter
Vernon Mann was under house arrest at his hotel in the city of
Chengdu.
   ``His passport and papers have been confiscated and he has been
ordered to stay in his hotel and `await punishment,''' said an ITN
spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The network said Mann was arrested while filming buildings and
buses gutted in rioting that broke out just after troops killed
hundreds of unarmed civilians in Beijing in running protesters out
of the city center.
   ITN said Mann was told to return to police headquarters Friday
morning.
   A press officer at the British Embassy in Beijing said its
officers were seeking help from the U.S. Consulate in Chengdu on
reports of Mann's detention.
   Chinese authorities on Wednesday gave John Pomfret of The
Associated Press and Alan Pessin of the U.S. government's Voice of
America three days to leave the country, saying they violated
martial law restrictions imposed on May 20.
   Both correspondents denied doing anything more than their jobs.
   Today, an organization representing 1,000 senior editors of daily
newspapers in the United States and Canada decried the expulsions,
saying they represented ``a serious blow to freedom of information
and the international reputation'' of China.
   ``We earnestly urge the Chinese government, in the interest of
press freedom and human rights, to lift all restrictions on foreign
and Chinese journalists,'' said the statement by the American
Society of Newspaper Editors.
   The martial law order bans foreign reporters from interviewing
student leaders, taking photos of troops or covering events around
Tiananmen Square, scene of the violent suppression on June 3-4.
Journalists generally have ignored the regulations.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said from Washington that
President Bush viewed the matter ``with great concern.''
   In New York, Louis D. Boccardi, AP president and general manager,
said, ``We deplore and have protested in the strongest terms to the
Chinese government this unwarranted assault on fair and factual
reporting.''
   Soldiers briefly detained two journalists with Agence
France-Presse on Wednesday, accusing them of taking photographs of
troops. Authorities confiscated the residence card of Denis Hiault,
the agency's bureau chief in Beijing, and seized film from
photographer Catherine Henriette.
   Television crews also have had film or equipment confiscated.
Some reporters have been stopped by police from talking to people on
the street or had notebooks taken. A British reporter working on a
tourist visa was ordered expelled from Shanghai.
   But the reporting continues.
   ``Our approach is still basically unchanged,'' said Vito
Maggiolo, managing editor of Beijing coverage for Cable News
Network. ``We're going out, doing what we have to do to tell a story
and show what's happening.''
   He said the martial law restrictions have caused some
limitations, particularly with filming in public.
   ``Every time you take out a camera in this town you wonder what
the Chinese authorities might do,'' Maggiolo said. ``We're wondering
who's around. All of this has us always wondering who is watching
us.''
   He said those concerns extend to the Chinese people questioned by
CNN reporters.
   ``We don't want to do anything to put the Chinese people in hot
water,'' Maggiolo said.
</TEXT>
