<DOCNO> AP890615-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0711EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Ireland     06-15 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Voters Decide Whether To Give Haughey Majority Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ireland held parliamentary elections today with
opposition leaders saying they would try to deny Charles Haughey a
fifth term as prime minister if his party does not win a majority of
seats.
   Analysts say Haughey, who has led the country four times with
minority governments, may win his majority this time.
   Even so, the standing of the the man who first became prime
minister in 1979 and his Fianna Fail party have slipped in opinion
polls since Haughey announced the new election.
   About 2.4 million people were eligible to vote and counting
begins Friday morning, with the first results to be announced that
afternoon.
   ``Lovely morning,'' Haughey said after casting his vote in north
Dublin. ``Everything's going great.''
   On the eve of the election, however, opposition leaders said they
would not vote for Haughey for another maximum five-year term as
prime minister if he fails to win a majority of the 165 seats in the
Dail, or parliament.
   Alan Dukes, leader of the Fine Gael party, and Def O'Malley,
leader of the Progressive Democratic Party, issued statements saying
they would not vote for Haughey should his party fall short of a
majority.
   They also indicated they they would not abstain to permit Haughey
to muster a plurality.
   In that case, Haughey shot back, voters have a choice between a
Fianna Fail government or no government at all.
   O'Malley called on voters to reject ``the obsession of Mr.
Haughey ... with absolute power.''
   Fianna Fail was preferred by 44 percent of those surveyed in the
final Irish Independent poll, published Wednesday. The Fine
Gael-Progressive Democratic coalition combined for 35 percent,
followed by the Labor Party with 12 percent, the Marxist Workers
Party with 5 percent and others with 4 percent.
   Haughey's party gained none of the undecided vote from a week
earlier, while Fine Gael was up 1 percent and the leftist Labor
Party was up 2 points.
   Fianna Fail has 80 seats in the Dail now and would need 83 to
control it. He might still be able to govern with fewer than 83, but
would need support from some other group or coalition of groups.
   Haughey had received support from Fine Gael for his major
economic policies, which reduced Ireland's budget deficit to less
than 5 percent of gross national product from a peak of 15 percent.
   The government also cut basic tax rates from 35 to 32 percent.
   Unemployment remains at 17.5 percent, however, and emigration has
increased since Haughey took office in 1987.
   The government also aroused deep antagonism in western Ireland by
introducing fishing licenses _ charging $20 a year for trout fishing.
   Fianna Fail strategists had believed it was a good time to call
an election, with inflation running at 3.5 percent a year and
interest rates at only 9 percent.
   Ireland's system allows voters to list their preferences in
descending order, and these are shuffled around in a complex
tallying system that makes opinion polls unreliable. Voters' second
choices will likely decide whether Haughey gets his majority.
   Ireland has not had a majority government since Jack Lynch's
Fianna Fail administration left office in 1973, and no government
has won consecutive terms since the 1960s.
   Though Haughey has served four terms, he was defeated between
each of them and has never won two consecutively.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
