<FIRST>r i PM-Poland     06-15 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>French President Offers Changing Poland Easier Credit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand of France has
offered to relax credit terms for Poland and push for rescheduling
part of this country's foreign debt to help it shore up its sagging
economy.
   Mitterrand made the offer during a dinner toast Wednesday night
on the first day of a three-day visit to Poland.
   He was to meet today with Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski,
then travel to Gdansk for talks with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   At the state dinner held by Polish leader Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski, Mitterrand told his audience that France wants to
provide ``concrete support for the process of reforms taking place.''
   He was referring to the Communist government's new dialogue with
Solidarity and the independent trade union's sweeping victory
earlier this month in the country's freest elections since World War
II.
   ``We wish for the success of the current experiment and back it
because it will help Europe in the East and the West,'' said
Mitterrand, who heads a Socialist government.
   Mitterrand said France would push for rescheduling Poland's $39
billion foreign debt.
   He also said France would offer Poland flexible short- and
medium-term credit for financing industrial projects, agriculture,
food processing, and tourism development.
   In a visit to Britain earlier this week, Jaruzelski was told that
that country would provide only limited economic aid to Poland.
Britain also agreed to press for rescheduling of Poland's debt.
</TEXT>
