<FIRST>r a PM-Live-InRape     06-15 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Live-In Rape,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Rape Example of Bad Consequences of `Trial Marriages'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA BEACH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge offered leniency to a man
convicted of beating and raping his live-in girlfriend, saying the
case illustrated the potential consequences of living together.
   Zackary Dwight Owens was convicted in April. A jury recommended
18 years in prison. Circuit Judge H. Calvin Spain on Wednesday gave
him 15 years.
   ``Trial marriages and live-in relationships can lead to bad
consequences,'' Spain said. ``And this is a prime example.''
   Owens will be eligible for parole in 2{ years, six months earlier
than if the judge had imposed the full sentence.
   The sentence reduction was unusual but within the judge's
authority, said Assistant Commonwealth's Attorney Kathleen M. Edge.
``The commonwealth obviously would have preferred the full jury
verdict,'' she said.
   Defense attorney G. Roger Schafer had argued that Owens was
provoked into beating his 30-year-old girlfriend when she told him
that she had slept with another man.
   ``They lived together for eight months with no prior violent
incidents,'' Schafer said. ``He had no history of violence and no
prior criminal record. Then one night he just lost control, but it
was provoked.''
   The woman testified Owens beat her, forced her into a bedroom and
sodomized and raped her. She said he held her captive two days,
raping her until she escaped from the condominium they shared.
   Owens, a car salesman, admitted beating the woman but said she
had agreed to have sex with him ``to make it up to me.''
</TEXT>
