<HEAD>Showers In East; Fair Skies in Central, Southwest U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 8-10 bgng `On Wednesday...', with 5 grafs to ADD
detail on storm around Washington; PICKS UP 11th graf pvs, `Cloudy skies
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Twin cold fronts moving through the East today churned up more
rain and thunderstorms, with Georgia and South Carolina getting the
most, while the central and southwestern United States had fair
skies.
   In Texas, showers and thunderstorms hit the lower Rio Grande
Valley. In Dallas, police evacuated parts of a neighborhood because
of flooding.
   ``Everything in the house was ruined. The walls are popping out,
the floors, the ceiling _ everything,'' said resident Betty Hicks.
   Two young brothers drowned Wednesday after being swept away in a
rain-swollen creek in Dallas, bringing to five the number of
fatalities from the flooding since Tuesday. At least one other man
was feared missing.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of the cold fronts,
scattering showers and thunderstorms from the central Gulf Coast to
the Ohio Valley.
   In the mid-Atlantic Coast region, a stationary front created more
rain and thunderstorms.
   The strongest thunderstorms bore down on northern Georgia early
today. A severe thunderstorm watch was in effect for northern
Georgia and northwestern South Carolina.
   On Wednesday, thunderstorms produced severe weather in Alabama,
Georgia, Louisiana, Maryland, Mississippi, Ohio, Virginia and the
nation's capital. At least seven tornadoes were reported, four in
Alabama.
   Around Washington, D.C., the storm disrupted afternoon rush-hour
traffic and cut off electricity to more than 170,000 customers, half
of whom were still without power at daybreak today. About 30 schools
in Washington and suburban Maryland closed because of power outages.
   ``This is the worst storm in terms of the number of customers
affected and damage to Pepco's electric distribution system in the
93-year history of the company,'' said Kevin Case, spokesman for
Potomac Electric Power Co.
   In Virginia, thunderstorms produced severe weather in the
evening. Winds downed power lines near Martinsville, and a traffic
accident that killed one person was blamed on the storm.
   In northwestern Ohio, a barn was destroyed and four other
buildings were damaged when a tornado touched down in a rural area
near Tiffin, officials said. No injuries were reported from
Wednesday night's storm.
   Cloudy skies with light rain and drizzle prevailed from the upper
Great Lakes to the northern Atlantic Coast. A cold front in the
northwestern United States brought showers and thunderstorms in the
northern Plateau and northern Rockies.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
East Coast to the Mississippi River, from Louisiana to south-central
Texas, the upper Ohio Valley, and Alabama and northern Georgia;
scattered showers in the Pacific Northwest; and scattered showers
and thunderstorms from eastern Washington and Oregon to the northern
Rockies.
   Predicted highs: 60s from New England across New York, the Great
Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley to eastern Kansas; 50s in
Michigan and Wisconsin; 60s in the Pacific Northwest and the
California coast; 90s in the south Atlantic coastal states, eastern
Montana, portions of Utah, along the Rio Grande in Texas and
California's interior valleys; and 100 to 115 in the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 36
degrees at Duluth, Minn., to 93 at Phoenix and Glendale, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 showery; Boston 58 drizzle; Buffalo 57 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 79 fair; Cincinnati 63 rain; Cleveland 63 foggy;
Detroit 61 foggy; Miami 82 fair; New York 60 drizzle; Philadelphia
65 foggy; Pittsburgh 64 rain; Portland, Maine, 56 cloudy; Washington
71 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 46 partly cloudy; Chicago 55 foggy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 63 fair; Denver 52 partly cloudy; Des Moines 54
cloudy; Indianapolis 63 cloudy; Kansas City 57 partly cloudy;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 44 fair; Nashville 67 rain; New Orleans 75
partly cloudy; St. Louis 63 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 65 fair; Anchorage 50 cloudy; Las Vegas 92
fair; Los Angeles 64 foggy; Phoenix 93 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City
70 fair; San Diego 62 foggy; San Francisco 60 partly cloudy; Seattle
58 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 cloudy; Toronto 57 drizzle.
