<FIRST>r a PM-BatmanArrested     06-15 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Batman Arrested,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Crime-Buster Cop Nabbed in Insurance Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years ago he was ``Batman,'' half of a
celebrated police undercover team responsible for hundreds of
arrests.
   On Wednesday, former Detective David Greenberg was charged in a
$350,000 insurance scam.
   Greenberg, 45, was arrested by postal inspectors at his home in
Bel Air Beach, Fla.
   As a detective, ``Batman'' Greenberg made hundreds of arrests in
the late 1960s and early '70s with his partner, Robert Hantz,
nicknamed ``Robin.'' Their exploits were recounted in the 1973 book
and 1974 movie ``The Super Cops.''
   Greenberg quit the Police Department in 1975 and was later
elected to the state Assembly. But in 1978, he was convicted on
federal mail fraud and obstruction charges. He served 10 months of a
two-year sentence.
   The charges filed this week accuse Greenberg; his brother and
business partner, Bruce Greenberg; and their lawyer, Samuel
Konigsberg, of changing documents as part of a scheme to cheat an
insurance company.
   The defendants, charged with mail fraud and insurance fraud, face
up to 10 years in prison and $500,000 in fines if convicted.
   According to court papers, after a 1986 burglary at one of
Greenberg's businesses, a video store in New York City, the men
altered documents to make it look as if the store was covered by a
$500,000 policy instead of a $350,000 one.
   According to the complaint, the Greenbergs also inflated the
losses from the burglary, claiming $350,000 in used videotaped
movies had been taken.
   Bruce Greenberg, 36 and Konigsberg, 34, were freed on $50,000
bail after arraignment in New York City. Prosecutors said David
Greenberg will be extradited to New York.
   In 1987, a 45-year-old retired police officer who was president
of another of David Greenberg's video companies was shot to death as
he left his office. The killing has not been solved.
</TEXT>
