<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Cameraman 2ndLd-Writethru a0512 06-15 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Cameraman, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0512,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Cameraman Shot in Head by Plastic Bullet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with ABC response to army allegations,
changes type of bullet to plastic sted rubber based on witness comment.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cameraman for ABC television was shot in the
head today with a plastic bullet when Israeli soldiers fired on
Palestinian demonstrators in the occupied West Bank.
   An army spokesman said the TV crew violated an army order putting
the area off limits to reporters. He said the army filed a complaint
with the Government Press Office and would likely file one with
police after investigating.
   The crew could then be subject to arrest, said the official, who
was not identified in keeping with army regulations.
   Bill Seamans, the ABC bureau chief in Israel, said: ``To the best
of our knowledge, we have followed all legal orders.''
   A Palestinian news agency said the cameraman, Shlomo Franco, was
filming a Palestinian demonstration in downtown Ramallah in which
protesters threw stones at soldiers. Troops opened fire, wounding
Franco and several Palestinians, the report said.
   Franco, an Israeli, was hospitalized at Hadassah Mount Scopus
Hospital in Jerusalem. A photographer who visited Franco saw three
fragments of a brownish-gray plastic bullet that had been removed by
doctors.
   Seamans said the bullet struck Franco above the left eye and
lodged between the skin and the skull, causing slight tissue damage.
``His condition is good,'' Seamans said.
   Franco, 42, has worked for ABC for more than 10 years.
   Seamans would not comment on an Israel radio report quoting
Franco as saying he was not shown any order barring reporters from
the area. The report also quoted ABC officials as saying troops
showed a closure order to another TV crew but that it was 10 days
old and no longer valid.
   The army official said the crew had arrived at the scene of a
skirmish between soldiers and about 50 Palestinian youths.
   ``The commanding officer at the scene presented the TV crew with
a warrant closing the areas. The crew left, went around the block
and returned on the side of the demonstrators,'' said the official.
   He said soldiers did not see the crew and opened fire with rubber
and plastic bullets. The cameraman was wounded slightly by a
fragment from a rubber bullet, the official said.
   ``They disregarded the closure order and covered the story from
the side of the people who were disturbing public order,'' said the
official.
</TEXT>
