<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Upset at Summons Served on Her Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imelda Marcos says it was outrageous that U.S.
marshals served a summons on her critically ill husband at the
hospital.
   The summons is based on the civil suit filed by the government in
connection with a criminal case brought against Ferdinand Marcos and
his wife last fall.
   The civil and criminal complaints accuse the Marcoses of looting
over $100 million from the Philippines and using it to buy real
estate and other assets in the United States.
   Deputy U.S. Marshal James Propotnick on Wednesday said marshals
served the summons on the former Philippine president on Monday by
leaving copies with an aide outside Marcos' room at St. Francis
Medical Center.
   Mrs. Marcos was served by posting the documents on the gate of
the Marcos home after the people there refused to accept the papers,
Propotnick said.
   ``This is outrageous. What are they trying to do to Ferdinand,
kill him?'' Mrs. Marcos said in a statement. ``This is a great
shame.''
   Marcos' attorney Richard Hibey called the serving of the summons
``barbaric.'' He said he expects to challenge the legality of
serving a summons on a man who is near death and unable to
understand what is going on.
