<FIRST>r i PM-EuropeanParliament     06-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-European Parliament,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Nations Vote for European Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People in Britain, Ireland, Denmark, the
Netherlands and Spain voted today in European Parliament elections
following campaigns dominated by national rather than European
issues.
   In the other European Economic Community members _ Belgium,
France, Greece, Italy, Luxembourg, Portugal and West Germany _
voting for the 518-member assembly takes place Sunday.
   Results in today's elections will not be announced until voting
has ended in the other EEC, or Common Market, countries Sunday
night. The parliament's limited powers include approving trade
agreements involving EEC members.
   Throughout the Common Market, 7,126 candidates are vying for
seats in the 518-member assembly representing 178 national parties.
   Opinion polls predicted the Socialists, with 166 seats, and the
Christian Democrats, with 112 seats, would strenghten their
positions in the elections. Green parties, which favor environmental
causes, also were expected to win more than the 20 seats they now
hold. These gains would be at the expense of conservatives and the
assembly's 16 extreme rightists.
   In Ireland _ as in Luxembourg and Greece on Sunday _ voting for
the European Parliament coincides with national elections.
   In these nations, the campaigns focused on national issues, such
as unemployment and immigration, rather than European issues, such
as the plan to remove the EEC's internal borders and create a single
market EEC by 1992.
   Yet that was also evident in nations where no national elections
are immediately in the offing.
   In the Netherlands, for example, the campaign was overshadowed by
issues facing Dutch voters in the Sept. 6 national elections. The
Amsterdam daily Trouw called voting for the 25 Dutch assembly seats
``a dull event.''
</TEXT>
