<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Earthquake     06-15 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Earthquake,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Strikes Central Asian Republic of Tadjikistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook northwestern
Tadjikistan today, but there were no reports of deaths or serious
damage, Tass said.
   The earthquake measured 5 on the 12-point Soviet scale, the
official news agency said. A quake of magnitude 5 is considered a
``fairly strong'' temblor capable of shaking furniture, breaking
windows and cracking plaster.
   The epicenter of the quake was located 150 miles north of the
city of Dushanbe, the capital of the mountainous republic that
borders China and Afghanistan. The quake struck at 8:13 a.m., the
news agency said.
   A strong earthquake measuring 7 on the Soviet scale destroyed a
village 30 miles southwest of Dushanbe in January, killing more than
270 people.
   On Dec. 7, an earthquake devastated much of northern Soviet
Armenia and killed about 25,000 people.
</TEXT>
