<FIRST>u i PM-India-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0481 06-15 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Says Troops Can't Leave Sri Lanka Yet</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To ADD comment from Sri Lanka, SUB 7th graf pvs, `The July...'
with 3 grafs; pickup 8th graf pvs, `Several Tamil...' TRIMS to tighten.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi says the
45,000 Indian troops in Sri Lanka will not withdraw immediately
despite a Sri Lankan request to pull out by July 31, newspapers
reported today.
   Gandhi told reporters Wednesday that a withdrawal depended upon
``full implementation of the July 1987 peace accord'' that sought,
with promises of limited autonomy, to end an insurgency by Sri
Lanka's ethnic Tamil minority.
   Last week, President Ranasinghe Premadasa of Sri Lanka sent an
envoy to New Delhi to request an Indian withdrawal by the end of
July.
   India has said in official statements that Premadasa's deadline
was impossible to meet, but Wednesday was the first time Gandhi made
a statement in public.
   ``We are joint guarantors to the agreement with Sri Lanka. Until
the agreement is implemented in full, we will have a responsibility
towards the security of Tamils in Sri Lanka,'' The Times of India
quoted Gandhi as saying in the southern city of Bangalore.
   ``We are willing to sit down and work out a process of
withdrawal,'' the prime minister added, according to the newspaper.
   Sri Lanka's Foreign Ministry said today that a mere request by
Sri Lanka for Indian troops to leave should be the only provision
for a pullout.
   ``It is regretted certain statements have been made both here and
abroad to support the continued presence of the Indian troops in Sri
Lanka,'' the ministry said in a communique. ``Such pronouncements
will only have the unfortunate effect of confirming the fears in the
minds of the people of Sri Lanka the Indian troops have come to this
country to remain and not to return.''
   The 1987 peace accord extended limited administrative powers to
the Tamil minority in the country's northeast in return for a
surrender of arms. The Tamils were not a party to the agreement,
however, and the largest Tamil guerrilla group has kept fighting.
   Several Tamil citizens' groups have asked India to remain until
provincial councils with Tamil representatives take office.
   In the past two years, up to 70,000 soldiers have been deployed
in Sri Lanka in an effort to try to end the Tamil insurrection and
to oversee the peace accord signed with Premadasa's predecessor,
Junius R. Jayewardene.
   More than 700 Indian troops have been killed and about 45,000
remain in the island nation off India's southern coast.
   Many ultra-nationalist members of the majority Sinhalese and
several government ministers resent the presence of the Indian
troops.
   Premadasa, who like Jayewardene is Sinhalese, took office in
January pledging to bring about an early Indian withdrawal.
   Tamil extremists started their separatist struggle in 1983. The
Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of the country's 16 million people,
claim discrimination by the Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the
population.
   More than 9,000 people have been killed in the Tamil insurrection
and at least 3,500 others have died in the Sinhalese backlash.
Ultra-nationalist Sinhalese say too many concessions are being given
to Tamils.
   India was drawn into the internal strife of its small neighbor
through its role as the regional power and the sympathies of its 60
million Tamils.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0076 </DOCNO>
