<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Nagy     06-15 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Nagy,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Prints Biography of Leader of Hungarian Revolt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state newspaper today broke years
of silence and published a historical account of the 1956 revolt in
Hungary. It said such a rebellion could be abused by ``enemies of
socialism.''
   The account included a biography of the leader of the failed
revolt, Imre Nagy, who is to be reburied in Budapest on Friday along
with four of his associates in a public ceremony. Their bodies were
thrown into unmarked graves after they were convicted of treason
during a show trial and executed.
   State-run media in Czechoslovakia, as in other Soviet bloc
countries, had been silent for many years about Nagy.
   The Hungarian Communist Party recently hailed Nagy as a ``symbol
of socialist reform and said the sentence was illegal.
   Soviet forces crushed Hungary's popular uprising in 1956 and
Czechoslovakia's reform movement of 1968. But unlike other East bloc
countries, such as Hungary and Poland, Czechoslovakia has not taken
the Soviet Union's lead and adopted social, political and economic
reform.
   ``It is natural that the present reform forces have found a
symbol in (Nagy) ... but we should not forget that his legacy as an
exponent of Hungarian revolutionary movement with emphasis on
martyrdom is a target of appropriation by enemies of socialism,''
the Slovak Communist Party daily Pravda.
   The newspaper characterized Nagy as ``contradictory,'' but said
``there is no doubt that everything he did, he did with the best of
intentions, especially in his effort to stop bloodshed.''
   The Hungarian Supreme Court is to review his case on July 6.
</TEXT>
