<SECOND>PM-Senate-Nominations,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Negroponte Confirmed as Ambassador After Delay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Negroponte, a former member of the
National Security Council staff, has won Senate confirmation as U.S.
ambassador to Mexico, surmounting questions about a possible role in
the Iran-Contra affair.
   The Senate confirmed the career diplomat by voice vote, with no
objections raised, Wednesday night.
   Committee action on Negroponte's nomination had been delayed by
the release of documents at the trial of former NSC aide Oliver L.
North. These documents appeared to raise questions about his
knowledge of North's activities in support of the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels.
   Negroponte testified during his confirmation hearings that he
knew nothing of North's covert activities in Honduras in 1985 in
support of the Contra forces based there.
   The Senate also approved the nominations of Bernard W. Aronson to
be assistant secretary of state for Latin American affairs and John
H. Kelly to be assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern and
South Asian affairs.
   The Senate took no action on the pending nomination of Michigan
businessman and Republican activist Peter Secchia to be ambassador
to Italy.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, has objected to Secchia's penchant in the past
for ``unseemly'' use of profane and crude language.
   Secchia has pledged not to use such language if confirmed as
ambassador.
