<FIRST>u i PM-Gorbachev-China     06-15 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-China,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Reforms in China Crucial to World Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
said today that Moscow regretted some aspects of the conflict in
China and that the failure of reforms there could pose dangers to
the world.
   Speaking at a news conference on the final day of his four-day
trip to West Germany, Gorbachev also praised some of the students
who took part in the pro-democracy movement that was recently
crushed by China's hard-line government.
   Gorbachev's comments were his most extensive yet on the crisis in
China and the government's violent suppression of the pro-democracy
movement.
   The movement gained strength during the week of May 15, when
Gorbachev began his historic visit to China, ending a three-decade
rift between the two communist powers. Up to 1 million people
rallied in the streets of Beijing demanding social reforms, almost
overshadowing Gorbachev's visit.
   At today's news conference, Gorbachev was asked whether he shared
the official Chinese view that the students were
counterrevolutionaries.
   The Soviet leader sidestepped a direct reply, recalling that he
had said during his visit to Beijing that negotiations were the
solution to resolving problems.
   ``I think all of us are very much concerned at what is happening
in China,'' he said. ``All of us want the process of deep reform not
to fail'' in such a large nation.
   ``That failure would be very dangerous for the entire process of
creating a healthy environment in the world,'' Gorbachev added.
   ``All of us want the people and the government of China to find a
way out which corresponds to the interests of the Chinese people and
common aspirations,'' Gorbachev said.
   He said this concern dictated the Soviets' ``balanced, serious
position'' on China, although this did not exclude that ``we regret
some aspects of what happened.''
   Gorbachev and the Soviets have been cautious in speaking about
the events in China, apparently anxious not to undo the results of
the Sino-Soviet summit that sealed the mending of relations after a
30-year rift.
   Gorbachev mentioned that he had received letters from
unidentified students in which they had spoken out in favor of
reform, bilateral cooperation and many other policies that he said
were broadly similar to those of the Chinese Communist Party.
   ``I cannot suspect these people of any evil intention,'' he added.
   But he said there ``could be elements'' in the protest movement
``that took advantage of the situation.'' Gorbachev did not
elaborate.
   The Chinese government, in an elaborate propaganda campaign in
state-run media, has portrayed protest leaders as thugs and
criminals and branded soldiers who occupied Beijing on June 3-4 as
heroes.
   Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources say the
military raid in Beijing killed 3,000 people, most of them citizens.
The Chinese government says 200 people died, half of them soldiers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
