<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0529,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds Arrested In Uzbekistan Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 6th, `He added...' to UPDATE with report
of arson attack, details of evacuations. Pickup 7th pvs, `Anikiev said...'
Subs 19th graf, `Ryzhkov said...' to conform. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have arrested hundreds of people in
Uzbekistan in an attempt to halt ethnic violence that has killed at
least 90 people in the southern republic, Soviet officials said.
   Lt. Gen. A. Anikiev, an Interior Ministry officer, said troops
were guarding intersections and government buildings and patrolling
streets in Fergana, the city hit hardest by the 10 days of rioting,
Pravda reported.
   Violence by the native Uzbeks has been directed against Meshki
Turks, an ethnic minority forcibly moved from Soviet Georgia to
Uzbekistan in 1944 by Soviet dictator Josef Stalin.
   The Communist Party newspaper said helicopters were patrolling
the tense city and a 10 p.m.-to-6 a.m. curfew that was imposed June
4 remains in effect.
   ``But the situation continues to be serious as an unknown hand
directs bandits to generate tension,'' Pravda quoted Anikiev as
saying.
   He added that the situation in Fergana, 1,500 miles southeast of
Moscow is ``completely under control,'' the newspaper said.
   The official news agency Tass later said police had received
repots of further disturbances today. It said a wagon with
children's clothing that had been collected for fleeing Turkish
refugees was burned in Fergana.
   Tass said more than 15,000 Turks had been evacuated by Wednesday.
Turks have been sent to refugee centers in Soviet Russia.
   Anikiev said prosecutors from throughout the country, including
KGB and Interior Ministry investigators, had converged on Fergana,
Kokand and the republic's capital, Tashkent, to investigate how the
unrest began.
   ``Several hundred people have been arrested on charges of
organizing pogroms, murder and violence,'' he said. ``Along with
ensuring public order, law enforcement personnel are stopping all
manner of provocative rumors and explaining the situation to people
to prevent panic.''
   Proceedings have begun in more than 60 criminal cases, the
newspaper said.
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzkhov, who led a Kremlin delegation to the
region this week, said on Wednesday that Communist Party and
government officials ``tarnished the party's prestige'' by giving
gasoline, transportation and vodka to attackers who killed Meshki
Turks.
   Ryzhkov made the disclosure at a meeting with party officials in
Andizhan, a regional center northeast of the Fergana Valley and the
heart of the violence.
   In a report on the session, the official news agency Tass said:
``The involvement of some party and government officials in pogroms
has become known.''
   Ryzhkov said murderers and attackers would be punished but that
communist officials involved bore a special responsiblity.
   Official newspapers say the Meshki minority is angry about the
slow response of troops when the violence broke out and their
failure to use weapons against marauders who attacked with
pitchforks, knives and hunting weapons.
   Anikiev said troops were not authorized to use weapons on the
first day of violence. Newspaper reports earlier this week suggested
that officials wanted to avoid a repeat of the clashes between
troops and pro-independence protesters in the Georgian capital,
Tblisi, on April 9, when 20 demonstrators died.
   Unlike demonstrators in Georgia, however, Soviet news reports
have indicated Uzbek rioters were armed.
   The Interior Ministry official also suggested that any delay in
deployment of troops was due to vague information and indecision on
the part of the republic's leadership.
   More than 12,000 troops had been sent to the region to contain
the violence. Soviet news reports have said that hundreds of homes
were burned in premeditated attacks on the Turkish minority.
   Ryzhkov said on Tuesday that a government commission will examine
the Meshki Turks' request to return to Georgia.
</TEXT>
