<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Slaying 1stLd-Writethru a0493 06-15 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Slaying, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0493,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Former Security Chief Feared Reporter Would Expose Drug
Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To CORRECT second reference to Caro Quintero sted Quintero,
Sub 6th graf pvs, `Quintero is...' Pickup 7th graf pvs, `Excelsior, also...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal security chief arrested in
the 1984 slaying of a crusading journalist had feared the reporter
would link him to Mexico's most notorious drug runners, news reports
say.
   Jose Antonio Zorrilla Perez, who was Mexico's equivalent of FBI
director, was arrested Tuesday and called the mastermind of the
murder of newspaper columnist Manuel Buendia.
   On Wednesday, opposition legislators demanded that former
President Miguel de la Madrid and Interior Secretary Fernando
Gutierrez Barrios testify before a parliamentary committee on their
``possible knowledge'' of details surrounding killing, said the
Excelsior News Service.
   The opposition's proposal was rejected by members of the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, the news agency said.
   The business daily El Financiero on Wednesday quoted testimony of
those interviewed in the investigation that led to Zorrilla's arrest
as indicating he feared Buendia would publicize his alleged links to
drug kingpin Rafael Caro Quintero.
   Caro Quintero is awaiting trial in the 1985 torture-murder of a
U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
   Excelsior, also quoting case testimony, said witnesses told
investigators Zorrilla was linked to Miguel Felix Gallardo and
Ernesto Fonseca Carrillo, both recently jailed for operating huge
drug smuggling operations.
   The testimony quoted by Excelsior also said Zorrilla had
illegally provided police credentials to 16 drug traffickers to help
them in their operations.
   ``I'm innocent. I need your help. I'm not guilty,'' Excelsior
quoted Zorrilla as saying as he was processed at the Northern
Penitentiary on Wednesday night.
   Zorrilla, 47, was scheduled to be arraigned today.
   He surrendered to authorities Tuesday night after a brief
shootout in a Mexico City neighborhood. No one was hurt.
   He was questioned for 18 hours after his arrest by the deputy
federal attorney general in charge of narcotics, Javier Coello Trejo.
   Zorrilla is accused of masterminding the May 30, 1984, shooting
death of Buendia in a Mexico City parking garage. Buendia was a
columnist for the daily Excelsior and author of hard-hitting books
on corruption and illegal sales of drugs and weapons.
   Authorities refused to identify three other suspects in the
killing, saying that could hamper their investigation.
   Mexico City Attorney General Ignacio Morales Lechuga on Sunday
night announced an arrest warrant for Zorrilla, saying the former
security director had ordered Buendia's death.
   The government has come under intense pressure to solve the
murder of Buendia, one of 25 journalists slain since 1982, and there
have been accusations that high-ranking officials were involved in a
cover-up.
   Zorrilla headed the Federal Security Department from 1981 to
mid-1984. The department was dismantled in 1985 because of
corruption.
   He previously was a congressman and private secretary to
Gutierrez Barrios, now the nation's top law enforcement official.
   Opposition legislators had asked Gutierrez Barrios and de la
Madrid, whose six-year term as president ended in December, to
testify before a parliamentary committee on the ``possible
knowledge'' they had of Zorrilla's involvement in Buendia's death,
Excelsior said.
   The governing party rejected the proposal. ``It is totally
frivolous, without foundation and justification,'' Excelsior quoted
PRI Deputy Dionisio Perez Jacomo as saying.
   Gutierrez Barrios has not made any public statements on
Zorrilla's arrest.
   In the Pacific coast state of Sinaloa on Wednesday, officials
announced the arrest of a suspect in the February 1988 killing of
another journalist, Manuel Burgueno Orduno.
   The government news agency Notimex quoted the suspect as saying
he killed Burgueno because of the reporter's written attacks against
the suspect's brother, the former Sinaloa state judicial police
commander.
   Police believe the former police commander, who remains at large,
ordered the slaying.
   The agency quoted state Attorney General Manuel Lazcano Ochoa as
saying the suspect, Rigoberto Rodriguez Banuelos, confessed to being
one of four people involved in the killing.
   The news agency said Rodriguez was arrested in Agua Prieta,
Sonora. It did not say when he was arrested.
</TEXT>
