<HEAD>Former Bush Aide Faces Further Questions on Iran-Contra Involvement</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Ledes with 14 grafs with Cranston stonewalling charge, Gregg
testimony. pickup graf 8 pvs, bgng, ``After talking....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alan Cranston today said the Bush
administration is refusing to respond to the Senate's request for
documents relating to the role of ambassadorial nominee Donald Gregg
in the Iran-Contra affair.
   ``We've been stonewalled by the administration,'' Cranston,
D-Calif., said as a Senate Foreign Relations Committee confirmation
hearing resumed into Gregg's nomination to be ambassador to South
Korea.
   Cranston said the National Security Agency ``has rejected our
legitimate inquiries out of hand.'' The CIA proposed a document
review arrangement requiring the presence of four Republican and
Democratic senators, prompting Cranston to call the restrictions so
severe ``as to be laughable.'' Cranston also said the Pentagon had
given unsatisfactory responses and the State Department had been
``utterly nonresponsive.''
   ``They answered our letter after their own self-imposed deadline
and failed to produce specific documents we requested _ and which we
know exist,'' said Cranston.
   Cranston said the Senate committee ``has been stonewalled by
Oliver North, too.'' The former White House aide oversaw the secret
Contra resupply operation from 1984 to 1986.
   Cranston said North hasn't complied with a committee subpoena for
uncensored versions of his notebooks. The uncensored notebooks
contain ``repeated January 1985 references to Felix Rodriguez which
suggest North's involvement in Rodriguez briefings of the Vice
President,'' said Cranston.
   Rodriguez is a longtime friend of Gregg who was sent to El
Salvador with Gregg's help in 1984. Gregg contends he didn't find
out about North's secret resupply operation until August 1986 and
didn't learn the extent of North's involvement and didn't tell his
boss, then-vice president George Bush, until four months later. At
the time, Gregg was Bush's national security adviser.
   Cranston, chairman of the foreign relations subcommittee on East
Asian and Pacific Affairs, promised a committee vote on the Gregg
nomination next Tuesday. Cranston has led the opposition to Gregg's
appointment.
   Democrats on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee are trying to
find out what Gregg knew about North's secret Contra supply network.
   The committee has been zeroing in on Gregg's ties to Rodriguez
and Gregg's activities after a Contra supply plane was shot down
over Nicaragua in October 1986. That is when the operation started
to come unraveled.
   Gregg insisted in testimony today that he first heard details of
the resupply operation in August 1986 from Rodriguez, but ``did not
know the extent of North's involvement'' until four months later.
   Gregg says he didn't inform Bush about the network until December
1986 after the Iran-Contra scandal emerged.
   If he had known in August 1986 about the network ``I would have
informed the vice president'' and ``I would have taken steps to stop
the operation,'' Gregg testified. The network operated during a
congressional ban on military aid to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   At a May hearing, Gregg said Bush first found out that Gregg had
information on North's operation and Rodriguez' involvement in it
through a newspaper interview given by Gregg in December 1986.
   After talking with Gregg late in 1984, Rodriguez was sent to El
Salvador to help that country in the battle against leftist
guerrillas.
   North recruited Rodriguez to work in the Contra rebel resupply
operation. The Contras, backed by the United States since 1981, have
been fighting to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government in
Nicaragua.
   At his recently completed trial, North testified that he thought
he spoke to Gregg about the resupply operation, but North gave no
specifics.
</TEXT>
