<FIRST>r i PM-Ghana 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ghana, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0536,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ghana Expels Mormons, Jehovah's Witnesses</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th, `Accra Radio...' to UPDATE with reaction
from Mormons. Pickup 8th pvs, `The Mormon...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ACCRA, Ghana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned the Mormon Church
and Jehovah's Witnesses and given their missionaries one week to
leave Ghana.
   The government of Flight Lt. Jerry Rawlings, in a statement
Wednesday carried on state-run Accra radio, accused the two groups
of disturbing public order and threatening Ghana's sovereignty.
   Accra Radio said two small, domestic sects, Nyame Sunkwa and
Jesus Christ of Dzorwulu, also were banned.
   Of the U.S.-based groups, the statement said:
   ``Despite repeated warnings, the two sects have continued to
conduct themselves in a manner which not only undermines the
sovereignty of Ghana but is also not conducive to public order.'' It
gave no details.
   It said the government had canceled residence permits for foreign
missionaries and other workers with the Mormon Church and the
Jehovah's Witnesses. Their churches were ordered closed.
   Accra Radio did not say how many people will be expelled.
   Jerry Cahill, a spokesman for the Mormon Church in Salt Lake
City, said the church would not comment until it had more details on
the expulsion order.
   The Mormon Church, known formally as Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints, is based in Salt Lake City. Mormons believe that
Jesus Christ established one church on earth, that it was removed
upon his death, and then restored in revelations to Joseph Smith in
the 1820s.
   The Jehovah's Witnesses have headquarters in Brooklyn, N.Y..
Their faithful believe that they adhere to the oldest religion on
earth, the worship of Almighty God revealed in the Bible as Jehova.
They refuse to bear arms, salute the flag, or participate in secular
government. They also refuse blood transfusions as being against the
Bible.
   The broadcast said a law requiring all denominations to register
with the Ministry of Interior in this West African nation had been
signed.
   Of Ghana's population of 13 million, 43 percent is Christian. The
other major group, 32 percent, adheres to traditional local beliefs.
   It was not immediately known how many people belong to the banned
groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
