<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-ReversePaternity     06-15 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Reverse Paternity,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Gives Legal Help to Men Trying to Prove Fatherhood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deeply divided Supreme Court today gave some
legal help to any man trying to prove he fathered the child of a
woman married to someone else.
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices said states must give such men a
``fair opportunity'' to prove paternity and seek visitation rights.
   But the court upheld California rulings that denied visitation
rights to a man, identified only as Michael H., who says he is the
father of a 7-year-old girl, Victoria, born to a woman identified as
Carol D. at a time when Carol D. was married to another man.
   At issue was the constitutionality of a California law, similar
to laws in many other states, that creates a presumption of
paternity in favor of a woman's husband if a child is conceived and
born during their marriage.
   Four high court members said men in similar circumstances to
Michael H. have no constitutional right to a hearing where
visitation rights could be won.
   Four justices voted to strike down the California law, saying it
infringed on Michael H.'s constitutionally protected ``liberty.''
   The key 9th vote was cast by Justice John Paul Stevens who voted
to uphold the law, but said Michael H. had been ``given a fair
opportunity to show that he is Victoria's natural father, that he
had developed a relationship with her, and that her interests would
be served by granting him visitation rights.''
   Stevens, saying he was willing to ``assume'' that Michael H. and
others in similar circumstances have a right to a judicial hearing
to establish paternity, said the California law does not violate the
right because Michael H. received a chance to prove paternity and
get visitation rights.
   ``Because I am convinced that the trial judge had the authority
under state law both to hear Michael's plea for visitation rights
and to grant him such rights if Victoria's best interests so
warranted, I am satisfied that the California statutory scheme is
(constitutional),'' Stevens said.
   Michael H. filed in a state court in Los Angeles a ``reverse
paternity'' lawsuit in 1982, seeking to have himself declared
Victoria's father. His lawsuit was dismissed.
   In upholding the dismissal, a state appeals court said the state
law presumption of fatherhood in Carol D.'s husband, identified in
court records as Gerald D., was based ``upon a determination by the
legislature as a matter of overriding social policy that ... the
husband is to be held responsible for the child and the integrity of
the family unit should not be impugned.''
   Michael H. said he had enjoyed a father-child relationship with
Victoria and that blood tests show a better-than-98-percent-chance
that Victoria is his biological daughter.
   Michael H.'s appeal said that Victoria was born as a result of an
affair Carol D. had while she was married to Gerald D.
   The appeal also said that Carol D. and Victoria moved to the
Virgin Islands to live with Michael H. for several months in 1982
after she and her husband were estranged.
   Court records indicate that Carol and Gerald D. later resumed
living together.
   Justice Antonin Scalia, joined by Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy,
wrote that Michael H. had no constitutional right to a judicial
hearing to establish paternity.
   Justices William J. Brennan, Byron R. White, Thurgood Marshall
and Harry A. Blackmun said he did have such a constitutional right.
   The case is Michael H. vs. Gerald D., 87-746.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
