<DOCNO> AP890615-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1136EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0522 06-15 0795</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0522,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with speech delivered; inserts 4 grafs on remarks
to crowd after 5th graf, He repeated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLYNCO, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, paying tribute to fallen
federal law-enforcement officers, today promised to wage an
anticrime campaign that will ``put the handcuffs on criminals, not
on the criminal justice system.''
   Bush also urged governors to join in his call for mandatory
prison time and no plea bargaining for violent offenders and an
expanded death penalty for convicted killers.
   The president spoke at the Federal Law Enforcement Training
Center, where agents and police officers from 60 agencies are
enrolled. It is also the place where U.S. ambassadors go to ``learn
to recognize and avoid terrorists,'' he noted.
   Bush also laid a wreath at the Peace Officers Memorial to the 39
graduates of the training center who have been killed in the line of
duty.
   He repeated a warning he made earlier this year at the funeral of
murdered Drug Enforcement Administration agent Everett Hatcher in
New York: ``Better that you had never been born than to attack one
of America's finest.'
   Before his speech, delivered under a broiling sun to a crowd of
several thousand, Bush attended a briefing where he fielded
questions from several students completing their training.
   Border Patrol agent David Rivera of El Paso, Texas, asked for
``some words of wisdom ... as we enter the field.''
   ``A word of wisdom would be, in spite of the suspicion or
circumstantial evidence, an individual should be treated with
respect and given his rights or her rights, even though the evidence
looks overwhelming,'' he said.
   ``I think we've got to stand for that. I know that sometimes is
difficult along the border when you have repeat offenders and you
have people that are brutally using this narcotics money for
personal gain and devastating communities.'
   At the ceremonies Bush signed a document transmitting to Congress
a the $1.2 billion ``take back the streets'' anticrime package he
unveiled a month ago.
   He told the officers he could have signed the transmittal in
Washington with ``a quick flourish of the pen'' and dispatched an
aide on a 10-minute car ride to Capitol Hill.
   ``But when it comes to fighting crime, you deserve more than
business as usual,'' he said. ``That is why I have come almost a
thousand miles to the center, to let you know we intend to back you
where it counts: on the streets and in the courtroom.''
   He said the center was training ``domestic freedom fighters in
the war on crime.''
   Bush spelled out anew three of the central planks of his
anticrime platform: doubling to 10 years the mandatory term for use
of semi-automatic weapons in crimes involving violence or drugs;
eliminating plea bargaining for violent federal firearms offenses;
and an expanded federal death penalty for killers and terrorists.
   ``When a criminal commits a crime with a gun and someone dies,
justice demands something in return: the ultimate penalty, death,''
the president said.
   ``I call on governors to match this federal initiative and
propose these same three standards at home: mandatory time, no deals
without cooperation and the death penalty,'' he said.
   ``Let's put the handcuffs on criminals, not on the criminal
justice system,'' he said. ``In short, I am proposing more law
enforcers to catch criminals, more staff to prosecute them and more
prisons to keep them off the streets.''
   Of the $1.2 billion package, $1 billion would be spent on
building more federal prison space. The prison system, designed for
30,951 inmates, now houses 48,000. The rest of the money would be
used to hire 825 new federal agents and 1,600 new prosecutors.
   Some congressional Democrats have complained that Bush wasn't
being tough enough, especially on semiautomatic weapons, where he
has suspended imports of foreign-made models but not sales of
domestic arms.
   His proposals also would double to 10 years the mimimum sentence
for using a semiautomatic weapon in a crime and ban semiautomatic
weapons clips of more than 15 rounds.
   Administration officials counter that the president crafted a
package that could get through the Congress, which under pressure
from the gun lobby is always wary of imposing new restrictions on
firearms.
   Bush also will outline his plan to a gathering of the 93 U.S.
attorneys at the White House on Friday.
   The president's half-day trip to Georgia was his second journey
outside Washington this week. He returned to the capital Tuesday
evening from a two-day swing through Montana, Wyoming and Nebraska
on behalf of his clear air initiative.
   Bush is taking three out-of-town trips next week _ to
Philadelphia on Monday, Richmond, Va., on Wednesday and New York on
Thursday _ for various speeches and events.
</TEXT>
