<HEAD>Explosion in Supertanker at Dubai Dry Dock, Casualties Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with more details of ship, possible cause
of explosion; CORRECTS name of managing company. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through the pump room
of a Pakistani-owned supertanker today while it was in dry dock, and
some deaths and injuries were reported, Persian Gulf shipping
sources said.
   Gulf-based marine salvage executives, speaking on condition of
anonymity, identified the tanker as the 231,439-ton Seiva and said
it was operated by the Atlas Shipping Management Co. of Hong Kong.
   The vessel was registered in the Bahamas, but the crew members
were believed to be Pakistani, the executives said.
   The supertanker was being repaired at dry dock facilities in
Dubai, a major southern gulf port, when the blast occurred about 4
p.m., the executives said.
   They said there were deaths and injuries among crewmen working in
the pump room at the time. But no details were available on the
casualties or how many people were aboard the vessel.
   ``A barricade has been thrown around the area where the tanker
was anchored, and we are unable to get close for details,'' said one
executive.
   He said the repair work involved welding and the blast was
probably caused by a spark from a welding gun that ignited gas in
the pump room.
