<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-RedSquad     06-15 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Red Squad,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Given New Protection from Federal Civil Rights Lawsuits in
Michigan Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today gave states and state
officials sweeping new protection from federal lawsuits accusing
them of civil rights violations.
   In a 5-4 ruling in a case from Michigan, the court said they may
not be sued under an 1871 law that authorizes damages against
``persons'' who violate people's civil liberties.
   States and state officials are not ``persons'' as defined by the
post-Civil War law, said Justice Byron R. White for the court.
   By contrast, the court previously has held that a city is a
person under the law and municipalities and their officials may be
sued.
   But White said today states and their officials enjoy
constitutional immunity that does not extend to cities. He relied on
the 11th Amendment, which gives states broad legal protection.
   ``Obviously state officials literally are persons,'' White said.
``But a suit against a state offficial in his or her official
capacity is not a suit against the official but rather is a suit
against the official's office.''
   Justice William J. Brennan, in a dissenting opinion, said the
court is giving a ``hypertechnical'' interpretation to a federal law
while ignoring its larger purpose.
   The Congress that passed the 1871 statute ``was fighting to save
the Union and in doing so it transformed our federal system,''
Brennan said. ``It is difficult, therefore, to believe that this
same Congress did not intend to include states among those who might
be liable under (the 1871 law) for the very deprivations that were
threatening this nation at that time.''
   Brennan was joined by Justices Thurgood Marshall, Harry A.
Blackmun and John Paul Stevens.
   White was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M. Kennedy.
   The court today refused to revive a suit accusing Michigan
officials of denying a promotion to a state employee because his
brother was a political activist.
   The employee, Ray Will, sought promotion to a job as data systems
analyst with the state police in 1973. He had been ranked second on
a promotion list and moved up to number one when the applicant above
him withdrew from consideration.
   But Will said he learned years later that he did not get the job
because a so-called Red Squad operated by the state police had
investigated his brother, Charles, a student political activist.
   The Red Squad, which monitored campus radicals with subversive
ideas, was held unconstitutional by a state judge in 1976.
   Ray Will then filed suit in state court under the 1871 federal
law. The suit named the state police and its director as defendants.
   A state judge in 1982 ruled that Will's rights were violated and
awarded him more than $153,000 for lost wages, emotional distress
and as punitive damages.
   But the Michigan Supreme Court overuled the judge in 1987 and
threw out the suit.
   The case is Will vs. Michigan Department of State Police, 87-1207.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
