<SECOND>PM-Republicans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,000</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   EDS: Top 7 grafs new with entire Rollins quote and statement he had
spoken inarticulately. Picks up 8th graf beginning ``Bush did
not...''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush says Republican Chairman Lee
Atwater is doing a ``great job,'' despite a widely condemned GOP
memo that likened House Speaker Thomas S. Foley's voting record to
that of a homosexual congressman.
   Bush's praise, at the opening of a two-day Republican National
Committee meeting, came as a prominent GOP campaign official said,
``I was guilty of being inarticulate'' in comments on Atwater's role
in the memo.
   Ed Rollins chairman of the GOP congressional campaign commitee,
said he did not intend to question Atwater's earlier statements
disavowing advance knowledge about the memo. ``I was defending Lee
and I take him at his word,'' he said today.
   ``I've heard myself on tape and I am inarticulate,'' he added.
   Rollins told a party meeting in Indiana earlier this week:
   ``I don't care how nice a man Tom Foley is, and he is a very,
very fine man. Just let me preface this by saying, we made a
terrible mistake last week as a party. The national committee, which
Lee Atwater, my friend and my deputy for four years, his committee
made a very serious mistake. I don't think, I take him at his word
that he didn't know about it. But you can't go out and deal with
innuendos and rumors. You need to go out and deal like I said in
facts.''
   The memo depicted Foley as a liberal and compared his voting
record to that of Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., an acknowledged
homosexual congressman. Mark Goodin, an aide to Atwater, resigned
under fire after saying he had approved the memo.
   Bush did not mention the memo episode during a speech Wednesday
night at a fund-raising dinner on the eve of a two-day meeting of
the RNC in Washington. But he had high praise for Atwater.
   ``Lee Atwater is doing a great job,'' the president said. ``He
has been a strong voice and a convincing voice about the need to
reach out to minorities and the disadvantaged.''
   Bush's praise of Atwater brought applause from the partisan crowd.
   Meetings of the party's executive, resolutions and rules
committees were scheduled for today, with Atwater, House Republican
Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia and other GOP leaders scheduled to
speak on Friday.
   Bush also touched obliquely on the recent ethical turmoil in
Congress, saying, ``Clearly it is time for an evenhanded ethical
approach across all branches of government.''
   But, he said, ``We will keep the competition on the issues.''
   Some Democrats have asked Bush to call for Atwater's resignation
because of the RNC memo, which was headed ``Tom Foley: Out of the
Liberal Closet.'' The memo compared the voting record of Foley,
D-Wash., with that of Frank, D-Mass., an acknowledged homosexual.
   Foley was elected speaker after Wright, D-Texas, resigned the
position in the midst of an investigation by the House ethics
committee. Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., also announced his
resignation after allegations about a purchase of junk bonds. Both
men denied any wrongdoing.
   House Republican leader Robert Michel of Illinois told the
fund-raiser audience Wednesday night that ``reform of the House must
be at the very heart of our party's effort'' as it moves toward the
1990 congressional elections.
</TEXT>
