<HEAD>Aide: Gordon to Withdraw From Race For Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Sen. Jack Gordon is withdrawing from the race
for the late Claude Pepper's U.S. House seat just two days after
announcing his candidacy, an aide said today.
   Gordon, 67, became the first Democrat to enter the race for the
seat held by Pepper, a liberal Democrat, since 1962. Aide Mike Petit
refused to say why Gordon was withdrawing. A news conference was
scheduled later today.
   Some Democratic leaders had expressed concern that Gordon, a
Miami Beach liberal first elected to the state Senate in 1972, would
be unable to attract conservative Hispanic voters needed to win the
Aug. 29 election.
   Cuban-born Hialeah Mayor Raul Martinez, a Democrat, has said he
is considering running but indicated he would be reluctant to oppose
Gordon.
   Two conservative Cuban-American Republicans _ state Sen. Ileana
Ros-Lehtinen and businessman Carlos Perez _ announced their
candidacies last week along with black laywer Jeff Allen. The
district is nearly half Hispanic.
   Pepper died May 30 at age 88. GOP leaders consider his
increasingly conservative district a prime opportunity to pick up a
seat in Congress.
