<FIRST>r a AM-FamilyPoisonings-Movie     06-15 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Poisonings-Movie,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Richardson Case Moves to Hollywood in Dispute Over Movie Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story of James Richardson, who
spent 21 years in prison wrongfully accused of murdering his seven
children, has become the center of a war of words between movie
producers and lawyers.
   Richardson wants a feature film about his crusade for freedom
done by producer Steve Jaffe, who bought the dramatic rights to a
1970 book about the case by Richardson's lawyer, Mark Lane.
   ``My project is more accurate,'' said Richardson, freed April 25
in Arcadia after a special prosecutor said he was unjustly accused
in the 1967 murders.
   Lane and Jaffe, Richardson says, control the rights to his life
story.
   But producers Suzanne Stanford and Gene Kraft told the St.
Petersburg Times that they have obtained the rights to ``everybody
except James Richardson,'' including newspaper reporters, Richardson
relatives and Arcadia residents who advanced the case while
Richardson was in jail.
   ``There's a tremendous story that surrounds Richardson during
that time,'' Kraft said. Richardson's trial and legal challenges are
available to any screenwriter as public record, and ``his story is
basically the backdrop,'' he said.
   Kraft said that if that logic fails to impress network
executives, the couple's partner might: David L. Wolper Productions.
   Wolper, known for his extravaganzas for the 1984 Olympics and the
Statue of Liberty centennial, is a ``network reliable,'' one of a
handful of producers programmers go to year after year, he said.
   A Wolper executive confirmed Stanford and Kraft have a contract
to develop the Richardson story, probably as a four-hour miniseries,
the Times reported Thursday.
   Jaffe accused his rival producers of trying to exploit
Richardson, who now works for comedian and diet guru Dick Gregory,
who runs a health and weight-loss clinic in Fort Walton Beach.
   And Lane said: ``They don't have James. They don't have me. I
don't know who else there is.''
   Kraft said that's Lane's whole problem.
   ``My feeling would be that Mark Lane is really going to do, not
the James Richardson story, but the Mark Lane story,'' Kraft said.
   Caught in the middle is Ellis Rubin. He worked with Lane as
Richardson's co-counsel, but was fired after Richardson went free.
Lane claimed Rubin threatened Richardson while trying to cut his own
movie deal.
   Kraft, Stanford and Mark Wolper, David Wolper's son, acknowledge
talking with Rubin. But Rubin would not talk to a reporter _ unusual
for the flamboyant Miami lawyer.
   Lane said Rubin has been silent because Richardson sent a letter
prohibiting him, under the rules of professional responsibility,
from discussing his case.
   Furthermore, Lane says, he will sue to stop any production that
does not pay Richardson for the story of injustice he endured for 21
years.
</TEXT>
