<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0565 06-15 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0565,0828</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Four Israeli Soldiers Jailed For Beating Palestinian</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with four soldiers ordered jailed in beating
of Palestinian prisoner. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRYAT MALAKI, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court today sentenced
four Israeli soldiers to up to nine months in jail for their roles
in the beating of a Palestinian who later died in custody.
   The defendants left the courtroom angered by what their attorney
termed ``particularly harsh'' sentences and immediately got into
fistfights with photographers waiting outside.
   A photographer for the Hebrew daily Yediot Ahronot suffered a
black eye in the 10-minute melee, and a military policeman who was a
friend of one of the soldiers was taken into custody for the assault.
   Also today, police raided a news service run by Sari Nusseibeh, a
Palestinian activist accused by Israel of being a mastermind and PLO
paymaster of the Palestinian uprising.
   Authorities ordered the Holy Land Press Service closed for two
years, and Nusseibeh said he was told to report to police
headquarters for questioning.
   ``The office was being used to advance the goals of the PLO and
find ways to incite the uprising,'' police spokesman Uzi Sandori
said.
   In another development, an Israeli cameraman for ABC-TV was shot
in the head today with a plastic bullet by Israeli troops dispersing
Palestinian stone throwers in the West Bank town of Ramallah, a
network producer said. A military official said the television crew
violated an army order putting the area off limits to reporters. The
camaraman was hospitalized in good condition.
   The four soldiers were convicted on May 25 of brutality in the
beating of 42-year-old Hani el-Shami on Aug. 22 while arresting him
in a sweep of the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya refugee camp.
   They had been accused of manslaughter but were acquitted when the
judge ruled that el-Shami died after a second beating inflicted by
other soldiers at a military camp. The other soldiers have not been
charged or tried.
   The judge, Col. Emanuel Gross, today sentenced three of the
soldiers to 18 months in prison, nine months of the term to be
suspended. They were 1st Sgt. Yitzhak Adler, 21; Pvt. Yitzhak
Kibbudi, 20, and Pvt. Ron Hakel, 19.
   A fourth soldier, Pvt. Ariyeh Luchato, 20, was sentenced to a
year in prison, six months suspended, because he arrived in the
middle of the beating.
   Defense Attorney Uziel Atzmon described the sentences as
``particularly harsh, especially since we had the feeling that the
major responsibility fell on the commanders.''
   The case was seen as a test of the army's willingness to
discipline soldiers accused of brutality and focused attention on
the army's beating policy. Since the uprising began December 1987,
516 Palestinians have died and more than 10,000 have been injured.
Twenty-two Israelis have also been killed.
   Police spokesman Uzi Sandori said authorities ordered the Holy
Land Press Service because the office in Israeli-annexed Arab east
Jerusalem, ``was being used to advance the goals of the PLO and find
ways to incite the uprising.''
   About two dozen police officers who entered Nusseibeh's
second-floor office carried out boxes and plastic bags filled with
papers.
   Officers changed the office lock and welded the entrance shut.
   ``I have no idea why this was done,'' Nusseibeh, a philosophy
professor at the West Bank's Bir Zeit University, told reporters.
   Sandori said police had evidence the office was being used to
help the PLO and its Fatah faction headed by PLO chief Yasser
Arafat. The PLO is outlawed in Israel. Sandori said police will
review the papers ``and then we will see if we have a good reason to
investigate him. But we wanted to close his office.''
   The Ramallah shooting occurred at 11 a.m. when the ABC crew was
filming Israeli troops dispersing a stone-throwing riot, said ABC
producer Lynn Eshel.
   The bullet struck cameraman Shlomo Franco, 42, above one eye.
   Yael Bossem, a spokeswoman at Hadassah Mount Scopus Hospital in
Jerusalem, said Franco was conscious. Franco was later said to be in
good condition.
   A photographer who visited him saw three fragments of a
brownish-gray plastic bullet that had been removed by doctors.
   The army official said the crew was at the scene of a
late-morning skirmish between soldiers and about 50 Palestinian
youths.
   ``The commanding officer at the scene presented the TV crew with
a warrant closing the area. The crew left, went around the block and
returned on the side of the demonstrators,'' said the official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said soldiers did not see the crew and opened fire with rubber
and plastic ammunition, wounding the cameraman, the official said.
   ``They disregarded the closure order and covered the story from
the side of the people who were disturbing public order,'' said the
official.
</TEXT>
