<HEAD>Jury Awards Woman $300,000 in Faith-Healing Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CORRECT town to Kingwood sted Kingswood
and ADD that verdict was against Hunters and their ministry. PICKS UP 5th
graf pvs, ``I had ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury awarded $300,000 to a woman who
swooned and fell at a faith-healing ceremony and fractured her back.
   Evelyn E. Kuykendall, 67, of Marshville, N.C., spent two months
in a hospital after no one broke her fall during a ``laying on of
hands'' in 1988.
   The faith healers, Charles and Frances Hunter of Kingwood, Texas,
had testified during the federal court trial that Mrs. Kuykendall
fell in a ``peculiar way'' and their ``catchers'' were not able to
reach her.
   The verdict against the Hunters and their City of Light
Ministries was reached on Wednesday.
   ``I had my eyes closed in prayer and I recall swaying, but when I
fell, I fell directly backwards and hit my lower back first,'' said
Mrs. Kuykendall.
   Asked if she could have fallen in some strange way, she said, ``I
don't see how. I'd done this many times and always been caught.''
   Mrs. Kuykendall's belief in faith healing has not been shaken
``one bit,'' and she holds no hard feelings toward the Hunters, said
her husband, Marion.
   Mrs. Kuykendall suffers from a spinal disease unrelated to the
fall and was led into the courtroom bent nearly double.
