<FIRST>r a AM-People     06-15 0980</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,1020</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor-director Sam Wanamaker celebrated his 70th
birthday at a ground-breaking ceremony for a replica of William
Shakespeare's Globe Theater.
   After 20 years of planning and fund-raising, Wanamaker signed a
$30 million contract with a construction company to build his
project close to the theater's original site on the south bank of
the River Thames.
   ``This is the second most important day of my life,'' the
American-born Wanamaker said at the ceremony Wednesday.
   The most important day, he said, will be April 23, 1992, the
scheduled completion date for his project, to be called the
International Shakespeare Globe Center. April 23 is Shakespeare's
birthday.
   The complex will be a center for Shakespeare studies and will
house two theaters, one of them a replica of the Globe, where
Shakespeare's plays were performed in the bard's lifetime. It will
also include an exhibition area, offices, restaurant, apartments and
shops.
   The original Globe Theater was built in 1599 and burned down in
1613. It was rebuilt, but was finally demolished in 1644.
Wanamaker's complex is believed to be a few hundred yards from the
original site. Archaeologists are working to locate the exact site.
   Nearby are the recently excavated foundations of the Rose
Theater, the only relic of a theater of Shakespeare's day to have
been found.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GLENS FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who's back, and which concert tickets
are gone?
   Within an hour and a half, some 5,000 tickets were sold Wednesday
at the Glens Falls Civic Center for the opening concert of the Who's
reunion tour this summer, their first performance in six years.
   Heavy rains may have soaked those in line but it did not dampen
their enthusiasm.
   ``I dropped my kid off and came flying,'' said Carol Alden of
South Glens Falls, who'd gotten the news of ticket sales from a
friend.
   The British band opens its 36-date summer stadium tour June 21 in
the 8,200-seat Glens Falls Civic Center on the edge of the
Adirondack Mountains in upstate New York.
   A last-minute decision to make fewer tickets available, including
eliminating standing-room tickets, helped speed sales, event
organizers said.
   The band's stage was ``so humongous,'' the center needed the
extra space, said Event Coordinator Jeff Barrett.
   Joe Patterson, 24, of Utica was first in line and forked over
$100 for four front-row seats, then pumped a clenched fist in the
air to the cheers of the crowd.
   ``This,'' he said, ``is awesome.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cellist Julian Lloyd Webber sold a 200-year-old
cello at auction Thursday for nearly $125,000 to help pay for his
divorce settlement.
   The cello, made by Guiseppe Guadagnini in 1791, was purchased by
a private German buyer, said a spokeswoman for Sotheby's auction
house. But don't worry, Lloyd Webber still has a Stradivarius cello.
   The younger brother of megamusical composer Andrew Lloyd Webber
said recently that he was selling the cello to help pay for his
divorce settlement. He and his wife, Celia, got a divorce in April
after a 15-year marriage.
   Lloyd Webber used the cello in many live performances and
recordings. He was once quoted as saying: ``The relationship between
me and my cello is like a marriage. Nothing, and I mean nothing,
comes between us.''
   The Sotheby's spokeswoman said the auction house was ``very
pleased'' with the price, which outstripped the pre-sale estimate.
She said Lloyd Webber's Stradivarius cello is worth at least twice
the price of the Guadagnini.
   ``Of course he is nostalgic about his cello but I think he feels
it is a shame to have such a nice instrument unused,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lee Iacocca told television executives to
start censoring their shows, or advertisers, including his own
Chrysler Corp., may pull out their commercials.
   The Chrysler chairman said Tuesday that viewers are tired of
trash TV and are venting their rage on the big advertisers with
angry letters and boycotts.
   ``I don't want to be the censor; I want you to do it,'' he said
in an address to the Hollywood Radio &amp; Television Society.
   Iacocca warned that companies such as Chrysler, which spends $250
million a year on television, could withdraw advertising from
objectionable programming if steps are not taken to tone down the
``bedroom bingo'' and violence.
   ``Help get me and every other sponsor out of the censorship
business,'' he said. ``We don't want the job.''
   He agreed that some complaining viewers are ``fanatics,'' but
said most are not. ``Don't write them off as a fringe group,'' he
said. ``They've found out they have clout and they're going to use
it.''
   A number of advertisers have reacted to consuer complaints since
a Michigan woman earlier this year got some advertisers to cancel
spots in Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``Married ... With Children.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kris Kristofferson wrote a song in Abbie
Hoffman's honor, and director John Avildsen of ``Rocky'' fame
created a video of the late political activist's life.
   Both works will be part of a memorial tribute planned for
Saturday in New York City. Among the expected guests are Norman
Mailer, Allen Ginsberg, Amy Carter, Buster Poindexter, Daniel
Ellsberg, Paul Krassner, Wavy Gravy and surviving members of the
Chicago Seven. Hoffman's three children are also expected.
   ``A man who led such an extraordinary life will be commemorated
by just a few of the thousands who knew, admired and loved him,''
said Abby Hirsch, one of the organizers of the event.
   Hoffman, 52, committed suicide April 12 at his New Hope, Pa.,
home with an overdose of phenobarbital.
   The memorial, ``No Regrets: A Tribute to Abbie Hoffman,'' takes
its title from Hoffman's final public speech, given to students at
Vanderbilt University about his political and social activism.
   He ended that speech by saying, ``I regret nothing.''
   Other memorials have also been held in Massachusetts,
Pennsylvania and Los Angeles.
