<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1252EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Freeholders     06-15 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Freeholders,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Right of Non-Property Owners in St. Louis Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who do not own property may not be
excluded for that reason from membership on a public body empowered
to recommend a reorganization of local government, a unanimous
Supreme Court ruled today.
   The court declared unconstitutional the composition of the St.
Louis City-St. Louis County Board of Freeholders.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun, writing for the court, said a
land-ownership requirement for appointment to such a public agency
violates the Constitution's guarantee of equal protection under law
for all people.
   ``The mere fact that the board of freeholders considers land-use
issues cannot suffice to sustain a land-ownership requirement in
this case,'' he said.
   The St. Louis freeholder board was created to write a proposed
charter for reorganizing the city and county government structure.
The board also was empowered to recommend new taxes to finance the
city and county governments.
   Any proposals by the board would be submitted to the voters in a
referendum.
   Board members were appointed by the mayor of St. Louis, the
county executive and the governor of Missouri.
   State Representative Robert J. Quinn, a St. Louis County resident
who does not own property, said his rights were violated by a state
constitutional requirement limiting membership on the freeholder
board to property owners.
   Quinn, in a suit on behalf of himself and all others in the city
and county who do not own property, said the exclusion violated the
U.S. Constitution's guarantee of freedom from unlawful
discrimination.
   But the Missouri Supreme Court ruled last year that the
constitutional protection does not apply because the freeholder
board does not have ``general governmental powers.''
   Blackmun said today that even though the freeholder board has a
limited role, that does not mean its composition can violate
constitutional protections against ``invidious discrimination.''
   The case is Quinn vs. Millsap, 88-1048.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1308EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     06-15 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Probe May Get to the Bottom of Rumors of Rocky Flats Nuclear Reaction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal investigation at Rocky Flats may
get to the bottom of decade-old rumors of a nuclear chain reaction
occurring at the weapons plant during fires 20 or more years ago.
   Rocky Flats critics long have suspected that such a reaction,
which could send radioactivity into the air, happened during one or
both fires in 1957 and 1969.
   Studies in 1977 and 1987 revealed relatively high quantities of
two radioactive elements that can be produced during a nuclear
reaction, but officials at the time said their presence can be
explained in several other ways.
   Rocky Flats officials have denied the fires led to a chain
reaction, although it was acknowledged that plutonium was released
into the atmosphere as a result of the blazes.
   The Denver Post today quoted unidentified sources as saying that
if a chain reaction did occur at Rocky Flats, evidence of it may
surface in Department of Energy or Rockwell International Corp.
documents regarding waste disposal.
   Federal agents raided the plant June 6 as part of an
investigation of alleged illegal storage and disposal of hazardous
waste at the plant.
   Rocky Flats, 16 miles from Denver, manufactures plutonium
triggers for nuclear bombs. It is operated for DOE by Rockwell.
   Dr. Carl Johnson, former Jefferson County health director, first
raised the issue of a possible nuclear reaction at Rocky Flats. In
1977, he found relatively high levels of radioactive cesium in soil
samples outside the plant.
   A 1987 Rockwell study of groundwater at Rocky Flats found high
levels of strontium.
   Cesium and strontium are produced during a nuclear reaction.
   Rockwell and DOE officials said the cesium and strontium came
from fallout from atmospheric bomb tests in Nevada and elsewhere.
   But Rocky Flats critics said the levels are too high to be caused
by fallout, and the Environmental Protection Agency asked the plant
in 1987 for more precise tests.
   Rockwell and DOE officials are conducting those tests, said Nat
Miullo, Rocky Flats project director for the EPA in Denver.
   ``The levels are still extremely low, and no data we have now
indicate that such a reaction occurred,'' Miullo said. But he said
the EPA would not accept Rocky Flats' explanation for the elements'
presence without further evidence.
   ``To reach that conclusion, based on less than high-quality data,
is something we will not stand beside,'' Miullo told The New York
Times.
   He said the strontium and cesium also may have been used in the
calibration of testing instruments and then dumped on the ground, or
they may have showed up as the result of false readings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
