<FIRST>u w PM-Scotus-Superfund     06-15 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Superfund,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules States May Be Forced to Help Pay to Clean Hazardous Waste
Sites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States may be forced, through private lawsuits,
to help pay for cleaning up hazardous waste sites targeted under the
so-called Superfund Act, the Supreme Court ruled today.
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices said the Constitution's Commerce
Clause gives Congress the power to strip state governments of their
constitutional immunity against private lawsuits.
   The decision will force Pennsylvania to defend itself against a
lawsuit by Union Gas. Co. aimed at recovering the clean-up costs the
company owes the federal government.
   Officials from Pennsylvania and 17 other states had told the
hight court that a ruling against Pennsylvania could expose states
to $100 billion in Superfund clean-up costs.
   Hazardous coal tar from an abandoned Union Gas facility began
seeping into Brodhead Creek near Stroudsburg, Pa., after state flood
control officials struck the deposit during excavation in 1980.
   Federal environmental officials worked with Pennsylvania to clean
up the problem, at a cost of about $1.4 million.
   The federal government then sued Union Gas to recover part of the
money, invoking the Superfund law _ also known as the Comprehensive
Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act.
   Union Gas, in turn, sued Pennsylvania. Its lawsuit accused the
state of negligently contributing to the discharge of the hazardous
material.
   The Philadelphia-based 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
that 1986 amendments to the Superfund law eliminated the states'
constitutional immunity in such cases and the suit could go forward.
   The appeals court said the Constitution's Commerce Clause allows
Congress to eliminate such immunity.
   Today, the Supreme Court agreed.
   Writing the court's main opinion, Justice William J. Brennan said
the Superfund law ``renders states liable in money damages in
federal court,'' and added that ``Congress has the authority to
render them so liable when legislating pursuant to the Commerce
Clause.''
   He was joined fully by Justices Thurgood Marshall, Harry A.
Blackmun and John Paul Stevens and, in part, by Justice Byron R.
White.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia,
Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy voted to dismiss the suit
against Pennsylvania. They said the state's immunity should prevail.
   Pennsylvania officials, with the support of 17 other states, said
the appeals court ruling wrongly exposed them to great financial
burdens.
   Federal environmental officials have listed some 22,000 hazardous
waste sites with clean-up costs approaching $100 billion, the state
officials said.
   Supporting Pennsylvania's appeal were New York, California,
Connecticut, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kentucky, Maryland, Missouri,
New Jersey, New Mexico, North Carolina, Oklahoma, South Carolina,
Utah, Vermont and West Virginia.
   The case is Pennsylvania vs. Union Gas, 87-1241.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
