<FIRST>r a AM-GrandIsleErosion     06-15 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grand Isle Erosion,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gulf Threatens Motel, Homes at Grand Isle</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2,000-foot-long section of beach on this
tiny resort island was declared an emergency area as the Gulf of
Mexico eats away beach front and threatens to wash away a motel.
   Workers for the island's municipal government started putting
sandbags around the Edgewater Motel late Wednesday, 24 hours after
the state of emergency was declared.
   ``There's no danger of the building falling overnight,'' Mayor
Andy Valence said as water lapped at the pilings under the
Edgewater. But, he said, something had to be done to protect the
building and nearby Louisiana Highway 1, the only route to and from
the island.
   ``It's bad. I don't know what's going to happen,'' said motel
owner Henrietta Collins. ``I have apartments right on the beach, and
it's washing my pilings out. I've already lost my land.''
   She said that before Hurricane Gilbert last year, the beach
extended out a hundred yards from her motel.
   Hurricanes last year eroded large areas, but such huge storms
aren't the only problem, Valence said. Wind up to 20 mph in recent
days has contributed to choppy water that accelerates natural
erosion.
   ``Last week on one day we lost five feet. Now, with the southwest
winds and about 3-foot seas, the beach area in the middle part of
the island is really being damaged,'' Valence said.
   Grand Isle's erosion problems have become more apparent in recent
years, as state and federal officials have become more aware of the
loss of marshy land all along Louisiana's coast.
   Louisiana loses 30 to 50 square miles of its coastal marshes
every year, about an acre every 15 minutes, an area the size of
Rhode Island over the past 30 years. More than 100 barrier islands
have disappeared off the Louisiana coast in 50 years.
   Part of the loss is due to salt water intrusion through canals
dredged for cypress logging at the turn of the century and for
oilfield exploration and development over the past 50 years. The
salt water kills vegetation that holds the marshes together.
   But most of the loss stems from the taming of the Mississippi
River, which used to spread tons of silt and fresh water through the
marshes, rebuilding wetlands and barrier islands. With levees the
length of the river and 27 sets of locks and dams along the
Mississippi and its tributaries, the silt no longer reaches the
marshes.
</TEXT>
