<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1324EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     06-15 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sleaze Takes Center Stage in Greece Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NIKOS KONSTANDARAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who aspire to lead Greece into the
1990s are locked in political combat so blunt and bellicose that
allegations of illicit sex, government corruption and even Nazi
sympathies have buried the issues.
   Premier Andreas Papandreou, 70, and opposition leader Constantine
Mitsotakis, 71, head into Sunday's national elections on the heels
of what many have called the most slanderous campaign since the
return to democracy in 1974.
   ``Most people buy three newspapers a day to find out who is
stealing, who is selling out, and who is having sex with who,'' said
film director Nikos Koundouros.
   The feud between the two men, whose personal emnity dates back to
1965, has obscured the fact that Greece has the highest inflation
rate, biggest deficit and weakest currency in the European Economic
Community.
   ``These phenomena are characteristic of a war of mutual
destruction between two gladiators, and of efforts to shift the
people's attention from the country's burning issues,'' says
Leonidas Kyrkos, a leader of a leftist coalition that is Greece's
third major political force.
   The Interior Ministry says 7.89 million Greeks are eligible to
vote the 300 seats in Parliament. A party that wins a majority can
name the premier and Cabinet.
   Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement controls 154 of the
seats, Mitsotakis' conservative New Democracy party holds 111 and
the remaining 45 are split between 20 small parties and independents.
   Mitsotakis' party led by about 10 percentage points in recent
polls. But 15 percent of voters were undecided and the close race
raises the possibility of a coalition or minority government.
   Mitsotakis has hammered away at a financial scandal shaking
Papandreou's government, and opposition newspapers are having a
field day with the premier's affair with a much younger woman and
his divorce Friday from his American-born wife, Margaret.
   Nude photos of Papandreou's 35-year-old fiancee, Dimitra Liani,
became almost daily fixtures in right-wing newspapers after the
premier announced the affair in September.
   ``He has made us the laughing stock of the world,'' Mitsotakis
tells supporters.
   The pro-government daily Avriani responded with what it alleged
were transcripts of Mitsotakis' intimate telephone conversations
with a woman who was not his wife. And a radio station owned by the
newspaper aired the almost inaudible tapes for days.
   ``No politician in Greece has been slurred as much as I have and
this is a continuation of those attacks,'' Mitsotakis said the day
after the tapes aired. ``Andreas Papandreou and (government security
services) are behind this.''
   The opposition press recently published excerpts from a diary
kept by the premier's former chief bodyguard that alleges
Papandreou's involvement in numerous sexual liaisons, telephone
tapping and other intrigues.
   ``That is how pitiful they have become. Their slander does not
touch us,'' Papandreou said at a recent campaign rally.
   The mudslinging is fueled by the partisan nature of Greece's mass
media.
   ``People have become used to the poison,'' said Serapheim
Fyntanides, managing editor of the liberal daily Eleftherotypia.
   Fyntanides' newspaper ran a blank front page one day this month
to protest the sleazy campaign.
   Papandreou handily defeated Mitsotakis in the 1985 elections. But
the men have been bitter rivals since Mitsotakis defected from the
party run by Panpandreou's father in 1965.
   Both accuse the other of engaging in political intrigues that led
to the military dictatorship that ruled Greece from 1967 until 1974.
   The insinuations can be as deadly as the blunt accusations. One
government newspaper runs a half-page photo daily of Mitsotakis
flanked by two German soldiers, implying he collaborated with the
Nazis during World War II.
   Mitsotakis points out that he was a member of the resistance,
arrested twice and sentenced to death by the Nazis in his native
Crete. When the picture first appeared in 1985, he responded that
both Germans were sympathizers of the resistance.
   Papandreou's party portrays the New Democracy as too willing to
sell out to foreign interests and buckle to U.S. influence.
   Mitsotakis contends the ruling party ``has cost the country 400
billion drachmas ($2.3 billion) in 24 of the better-known scandals.''
   George Koskotas, a Greek financier jailed in the United States,
alleges Papandreou authorized the $200 million looting of Koskotas'
Bank of Crete as a way to finance the governing party.
   Mitsotakis advocates a free market economy and pledges to
streamline Greek bureaucracy and cut the 14 percent annual inflation
rate. He said he considers NATO membership and U.S. military bases
vital to Greece's defense.
   Papandreou came to power in 1981 promising to pull Greece out of
NATO and the EEC and to close the American military bases here.
However, the premier now says Greece benefits from its membership in
both groups and his government is close to a new bases agreement
with the United States.
</TEXT>
