<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Tracy     06-15 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Tracy,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Novelist, Travel Writer Dead at 75</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honor Tracy, a travel writer, columnist and author
of novels that satirized Irish and English society, has died at the
age of 75.
   Miss Tracy died at a nursing home in Oxford on Tuesday. The cause
of death was not given.
   Born and educated in England, she traveled extensively from the
home base she set up in rural Ireland, and published novels and
books set in the British Isles, the West Indies, Japan and Spain.
   From Ireland, she wrote a witty weekly column for The Sunday
Times of London, and became known for her idiosyncratic, original
views, especially when she sued her own newspaper in 1954 for
impugning her professional reputation.
   The paper, facing a lawsuit from an Irish priest who felt
maligned by Miss Tracy's column, ran an apology without consulting
her.
   Miss Tracy won her lawsuit against The Sunday Times, the judge
describing her as ``a woman of great resolution and determination.''
   She published her first fiction in magazines in 1943 while
working for the British Ministry of Information.
   Her hilarious account of Irish life, ``Mind You, I've Said
Nothing!'' was published in 1953, followed the next year by her
first novel, ``The Deserters,'' about military policewomen.
   She wrote half a dozen novels, the most successful of which was
``The Straight and Narrow Path,'' in 1956.
   A brief marriage ended in divorce. She had no children.
</TEXT>
