<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MIARemains     06-15 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Remains,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese to Return More Remains Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese government has informed the
United States it will return next week the remains of what it
believes are 28 American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War,
the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Spokesman Pete Williams said the transfer of the remains would
occur Wednesday, with a team of U.S. military officials flying to
Hanoi. The remains will be flown to an Army laboratory in Hawaii for
possible identification, he said.
   The repatriation will be the 10th since August 1987, when the
United States made a special effort to enlist greater assistance
from Vietnam in accounting for missing Americans.
   The group of 28 is one of the largest to be returned by the
Vietnamese government. The largest repatriation occurred last
December and involved the remains of 38 individuals.
   ``The U.S. government recognizes and appreciates the efforts of
the Vietnamese government which resulted in this unilateral
repatriation and hopes that such accelerated cooperation will
continue to bring increased accountability for Americans still
missing or otherwise unaccounted for in Vietnam.''
   The Pentagon said it had not received any information from
Vietnam on precisely where the various remains had been recovered or
the circumstances surrounding their discovery.
   Currently, 2,353 Americans continue to be listed as missing in
Indochina as a result of the Vietnam War, of whom 1,719 are listed
as missing in Vietnam.
   All told, the remains of 200 Americans have been repatriated to
the United States from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the
Army lab since the end of the war.
   In the past, remains repatriated by Vietnam have occasionally
included those of Vietnamese individuals. As a result, the Pentagon
routinely declines to predict whether all repatriated remains can be
individually identified by the Army laboratory in Honolulu.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
