<FIRST>r a PM-UndergroundAtlanta     06-15 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underground Atlanta,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Underground Shopping Complex Opens in Atlanta</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hecklers and a last-minute lawsuit failed to stop
the opening today of Underground Atlanta, a $142 million complex of
shops, restaurants and clubs designed to put the fun back into
downtown Atlanta.
   Mayor Andrew Young's speech was drowned out by homeless advocates
blowing whistles and chanting, ``Atlanta keeps the homeless
underground.'' Police said six protesters were moved. They were not
immediately charged.
   Earlier today, a judge refused to block the developers from
calling the project Underground Atlanta, ruling against a company
called Underground Atlanta Inc. that claims to hold the rights to
the name.
   The project, the result of a three-year overhaul by The Rouse
Co., is seen by backers as the solution to the common complaint that
there's not much fun downtown. It offers 22 restaurants and clubs
and nearly 100 retailers.
   At a news conference, Young said Underground Atlanta has given
the city's center a boost of confidence and strengthened its shaky
investment climate.
   ``Its importance to the city of Atlanta was a heart transplant,''
he said. ``What we've done is put in a new heart. ... It makes other
things happen.''
   At the opening ceremony, Young angrily began defending the city's
record on the homeless against hecklers, then gave up trying to
speak. The number of demonstrators was unclear because they were
scattered throughout the crowd.
   Wind and rain moved through the city just before the complex
opened, but the party, held in a covered area, went on as planned.
About 2,000 attended, with 2,000 more milling about the complex, far
fewer than the hoped-for tens of thousands.
   The original Underground Atlanta opened in the city's viaducts in
1969 but closed in 1982 under the perception that it was riddled
with crime. The new version is around the original site but is three
times bigger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
