<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1358EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UCLAPollution     06-15 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UCLA Pollution,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Identifies Itself as Major Polluter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The picturesque University of California, Los
Angeles, campus is one of Southern California's major sources of
pollution, says a UCLA study.
   The university creates 15,000 tons of solid waste, 800 tons of
medical waste and 100 tons of hazardous waste such as asbestos,
poisons and explosive chemicals each year, researchers in the
Graduate School of Architecture and Urban Planning estimated.
   State legislators have expressed interest in the study because
universities historically have been exempt from many environmental
regulations.
   Officials at the campus, located in an area of gentle rolling
hills six miles from the Pacific Ocean and 12 miles from downtown
Los Angeles, said they will study the report and consider some of
its recommendations.
   The university's manicured grounds, filled with palm trees,
magnolias and acres of green grass, even come under criticism in the
study. Those grounds require huge amounts of water in an arid region
that might be better served by desert vegetation, the study said.
   ``We do not mean to imply that UCLA is a worse polluter than
other universities and certainly not than some industries. But it
certainly plays a role,'' said Robert Gottlieb, faculty adviser to
the six graduate students who wrote the study. He described the
findings for a Los Angeles Times story Thursday, a day in advance of
the study's release.
   ``The purpose of the study is to show, as graphically as
possible, what that role is and ... how a university like UCLA, with
all of its intellectual and scientific resources, is uniquely
positioned to start solving some of the nation's most complex
environmental problems.''
   The campus is the city's third largest user of electricity, the
eighth largest consumer of water and with its large fleet of
vehicles, the 10th largest producer of carbon monoxide, the study
says.
   Some suggestions in the study for cutting down on waste include
using coffee mugs instead of disposable cups, making photocopies on
both sides of a sheet of paper, replacing campus mail envelopes with
reusable folders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
