<FIRST>u a AM-BattleshipCrewman 1stLd-Writethru a0645 06-15 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battleship Crewman, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sailor Who Said He Was USS Iowa Scapegoat Is Reassigned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `The Navy..., to CORRECT to breech sted magazine.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sailor who said the Navy was trying
to make him a scapegoat for the deaths of 47 shipmates in the
explosion aboard the battleship Iowa reported to new duties Thursday
at the Mayport Naval Station.
   Gunner's Mate 3rd Class Kendall Truitt, 21, has been reassigned
to a destroyer commander's staff in the weapons department, said
Cmdr. Tim Taylor, Mayport spokesman.
   ``He's being handled exactly like any other third-class petty
officer,'' Taylor said at a news conference.
   Truitt's attorney said Wednesday that his client would have no
further comment until the Navy's investigation of the USS Iowa blast
is complete.
   ``He wants to become a sailor again,'' lawyer Ellis Rubin said in
a telephone interview from Miami. ``He would like to just put this
behind him.''
   Shortly after the April 19 disaster, the Navy called Truitt a
hero for trying to save crewmates. Later, published reports said the
Navy was investigating the relationship between Truitt and Clayton
Hartwig, a gunner's mate who was killed.
   Truitt, sole beneficiary of a $50,000 double-indemnity life
insurance policy purchased by Hartwig, reportedly was under
investigation to see if there was a link between the men in a murder
or suicide plot.
   Truitt has vehemently denied wrongdoing and has said the Navy was
seeking a scapegoat.
   The Navy in late May ordered Truitt transferred to Mayport, away
from Iowa crewmates he had publicly accused of false speculation
about his relationship with Hartwig. Truitt also has suggested the
explosion may have been caused by inexperienced sailors pushing bags
of gunpowder too quickly into the gun's breech.
   Rubin said he hopes the Navy board of inquiry report into the
disaster will include an apology to Truitt.
   The Iowa left its home port of Norfolk, Va., on June 8 for a
six-month deployment in the Mediterranean.
</TEXT>
