<DOCNO> AP890615-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1445EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SenateMailings     06-15 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate Mailings,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators' Mass Mailings Cost $52.7 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mass mailings by 100 senators during 1987-88
cost taxpayers more than $52.7 million, the congressional watchdog
Common Cause reported Thursday.
   The 27 senators seeking re-election last year spent $20.1 million
of the total, an average of 48 cents per household, according to the
Common Cause study.
   The per-household figures compared to an average of 31 cents for
the 67 senators who were not campaigning for re-election, and 15
cents for six senators who retired in 1988.
   ``Franked mass mailings are used for campaign purposes by members
of Congress and provide incumbents with an unfair and discriminatory
advantage over their challengers,'' Common Cause President Fred
Wertheimer said. ``The use of the frank for mass mailings should be
eliminated or sharply curtailed.''
   The study said taxpayer-financed mailing costs for both houses
have increased from $48.9 million in fiscal 1978 to $113.4 million
for fiscal 1988.
   The bulk of the cost is for mass mailings rather than individual
letters sent out by a member in response to a constituent's
correspondence, the study said.
   In February, the Senate changed its policy and expanded from
three to six the number of mass mailings each senator can make to
every address in his or her state each year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
