<FIRST>u w AM-Republicans     06-15 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Republicans,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>State GOP Leaders Support Atwater Despite Foley-Memo Incident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Republican leaders on Thursday generally
backed GOP Chairman Lee Atwater, who has drawn Democratic fire in
connection with a party memo that likened House Speaker Thomas S.
Foley's record to that of a homosexual lawmaker.
   ``I think everybody agrees it was inappropriate and I think the
proper action was taken (with the resignation of an Atwater aide)
... and that's the end of it,'' Michigan State Republican Chairman
E. Spencer Abraham said.
   ``I found absolutely nothing in it that was insulting to
anybody,'' said Perry O. Hooper, GOP national committeeman from
Alabama. ``I have found nobody that was concerned.''
   Hooper, like several other Republicans gathering for the party's
annual summer meeting, said that when he read the memo he
interpreted it as a description of Foley's position on issues, not a
reflection on his personal life.
   On the other hand, Richard M. Rosenbaum, the national
committeeman from New York, said, ``I find what happened to be very
embarrassing and regrettable.''
   Asked whether the incident would be damaging to Atwater,
Rosenbaum said, ``I don't know. It's still a little early to get a
real consensus.''
   President Bush said in a speech to a party fund-raising dinner
Wednesday night that Atwater is ``doing a great job.'' The president
made no reference to the Foley memo.
   The memo depicted Foley as a liberal and compared his voting
record to that of Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., an acknowledged
homosexual. Mark Goodin, an aide to Atwater, resigned after saying
he wrote the memo, which bore the heading, ``Tom Foley: Out of the
Liberal Closet.''
   Some Democrats have asked Bush to fire Atwater from his party
post.
   Jennifer Dunn, the Republican national committeewoman from
Foley's home state of Washington, said she had received ``very few
calls'' about the memo.
   ``It was a very unfortunate thing, but I think it turned into a
media issue and a Democratic issue,'' Ms. Dunn said.
   Elsie H. Hillman, committeewoman from Pennsylvania, said, ``I
guess I'm very naive; I would not, if it hadn't been written up and
hadn't had such a violent explosion, I probably would not have made
any connection with that.''
   Mrs. Hillman said she believes Atwater's position is safe, noting
that the president supports him and has said he believes Atwater's
denial that he knew about the memo.
   William M. Taylor, GOP committeeman from Florida, said, ``I don't
know of anybody who thinks he (Atwater) is in trouble.''
   ``It probably shouldn't have been said in retrospect, but my
hindsight is always 20-20,'' Taylor said.
   Abraham, who is chairman of the organization of Midwestern
Republican state chairmen, said his group met Thursday ``and the
comments were all favorable'' to Atwater.
   ``I think everybody agrees it was inappropriate and I think the
proper actions were taken and Mark Goodin resigned and that's the
end of it,'' the Michigan chairman said.
   Donald B. Cox, national committeeman from Indiana, said
Republicans in his state were not concerned about the issue and, ``I
think it's more of a Washington thing.''
</TEXT>
