<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-15 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASPER, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If any firemen are worried about whether they
are able to grow a beard to participate in the city's centennial
celebration, they can save face by citing a department policy.
   Beards remain forbidden but the department has relaxed its
mustache policy to allow neatly groomed handlebar mustaches until
Dec. 31, Chief Doug MacDonald has ruled.
   A firefighter would have difficulty sealing his air mask when
wearing a beard, MacDonald said.
   Organizers of the 100th anniversary celebration have threatened
to levy ``fines'' against beardless men. The chief said no
firefighters requested permission to grow beards, but one or two
asked if the city would pay the fine.
   ``My response to that was, as I understand it, it's facial hair,
and we have a mustache policy. Therefore they shouldn't be fined,''
McDonald said.
   The chief said he will ``attempt to come up with a handlebar
mustache'' in keeping with his new policy.
   Police Chief Fred Rainguet has allowed beards, but if they don't
meet his standards, the offending officer may be called before a
Beard Review Board.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NATICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenneth Dumas believes he has gone where no
collector of ``Star Trek'' memorabilia has gone before.
   This was no five-year mission, as the prologue of the television
show used to say. When Dumas was 9, he began to seek out and explore
the galaxy of toys, posters, comic books and other spinoffs that
enterprising business people created for science fiction fans.
   Fifteen years later, the 24-year-old state-employed mapmaker says
he may have the largest personal stockpile of ``Star Trek''
memorabilia on this planet.
   ``I haven't found one person who has beaten it,'' Dumas said.
   He figures he has about 32,000 items, the most prized being a
fully operational ``Star Trek'' pinball machine. Remember the
hand-held communicators Kirk and Spock used when exploring planets?
Dumas has seven, as well as a medical scanner like the one used by
Dr. McCoy.
   Dumas has 300 paperback adventures in assorted editions and a
video library of all but 11 of the 79 TV episodes. But he is not
fond of the second-generation ``Star Trek'' television series, the
current movie sequel or the conventions held by ``trekkers.''
   ``I classify myself as a `Star Trek' memorabilia collector,'' he
said. ``I don't wear Spock ears and the costumes and go to
conventions and look stupid.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's nothing unlucky about the number
13 to the Lehman family, especially in June.
   Howard Lehman was born June 13. So was his father, Jerry.
   And now, as if there weren't enough cakes to bake this time of
year, Allison Lauren Lehman was born Tuesday, the third-generation
with the same birth date.
   ``My father-in-law said to me this morning, `OK, you have 18
hours to have the baby,''' Denise Lehman said after giving birth
four days ahead of schedule.
   ``I'd almost forgotten about my birthday,'' said her husband,
Howard. ``All my efforts and thoughts were concentrated on the baby.
It's a great birthday present.''
