<FIRST>r a AM-HotHouse     06-15 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hot House,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Removal of Radioactive House Cost $11.6 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSDOWNE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price tag is millions more than first
predicted, but a 10-month cleanup has removed the last vestiges of a
radioactive house contaminated decades ago by an enterprising
professor, officials said Thursday.
   The federal government said Thursday that it cost at least $11.6
million to tear down the suburban Philadelphia house and two
neighboring garages and haul the contaminated debris, along with
4,000 tons of radioactive soil, to a burial site for toxic waste in
Utah.
   ``I think that's the end of it,'' said Victor J. Janosik of the
Environmental Protection Agency. ``We're all cleaned up out there
and we're just doing restoration now.''
   The restoration includes the rebuilding of the two garages and
driveways also destroyed as the cleanup effort, and cost, expanded.
   At first, officials thought they could clean up the site for
about $2 million, but the first written estimate compiled by the EPA
expanded that to $4.5 million. The cost continued to grow as the
true extent of the contamination became known, Janosik said.
   ``We anticipated that most of the contamination would be within
one foot of the soil; in places we were going down to as much as 11
feet,'' Janosik said.
   Contractors began pulling apart the house in August 1988. It was
contaminated from the mid-1920s to the mid-'40s by a University of
Pennsylvania physics professor who used his basement to pack needles
with radium for sale to doctors and hospitals. The radium needles
were used to treat cancer.
   The house was placed on the EPA's Superfund list in 1985 _ the
only private residence to make the list _ after a cleanup in the
1960s failed to decontaminate it.
</TEXT>
