<FIRST>u w AM-FactoryUse     06-15 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Use,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Use Edges Down in May, Easing Inflation Worries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operating rate for U.S. factories continued
to ease last month, the government reported Thursday, and economists
said the slower pace so far this year should continue to cool
inflationary pressures.
   The Federal Reserve said the operating rate in May was 83.8
percent, 0.3 percentage points below April's 84.1 percent. The May
rate matched the rate in March, which had declined 0.1 percentage
point from February. Rates peaked in December and January at 84.3
percent, a 10-year high.
   ``This is telling us that the economy still has plenty of room to
run and the inflationary pressures are going to be cooling off,''
said Maury N. Harris, chief economist at Paine Webber in New York.
   The report ``should relieve concerns about too high a utilization
leading to inflation,'' agreed S. Jay Levy of Levy Economic
Forecasts in Chappaqua, N.Y., adding that the general pattern also
``should erase the fears of a too serious slowdown.''
   The steady increase in operating rates last year had caused
economists to worry about accompanying inflationary pressures. The
closer U.S. industry gets to full operating capacity, the greater
difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading to
shortages and price increases.
   Until recently, the Fed had been pushing up interest rates in an
attempt to cool those inflationary pressures without slowing growth
so much that the economy slides into a recession.
   ``It's (the slowing operating rate) consistent with the Fed's
soft landing scenario,'' said economist Cynthia Latta of Data
Resources in Lexington, Mass. ``Certainly some of the pressure on
the productive capacity is easing and that should translate into
less upward pressure on prices.''
   Last month's operating rate of 83.8 percent was up from 82.9
percent a year earlier.
   The operating rate fell 0.3 percentage points to 84.0 percent at
manufacturing plants, returning to the March operating level. Prior
to April, the rate had declined since it peaked at 84.7 in January.
   Analysts generally consider an operating rate of 85 percent or
above as an indication of inflationary pressures.
   The rate at factories producing durable goods, big ticket items
expected to last more than three years, fell from 82.8 percent in
April to 82.5 percent in May, reflecting decreases in most
categories.
   The rate at factories producing non-durable goods edged down from
86.3 percent to 86.0 percent last month.
   In another report Thursday, the central bank said industrial
production was unchanged in May after a 0.6 percent hike in April.
Production had edged up 0.1 percent in March after falling 0.2
percent in February, the first decline in a year.
   The Fed's industrial production index stood at 141.4 percent of
its 1977 base, 3.9 percent higher than a year ago and the same as
last month's index.
   Production fell 0.1 percent at manufacturing plants making both
durable and non-durable goods.
   Output at mines and oil wells rose 1.2 percent following a 1.0
percent jump in April. The May output was 1.4 percent higher than a
year ago.
   Production at utilities edged down 0.5 percent after remaining
flat in May.
</TEXT>
