<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Bombers     06-15 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Bombers,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>First B-2 Bomber Flies in the Next Few Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first B-2 bomber will fly in the next few
weeks, the deputy secretary of defense told Congress Thursday as he
defended the $500 million plane.
   Donald J. Atwood, the No. 2 official at the Pentagon, said
defense officials ``remain convinced the B-2 is a vital'' element
for the nation's security. ``As a deterrent, the B-2 is essential,''
he said.
   Atwood told the Senate Armed Services Committee that he and
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney recently visited the heavily secured
Northrop Corp. plant in Palmdale, Calif., where workers are
assembling the B-2 to make sure the project is moving forward
properly.
   ``The degree of quality control gives me great confidence,''
Atwood said, noting that the radar-evading bomber, also known as the
Stealth bomber, will be constructed with composite materials.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., the committee's chairman, told Atwood there
will be a great temptation in Congress to siphon money slated for
the B-2 for other programs that the Pentagon wants to eliminate to
save money in fiscal year 1990.
   Among the programs Cheney wants to kill in the spending year that
begins Oct. 1 are the Navy's F-14 Tomcat fighter and the Marine
Corps' V-22 Osprey aircraft. The Pentagon's proposed purchasing
program for that year is estimated at $69 billion.
   Atwood defended terminating some programs while spending money on
the B-2. Defense officials have proposed building 132 of those
bombers, eventually making three a month at a cost of $500 million
each, including research and development.
   Under questioning by Nunn and Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., Atwood
said the federal government has already committed to spend $22.4
billion on the B-2, including $15.5 billion for research and
development.
   ``When will it fly?'' Exon asked.
   ``Within the next two to three weeks,'' responded Atwood.
   Nunn also sought assurances the Defense Department would not use
money from a revolving contingency fund to correct problems on the
B-1B bomber without informing Congress. Three of the 100 bombers
already have crashed.
   Atwood, who said the Air Force estimates it will cost between
$700 million and $800 million to fix the electronic countermeasure
systems on the B-1Bs, gave Nunn the promise the senator wanted.
   On other issues, Atwood said:
   _ The Pentagon's management study, completed at the behest of
President Bush, has been sent to the White House. It will probably
be forwarded to Congress shortly, he said.
   _ Defense officials are working with contractors to ensure they
establish monitoring system designed to counter any fraud or
corruption. The new controls stem from investigation of Pentagon
procurement practices known as the ``Ill Wind'' investigation.
   Nunn said that once prosecutors have completed their probe,
Congress will schedule hearings to look into the purchasing system.
Atwood did not know how much longer the ``Ill Wind'' investigation
will continue.
   The investigation began three years ago. So far, more than a
dozen people and contractors have either pleaded guilty or been
convicted in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
