<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     06-15 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Of Radical Students Clash With Riot Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of radical students fought
riot police with rocks and firebombs Thursday to protest a
government crackdown on campus activism and dissident movements.
   Students clashed with police in front of at least four
universities. No injuries or arrests were reported.
   Fierce fighting broke out at Yonsei and Sogang universities in
western Seoul, where about 2,000 students, many hurling rocks and
firebombs, tried to march into the streets.
   Police, armed with padded fatigues, helmets and shields, blocked
the students by hurling back rocks. They did not use tear gas.
   Smaller clashes also were reported at two other universities in
the capital.
   The students criticized a continuing crackdown by President Roh
Tae-woo's government on dissident movements and demanded that
student leaders be allowed to take part in a world youth festival in
the North Korean capital of Pyongyang on July 1-8.
   Sogang students were furious about a police raid on their school
last week to seize propaganda materials for the Pyongyang festival.
Sogang, a Jesuit school, is the headquarters of radical students
campaigning to go to the sports and cultural event.
   Seoul officials accused communist North Korea of using the
festival to promote dissident activity in South Korea.
   The Koreas have been bitter rivals since their land was divided
in 1945 at the end of World War II. They fought the Korean War in
1950-53.
</TEXT>
