<FIRST>r w AM-HUDProbe     06-15 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Wants All HUD Offices Checked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh ordered
prosecutors Thursday to check all local offices of the Department of
Housing and Urban Development for possible cases of fraud and
embezzlement.
   The attorney general's order came in the wake of mounting
evidence of massive fraud of HUD by real estate agents who handle
the proceeds from the sale of government-owned houses obtained
through mortgage foreclosures.
   Thornburgh ordered the nation's U.S. attorneys to review the
operation of the property-sale programs in the local and regional
HUD offices within their 94 jurisdictions, said David Runkel, chief
Justice Department spokesman.
   The increased Justice Department involvement is something Housing
Secretary Jack Kemp ``has been actively seeking,'' said Mary
Brunette, a top aide to the secretary.
   She said HUD auditors already checking agency operations around
the country ``would be involved in every possible aspect of a
Justice Department investigation and would be fully cooperative and
would welcome the assistance.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said President
Bush is ``confident that Secretary Kemp's going to get it (HUD)
straightened out, to turn the management around and cooperate
fully.''
   At least three U.S. attorneys already are investigating alleged
fraud by real estate agents. In Fort Worth, Texas, a federal grand
jury has charged a real estate agent with stealing $2.5 million from
the sale of 55 HUD-forclosed homes in the Dallas area.
   In addition, the U.S. attorney in Baltimore is investigating a
Maryland real estate agent who has acknowledged keeping $5.5 million
from the proceeds of HUD-owned properties.
   Marilyn Louise Herrell, nicknamed ``Robin HUD'' by investigators,
has claimed in interviews that she gave most of the money to
charitable organizations to help the poor.
   Federal authorities in Washington are searching for a local
attorney who acted as a HUD escrow agent before he disappeared last
year. Investigators say $3 million may be missing.
   Four officials in HUD's Washington field office, including the
director, were recently placed on leave with pay by Kemp.
   HUD auditors also have been sent to several cities, including
Denver, Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles and New Orleans to check
records of the property sales.
   Real estate agents who represent HUD at the property closings are
supposed to turn over the proceeds of the sales to HUD. But auditors
have determined that money is not being returned to the agency.
   HUD officials, meanwhile, confirmed a report in Thursday's
editions of The Washington Post that they had asked the U.S.
attorney in Denver to investigate allegations that a HUD accountant
in Denver manipulated an automated bill-paying system to transfer $1
million into his personal bank account.
   Justice Department officials in Washington declined to comment on
the case.
</TEXT>
