<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-RandomTesting     06-15 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Random Testing,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Looking At Adding Alcohol Checks To Random Drug Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department is considering
expanding its drug-testing program to include random checks for
alcohol abuse among 4 million transportation workers, Secretary
Samuel Skinner told Congress Thursday.
   The transportation secretary also said he would recommend that
President Bush veto a House anti-drug bill if passed. He said the
measure, which covers only railroad workers, would require the
administration to start over on a drug-testing program it has
already ordered.
   Skinner made the announcement on alcohol testing before a Senate
committee considering its version of legislation to require random
drug and alcohol testing throughout the aviation, railroad,
shipping, pipeline, trucking and mass transit industries.
   The Transportation Department last November ordered drug testing
programs in private transportation industries beginning at the end
of this year, but the programs face several court challenges. The
Supreme Court has approved some drug testing but has yet to act on
random testing.
   The proposal to put random testing into law brought general
support from transportation industry representatives and strong
objections from groups representing the employees who would be
tested. The Senate passed a random testing law in both 1987 and 1988
but the House failed to accept it.
   ``I have decided that we must step forward and address the issue
of alcohol misuse in transportation now,'' Skinner told the Senate
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
   The secretary said he has directed department lawyers to prepare
proposed rules that would allow officials to explore ``what more
needs to be done and how best to do it.''
   Skinner said a Coast Guard program of mandatory post-accident
alcohol testing for the maritime industry begins in December, but he
said testing rules that would cover all of transportation raise
complex questions and should be drafted carefully.
   ``A lot more thought needs to go into the idea of extending
random testing to alcohol, and I am making it a high priority to get
needed information,'' he said. He noted, for instance, that alcohol
is legal while current rules apply to illegal drugs.
   Skinner said the House version of the anti-drug bill would
mandate random alcohol test rules just 90 days after enactment of
the bill. ``I look to the long term, and I know that to develop a
program that will achieve its objective and withstand legal
challenge requires more care and consideration,'' he said.
   Committee Chairman Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., said alcohol and
illegal drug use by transporation workers cannot be ignored, saying
that drugs or alcohol caused railroad accidents once every 12{ days
last year.
   ``Call it intimidation. Call it whatever you will,'' he said.
``But the fact is that random testing is the only method we have to
reasonably ensure that transportation employees will not use drugs
on the job.''
   Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, sponsor of the House drug bill, said
Skinner's decision to explore alcohol testing was a change from his
department's position that it was not needed.
   He said the anti-drug bill requiring random testing of railroad
workers has bipartisan support and said Skinner wants anti-drug
measures left to the ``whims of the transportation secretary.''
   Michael O'Connell, lawyer for a national association of
owner-operated heavy trucks, said drivers oppose random testing
because ``millions of innocent drivers will be victimized by the
regulations.''
   O`Connell introduced Sandy Craig of Anderson, Ind., who owns and
drives a single truck with her husband, as an example of a driver
who would be subjected to urine testing, possibly in the presence of
the person conducting the test.
   Mrs. Craig, interviewed after the hearing, said she opposes
roadside random testing because it would delay her trips, ``and I
think the procedure proposed is humiliating.''
</TEXT>
