<FIRST>r a AM-MoneyWasher     06-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Washer,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Hotel Coinwasher Feted At 85th Birthday Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veteran money-launderer Arnold Batliner
celebrated his 85th birthday Thursday, unworried that the FBI might
get on to him. Actually, the pint-sized octogenarian washes all the
change used at the St. Francis Hotel.
   Batliner estimated, with a computer assist, that he has washed
$15.5 million in coins at the hotel over 27 years _ more than a
million pounds of change since 1962.
   Coin-washing has been a tradition at the hotel since 1936, when
silver dollars were in circulation.
   ``The coins were washed as a service for the ladies who
frequented the hotel and wore white gloves which were soiled by the
dirty money,'' said hotel spokesman Don Blum.
   ``We all love you,'' Robert Wilhelm, the hotel's managing
director, told Batliner at a champagne birthday party. The staff
sang ``Happy Birthday,'' tossed down bubbly and snacks, and gave
Batliner a 19-inch color TV.
   And there was a birthday cake decorated with a large candy
replica of a silver dollar.
   Batliner, whose workplace is a security-tight room deep in the
bowels of the famous hotel on Union Square, beamed when reporters
and cameras recorded the scene. Like Batliner, the hotel is also 85
years old this year.
   When the coins come out of the ancient Sahara Silver Burnishing
machine in use at the hotel since 1936, they are as bright as the
day they were minted, a ``touch of class'' the St. Francis says.
   The machine uses buckshot and a special soap compound to wash
each load for 90 minutes before the coins go into a rinse of boiling
water, are dried, recounted and wrapped.
   Batliner said he enjoys his work, reduced to a half-day since he
was hospitalized a few years ago after a mugging at his doorstep.
   ``I'm half-retired, you can say,'' he chortled.
   He said he has one complaint about taking on those dirty coins
delivered by banks in sacks of $1,000.
   ``Sometimes there's chewing gum in them,'' he muttered, but he
added with some pride that he never encountered a coin he couldn't
clean.
</TEXT>
