<FIRST>r w AM-FCC-AmateurRadio 1stLd-Writethru a0652 06-15 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FCC-Amateur Radio, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0652,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Stands By Decision to Allocate Frequency Band</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update with ARRL reaction, INSERTS three grafs after 2nd
graf bgng ``The commission's ... ''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Thursday reaffirmed its decision to allocate to land mobile radio
service a frequency band that previously had been available to
amateur radio operators.
   The commission's August 1988 action had been appealed by the
American Radio Relay League and about 700 other amateur radio
organizations and individual ham radio operators.
   David Sumner, ARRL's executive vice president, said the league
plans further appeals in federal court.
   ``The commission's action today is a disappointment, but not a
surprise,'' he said. ``The entire history of this proceeding is one
of the commission ignoring evidence that did not support its
preconceived position.''
   Sumner added that ``now it will be up to the federal Court of
Appeals to determine whether, by so doing, the commission
overstepped its bounds.''
   At Thursday's meeting, the FCC stood by its decision to maintain
the 216-220 MHz band for maritime mobile communications, allocate
the 220-222 MHz band _ which earlier had been available to amateurs
_ to land mobile service and allocate the 222-225 MHz band
exclusively to amateur service.
   A number of other frequency bands also are currently allocated to
amateur radio operators.
   In affirming the previous action, members of the commission said
they were particularly sensitive to the needs an concerns expressed
by amateurs, particularly their requirements for emergency
communications.
   The commissioners said allocation of the 220-222 MHz band to land
mobile service was driven by the need to provide frequencies for
development of spectrum-efficient land mobile technology.
   In other actions Thursday, the FCC:
   _Proposed amending its rules to permit mobile stations in
aviation services to use 40 reallocated channels in the 136-137 MHz
band.
   The commission called for allotting 20 channels for aeronautical
en route services and 15 channels for air traffic control purposes,
with the remaining five channels to be held temporarily in reserve
for future aeronautical advisory and automatic weather observation
services.
   _Amended its rules to expand the use of mobile service
frequencies for tone signaling, which is used for ripping alarms to
indicate equipment malfunctions, monitoring and changing the
operational status of equipment, as well as detecting intruders and
hazardous conditions.
</TEXT>
