<FIRST>r i AM-Chess     06-15 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chess,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karpov in Unexpected Draw at World Cup Tournament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly Karpov of the Soviet Union
escaped with a draw against British grandmaster Nigel Short in a
ninth-round game to maintain his lead in the World Cup chess
tournament Thursday.
   The outcome caused a sensation among grandmasters watching the
duel as Karpov, the former world champion, was in a seemingly
hopeless position when the encounter was adjourned after a 60-move
struggle from a Queen's gambit on Tuesday.
   ``Unbelievable!'' shouted Yugoslav grandmaster Ljubomir
Ljubojevic as he watched the drama unfold on a monitor in the press
room adjoining the tournament hall. ``Karpov has a thousand lives.''
   Short, the only player to defeat Karpov this year, was at a loss
for an explanation.
   ``Seven moves into the resumption, I missed a winning
continuation,'' he said. ``I don't know what came over me. I had
analyzed it so well, but Karpov took a completely different line
from what I had prepared.''
   ``He played without any threats, just coordinating his pieces.
Maybe that's why I went wrong,'' Short said.
   Karpov agreed.
   ``Nigel should have floored me 10 times over, even though it was
not so easy as some of the others thought,'' he said. ``But when he
wasted his best chance, I could easily even out. I was lucky.''
   The extra half-point boosted Karpov's score to six points from
the eight games he has played so far and kept him on top of the
standings with a half-point lead over Jan Timman of the Netherlands
and Britain's John Nunn, who tallied 5{ points after nine games.
   It also kept alive Karpov's chances of catching world champion
Gary Kasparov of the Soviet Union in the race for the world cup. The
final cup tournament is in August.
   Two other adjourned games from the previous rounds in the
$100,000 Rotterdam event were completed Thursday.
   Jaan Ehlvest of the Soviet Union and Lajos Portisch of Hungary
drew their adjourned eighth-round game, as did Jesus Nogueiras of
Cuba and Soviet grandmaster Arthur Yusupov.
   The 11th round of the tournament continues Friday.
</TEXT>
