<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CivilRights-Reaction     06-15 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Civil Rights-Reaction,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights and women's rights advocates,
protesting a series of Supreme Court decisions they say are turning
back the clock on racial progress, accused the court Thursday of
engaging in ``redneck justice.''
   The court's latest ruling, although a partial victory for
minorities, touched off a storm of angry rhetoric because it comes
on the heels of recent decisions erecting roadblocks for
anti-discrimination efforts.
   Molly Yard, president of the National Organization for Women,
said conservatives on the court ``again revealed themselves to be
hostile and insensitive to the progress of the last 20 years.
Redneck justice meted out with country club manners is no less
painful than the real thing.''
   The court, by a 5-4 vote Thursday, barred the use of a key 1866
civil rights law to fight racial harassment. But the justices,
voting unanimously, did uphold use of the law to sue private
individuals and to fight other forms of discrimination.
   John Buchanan of the liberal People for the American Way said,
``It's a sad commentary on the state of the court's general outlook
on civil rights that today's decision must be greeted with a measure
of relief.''
   He and others said minorities and women now must turn to Congress
for help.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., urged President Bush to join
Congress in proposing bills to reverse the high court rulings.
   ``Taken separately, each of these retreats would be a source of
genuine concern,'' he said. ``Together they are a serious threat to
the 35 years of progress we have achieved toward a better and fairer
society.''
   Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., chairman of a House Judiciary
subcommittee on civil and constitutional rights, warned that a court
majority led by appointees of former President Reagan intends to
carry out ``Reagan's unfinished agenda to reverse'' years of
progress for minorities and women.
   Edwards said Thursday's ruling sends this message to minorities:
``Be thankful you have a job but too bad if you experience
discrimination once you're hired.''
   Benjamin Hooks and Ralph Neas of the Leadership Conference on
Civil Rights called the current Supreme Court term, due to end
within two weeks, ``a disaster for all those committed to equal
employment opportunity.''
   Julius Chambers of the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund
said the latest ruling means ``employers who do not want blacks on
their work force can simply hire blacks and harass them on the job
until they quit.''
   Women's rights groups were equally alarmed.
   ``In several rulings ..., a slim majority of the court has turned
back the clock on advances which so many worked long and hard to
achieve,'' said Marcia Greenberger of the National Women's Law
Center.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
