<FIRST>u i AM-Hostages 1stLd-Writethru a0639 06-15 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0639,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede: SIDON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Belgian Hostage Freed in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with Cools' arrival in Damascus,
other. ADDS LaserPhoto number. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI1</HEAD>
<HEAD>By LOUIS FARES</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Belgian physician Jan Cools was freed
Thursday after 13 months as a hostage in Lebanon and came to
Damascus, bound for home.
   ``I would like to thank everybody who helped in getting me
released,'' the 32-year-old relief worker said earlier Thursday in
Sidon, his eyes filled with tears, upon being freed in that southern
Lebanon port city.
   ``I feel very happy to be free. I feel very tired.''
   He said his captors treated him well.
   Cools thanked ``especially Col. Moammar Gadhafi for getting me
released.'' Gadhafi leads the radical North African Arab nation of
Libya.
   The physician worked for the Norwegian humanitarian organization
NORWAC and was kidnapped May 21, 1988.
   Upon his arrival in the Syrian capital, Cools was immediately
taken to the home of Belgian Ambassador Andre Vokaer and declined to
make any statements to reporters.
   Damascus airport officials said a Belgian military transport
plane arrived at 11:30 p.m. with Cools' parents and two doctors
aboard. Embassy officials said the plane was to fly Cools home later.
   Belgian Foreign Trade Minister Robert Urbain, who drove with
Cools from Lebanon, said Cools will stay in Damascus for a few days.
   Fourteen other foreigners _ including nine Americans _ are held
hostage in Lebanon, most by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems. Three others
are missing.
   The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   In Sidon, Cools spoke with reporters in the apartment of Mustafa
Saad, whose predominantly Sunni Moslem militia has controlled that
city 25 miles south of Beirut since Lebanon's civil war broke out in
1975.
   Younis Amran of the Fatah-Revolutionary Council, a Palestinian
guerrilla group led by terrorist Abu Nidal, sat near Cools as the
freed relief worker spoke. Cools thanked Saad for ``efforts that
facilitated my release.''
   Amran said the group calling itself Soldiers of Justice, which
claimed responsibility for abducting Cools, freed him at Gadhafi's
request following ``efforts by us,'' and he was turned over to Saad.
   An aide to Saad said Urbain and the minister's chief aide, Robert
Willermain, drove from Damascus to Saad's residence especially for
the release. Speaking in French, Cools said before leaving Sidon
that his captors told him Thursday morning to ``take a shower.''
   ``I took one, they bought me the new clothes that I am wearing
now and told me I will be released upon Col. Gadhafi's mediation.
They brought me here.''
   He was dressed in a beige shirt and trousers.
   On Wednesday, the Soldiers of Justice issued a statement saying
he would be freed in response to an appeal from Gadhafi. It said
negotiations were conducted by the Abu Nidal faction.
   ``We hope this goodwill gesture will awaken the conscience of
Western nations to support the causes of the oppressed, especially
the people of Palestine, who are subjected to daily killings and
destruction,'' it said.
   There has been widespread speculation that Abu Nidal's group
kidnapped Cools, but spokesmen for the organization have denied it.
   Police say the Soldiers of Justice is a name used by the
terrorist's followers.
</TEXT>
