<FIRST>r w AM-PentagonBudget     06-15 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon Budget,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Orders Attack on Gimmicks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has ordered an
internal attack on budget gimmicks used by the Pentagon to make its
five-year spending plan seem small enough to confirm to President
Bush's decisions, a pleased congressional critic disclosed Thursday.
   The special review is expected to slash at least $45 billion from
the spending projections for the fiscal years 1990 through 1994,
even though the Bush administration already has agreed to cut
Pentagon budget requests by $65 billion during the period.
   The two figures are not additive. The $45 billion in projected
cuts would offset elimination of the accounting tricks without
changing the five-year total, $1.6 trillion.
   Cheney's order was disclosed by Rep. Andy Ireland, R-Fla., in a
letter he released from the General Accounting Office updating the
results of a critical study presented to Congress on May 10.
   The GAO update states that Cheney has ordered a ``program
execution review'' with the objective of ``elimination of negative
planning wedges in the five-year defense plan (and) close
consideration of the affordability of currently proposed major
weapons programs.''
   The so-called negative planning wedges are deductions used to
balance some $45 billion worth of spending requests that exceed the
Bush administration's latest five-year plan.
   For example, the Pentagon plan currently contains a negative
figure of $21.7 billion derived from its historical experience that
2 percent or 3 percent of procurement funds ultimately are not spent
because of program changes. GAO said this deduction should not be
included.
   While the special review involves annual budgets that would
undergo extensive revision in any case before finally being
submitted to Congress, it is nonetheless significant because it
could force the immediate demise of programs that the military
wanted to keep alive on its wish list.
   Ireland hailed Cheney's move, saying the defense chief was
showing ``a real commitment to bringing Pentagon spending into line
with fiscal reality.''
   ``While Secretary Cheney makes fundamental changes in the
Pentagon's planning process, Congress also needs a healthy dose of
self-discipline and foresight,'' Ireland added.
   ``Congress must put aside parochial concerns and focus only on
those programs that contribute to a strong and efficient national
defense.''
   The GAO study released last month strongly castigated the Defense
Department for providing Congress a five-year defense plan that
``might be close to'' being worthless. Charles Bowsher, the head of
the agency, said the plan would require at least $147 billion more
than the Pentagon conceded would be needed.
   Especially troubling, Bowsher testified, was the fact the
Pentagon's spending plan exceeded President Bush's own budget plan
by $45 billion.
   Bowsher told the panel that ``since the mid-1980s, the
department's five-year defense planning has been fiscally
unrealistic. More weapons were being planned and developed than
could be produced in an economic manner or supported once they were
produced.''
   Congress has approved $290.2 billion in spending authority for
the Pentagon this fiscal year and is expected to approve a request
of $295.6 billion for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
