<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-SpecialArts     06-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Special Arts,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Wants to End Discrimination Against the Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush promised Thursday to push to end
discrimination against disabled people and increase access for them
as he hosted a festival at the White House for handicapped people
with artistic talents.
   ``You're all well on your way to the kind of life that I want to
see for every American _ a life of independence and opportunity and
productive involvement in our mainstream. And that means a
commitment on society's part to end discrimination, to increase
access and opportunity in our schools, on the job and in every
aspect of our society,'' Bush told a gathering of a few hundred
young people on the White House lawn.
   The White House event was sponsored by the Very Special Arts
organization, which is holding a weeklong international festival in
Washington to recognize the accomplishments of the physically and
mentally disabled in the areas of music, dance, drama and creative
arts.
   Bush and his wife Barbara sat in the front row for a show emceed
by game show host Monty Hall and featuring performances by Kenny
Rogers, the Gallaudet Dance Company from the Gallaudet University
for the deaf, and a 14-year-old blind Thai boy who once was a street
begger and now sings in eight languages.
   The boy, Phongsak Muenchanai, sang ``We Are The World,'' and a
rousing ditty in Japanese. He then called the president to the stage
asking to shake his hand. ``I would like to know the difference
between the hand of the president of the United States and a blind
boy like me,'' he said.
   Bush said the boy's accomplishment ``tells us all there's no
limit to how far we can go or what we can achieve.''
   ``You guys don't let any disabilities stand in your way,'' he
told the gathering. ``So it's up to us to make sure that
discrimination doesn't stop you. And federal law must protect
individuals with disabilities and I'm going to do my level best to
see that it does.''
   The Very Special Arts is an organization founded in 1974 by Jean
Kennedy Smith, sister of the late President Kennedy, to coordinate
arts programs for children and adults with mental and physical
handicaps.
   The organization is an educational affiliate of the John F.
Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts. Its international festival
this week brings together artists from 52 countries.
</TEXT>
