<FIRST>r w AM-China-Visas     06-15 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Visas,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>188 Given Permission to Visit United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy in Beijing and four other
consulate offices in China granted visas Thursday to more than 100
Chinese to go to the United States, the State Department reported.
   Another 114 applicants were turned down for a variety of reasons,
the most likely one being that they apparently intended to use
temporary visas to try to remain permanently in this country.
   Additionally, 350 applicants were asked to return to U.S.
diplomatic offices to have their situations reviewed. Many of them
were sent home because U.S. officials did not have enough time to
interview them by the end of the day.
   The visas were issued by the U.S. Embassy in Beijing and the
consulates in Shanghai, Guangzhou, Chengdu and Shenyang. The embassy
and the Shanghai consulate had suspended processing while assisting
Americans in leaving China and then resumed on Wednesday.
   Almost all the visas approved were for brief stays. They required
the approval of Chinese authorities, who issued exit permits, and a
knowledge of English.
   An exact count was not available because the Beijing Embassy
reported that of 138 applicants interviewed on Thursday ``a
majority'' were approved.
   In Shanghai, 62 were approved, in Gunagzhou, formerly Canton, 15,
in Shenyang, ll, and in Chengdu, 2.
   There were no reports of interference with applicants by Chinese
security forces posted outside the U.S. diplomatic offices.
   But dissidents and other pro-democracy advocates sought by
Chinese authorities were unlikely to apply. They either would be
apprehended by security forces or denied the required exit permits.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the embassy
and consulates would process as many applicants as show up. The
staff at the embassy and the consulates was not reduced even though
other Americans were urged to leave China.
   There were no figures on how many applications were approved on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
