<FIRST>r w AM-Kemp-Drugs     06-15 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kemp-Drugs,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Says Rights to Be Respected in His Drive for Drug-Free Public
Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp, saying he seeks to
``remove the guilty and protect the needy,'' sought on Thursday to
reassure lawmakers that individual rights will be respected in his
drive for drug-free public housing.
   ``I will be equally tough for due process,'' Kemp told the House
Select Committee on Narcotics Abuse and Control in outlining his
agency's plan to rid public housing of drug dealers and users.
   Key provisions would speed drug-related evictions and seize
apartments of alleged dealers and users. Those elements have been
criticized by tenants' rights groups as not providing adequate legal
protection for the accused.
   ``As we aggressively pursue our objectives to eradicate drugs
from our housing programs we will not do so at the expense of
individual tenants' rights,'' he added in a written statement.
   He said his Department of Housing and Urban Development is
reviewing each state's judicial structure as it relates to eviction
to ensure individual rights are protected.
   HUD has granted exemptions from the agency's administrative
grievance procedures in evictions of alleged drug dealers and users
in public housing in Virginia, Massachuestts, New York and the
District of Columbia.
   Public housing managers said federal regulations which required
local government officials to allow tenants threatened with eviction
to appeal to agency administrative panels and then to courts slowed
evictions by as much as a year.
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., questioned how he would envision
handling the case of the possible eviction of a single mother or
grandmother living in public housing with a drug-selling teen-ager
she feared.
   ``You cannot have one policy that will cover every single
condition in public housing,'' Kemp said, adding eviction actions
would have to be reviewed on a case-by-case basis.
   However, Kemp said he wanted to give public housing authorities
the power to ``to remove the guilty and protect the needy.''
   Kemp also cited the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 as legislation
that has hampered his anti-drug efforts.
   The law makes it illegal for any recipient of federal money to
discriminate based on ``mental and physical impairments,'' and
includes drug and alcohol dependent persons among those defined as
being legally handicapped.
   As a result, Kemp said public housing which gives priority to the
disabled would have to include such people.
   ``In my view the drug user should not be put at the top of the
waiting list for public housing,'' said Kemp.
   Sen. Dan Coats, R-Ind., has introduced legislation to exclude
drug addicts and alcohol-dependent persons from those protected by
the 1973 law.
   Other aspects of HUD's plan plan for drug-free public housing
would tighten security, reclaim vacant units and deny access to drug
dealers, encourage resident management and homeownership, establish
an anti-drug hotline at HUD for residents to anonymously report
drug-related activities, terminate housing assistance of those
convicted of drug crimes and provide money for athletic programs in
public housing.
   Kemp offered no figures on the total cost of the program.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., head of the
Appropriations subcommittee on HUD and independent agencies, told a
meeting of the Council of Large Public Housing Authorities the
secretary's anti-drug effort was initiated to show that the
government wanted to be a good landlord.
   ``The point has been made. Now the point has to be turned into
dollars,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SovietAlcoholics     06-15 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Alcoholics,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recovering Soviet Alcoholics Ending U.S. Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Moscow cinematographer named Victor, sober
now for nine months, says he's undergoing a personal ``perestroika''
thanks to the small but growing fellowship of Alcoholics Anonymous
in the Soviet Union.
   ``Perestroika is a very popular word now in my country,'' he
said, referring to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
restructuring the Soviet economy. ``We alcoholics can restructure
ourselves and become better, happier persons. I am rebuilding my
life.''
   Victor, 42, who followed A.A. tradition in asking that his last
name not be used, is among three recovering Soviet alcoholics who
are ending a two-month tour of the United States. They held a news
conference Thursday at the National Press Club.
   Since they arrived April 10 in New York, Victor and his
companions, Sasha, 43, and Volodya, 37, have attended scores of A.A.
meetings from Massachusetts to Texas, visited alcoholism treatment
centers and met with such celebrities as Betty Ford and Kitty
Dukakis, who also are recovering alcoholics.
   On Monday, they met with President Bush's physician, Dr. Burton
Lee, at the White House. They'll end their tour this weekend in
Atlanta with a side trip to Plains, Ga., where they will attend a
Sunday school class led by former President Carter.
   The tour was organized by the Rev. J.W. Canty, an Episcopal
priest from New York who is chairman of the non-profit Soviet-U.S.
Joint Conference on Alcoholism, Drug Addiction and Peace in Moscow.
   Canty, who helped start the first A.A. meeting in the Soviet
capital in August 1987, told reporters that ``A.A. would have to
function underground if it weren't for the new, freer attitudes''
under Gorbachev's reform policies.
   The ``Moscow Beginners'' group of A.A. has about 40 members who
meet seven nights a week at various spots in the Soviet capital.
Small groups active in other Soviet cities bring total A.A.
membership to fewer than 100, Canty said.
   ``It's very small, but it's a beginning,'' Canty said. ``It's
working slowly but well. If you can save even one life, that's an
enormous contribution.''
   Alcoholics Anonymous, a 12-step program of recovery that stresses
spiritual growth and mutual support among members who share their
``experience, strength and hope,'' claimed about 835,500 members in
the United States last year, and more than 1.5 million members
worldwide.
   Canty went to Moscow in 1985, shortly after Gorbachev took office
and began a strict anti-alcoholism campaign. The Communist Party
newspaper Pravda estimated in November 1987 there are more than 4.5
million registered alcoholics in the Soviet Union, with 1 million of
them requiring compulsory care.
   Canty said the actual number of Soviet alcoholics probably ranges
from 10 million to 15 million. He said his efforts to encourage the
growth of Alcoholics Anonymous in that country have been made easier
by the personal support of Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, who
``showed great interest in our work.''
   The times and locations of A.A. meetings are routinely announced
on government-run TV and radio broadcasts. A Gorbachev aide once
informed Canty that the Soviet leader had read all the
Russian-language A.A. pamphlets circulated by Canty's office.
   Volodya, a Moscow factory machinist who drank two bottles of
vodka every day until he got sober 16 months ago, said alcoholics
still suffer a painful stigma in the Soviet Union.
   ``They are treated like the worst human beings,'' he said, while
in America ``they know it is a disease that is treatable, and even
famous people can confess to being recovering alcoholics.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-China     06-15 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-China,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Sees Danger to World if China Halts Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who is determined
to reform the Soviet Union, said Thursday it may be dangerous for
the world if reform stops in China, the other communist giant.
   ``I think all of us are very much concerned at what is happening
in China,'' he said. ``All of us want the process of deep reform not
to fail'' in such a large nation.
   ``That failure would be very dangerous for the entire process of
creating a healthy environment in the world,'' the Soviet president
told a news conference at the end of a four-day visit to West
Germany.
   Gorbachev expressed concern about events in China and said,
without being specific, that his government regretted ``some aspects
of what happened.''
   The comments were his most extensive on the subject since the
Congress of People's Deputies in Moscow passed a cautiously worded
resolution after the military crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators in Beijing two weeks ago.
   He praised at least some of the students, who he said wrote him
an interesting letter, but he made no mention of the violence used
on them.
   Estimates of the number of people killed range from a few hundred
by the government to about 3,000 by Chinese witnesses and Western
intelligence.
   When asked whether he shared the official Chinese view that the
students were counterrevolutionaries, Gorbachev did not reply
directly. The Soviet leader recalled that, during a visit to Beijing
last month after a 30-year rift with China, he said dialogue was the
way to resolve problems.
   After he left, ``the situation became rather grave,'' he said.
   ``I don't think we have full information'' on which to make an
assessment, and that dictated his ``balanced, serious position'' on
China, he said.
   Gorbachev said he received letters in which Chinese students
spoke out for reform.
   ``I cannot suspect these people of any evil intention,'' he said,
but there ``could be elements ... that took advantage of the
situation.''
   He did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
