<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAir-Corn     06-15 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air-Corn,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's Clean-Fuel Plan Would Boost Corn Prices, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The provision in President Bush's clean-air
package to require use of clean-fuel cars could boost corn prices as
much as 15 cents a bushel, an ethanol industry group said Thursday.
   Production of ethanol, which is made from corn, would rise from
850 million gallons to 1.1 billion gallons a year, the nation's
current production capacity, the Renewable Fuels Association
estimates.
   ``We're real encouraged by that,'' Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., a
leading advocate in Congress of alternative fuels, said in an
interview. ``I personally feel that (estimate) is quite
conservative. ''
   The clean-air program Bush unveiled Monday would require the sale
of a million clean-fuel cars in the nation's nine most polluted
areas by 1997.
   Those cars, which would be powered by methanol, ethanol or
natural gas, would produce fewer of the chemicals that cause ozone
pollution.
   ``Generally, we're very pleased with the president's
announcement,'' said Bob Dinneen, legislative director for the
Renewable Fuels Association. ``We think that it will greatly enhance
the potential for increased production and use of ethanol.''
   General Motors officials recently told Congress they are prepared
to recommend the use of ethanol in their automobiles as early as
next year, Daschle said.
   ``The automobile companies have seen this coming for some time
and they're prepared to address the challenge a lot more effectively
than we might otherwise give them credit,'' Daschle said.
</TEXT>
