<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     06-15 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Get Prison Terms for Beating Palestinian</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Settlers, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIRYAT MALAKI, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military judge gave four soldiers
prison terms of up to nine months Thursday for the beating of a
Palestinian who later died, and he called on the army to ``have the
courage to look in the mirror.''
   The judge, Col. Emanuel Gross, urged the military to bring to
trial officers who gave illegal orders that extended army policy of
beating Palestinians who were rioting to include those who were
arrested.
   The case focused national attention on the beating policy, which
drew fire from foreign governments and human rights organizations
after beatings by soldiers appeared on television newscasts abroad.
   Also Thursday, a 46-year-old man in the Gaza Strip was fatally
stabbed by fellow Palestinians who accused him of collaborating with
Israeli authorities, Israel radio and Arab sources said.
   Sixteen Palestinians were reported shot and wounded in clashes
with soldiers in the Gaza Strip and West Bank, including a
12-year-old boy shot in the pelvis in the Shati refugee camp in Gaza.
   Shlomo Franco, 42, an Israeli cameraman for the U.S. TV network
ABC was shot in the face with a plastic bullet by soldiers
dispersing Palestinian rioters in Ramallah, West Bank. He was
reported in good condition.
   The four members of the elite Givati Brigade were convicted of
brutality on May 25 but acquitted of manslaughter. Doctors testified
the 42-year-old victim, Hani Shami, died not from their blows but
from a later beating by other unidentified soldiers.
   Gross urged prosecutors to try officers who issued the beating
orders, saying: ``There won't be any value to this trial if we don't
do anything to enforce the law. We have to have the courage to look
in the mirror.''
   The army has said it did not plan to bring charges against the
brigade commander but did not make clear if it intended to charge
other officers.
   Gross said, ``The affair exposed in this case symbolizes perhaps
a breakdown in values which, if continued, would endanger the basic
values that are the true cultural heritage of our country.''
   After Thursday's sentencing, a brawl erupted outside the
courtroom when one defendant, Pvt. Ron Hakhel, 20, lunged at
photographers and TV camera crew.
   The defendants and several of their friends, including a military
policeman, brawled with photographers for almost 10 minutes. One
photographer emerged with a swollen eye.
   Hakhel, Pvt. Yitzhak Kibbudi, 20, and 1st Sgt. Yitzhak Adler, 21,
were sentenced to serve nine months in prison and given additional
nine-month suspended sentences and two years probation.
   Pvt. Ariyeh Luchato, 20, was given six months in prison, six more
months suspended and six months probation. The ruling noted he
participated in only part of the beating.
   The beating was administered after the victim was arrested last
Aug. 22 in the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya refugee camp.
   In Arab east Jerusalem Thursday, police seized files and papers
from a news service office run by Palestinian activist Sari
Nusseibeh, whom Israel has accused of being the Palestine Liberation
Organization paymaster for sustaining the uprising.
   The office, which provided information to foreign newspapers, was
ordered closed for two years.
