<FIRST>u w AM-Gregg 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gregg, 1st Ld -Writethru,a0698,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gregg Insists He Didn't Know About North's Efforts to Resupply Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 7-9 bgng: ``Meanwhile, Sen. Charles,'' with Robb
supporting Gregg.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ambassadorial nominee Donald Gregg, under
intense questioning by Senate Democrats, did not waver Thursday from
his insistence that he didn't know at the time about Oliver L.
North's secret efforts to resupply Nicaraguan rebels.
   Gregg, who served as then-Vice President Bush's national security
adviser, said that when he finally learned in December 1986 that his
associate, former CIA agent Felix Rodriguez, had been recruited to
help in North's operation, he felt betrayed.
   ``I was furious at North, I felt very let down by Felix and I
faulted myself for not putting the pieces together,'' Gregg told the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee which is weighing his nomination
to be ambassador to South Korea.
   Gregg's story, given under oath, did not shift in any major
respect from his testimony at an initial hearing last month.
   But Democrats insisted that Gregg could and should have known of
Rodriguez's involvement with North months earlier than he has
admitted and that he should have alerted Bush.
   They repeatedly challenged Gregg's credibility and said his
alleged lack of judgment disqualifies him for confirmation as an
ambassador.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., became the first committee
Democrat to say he may vote for Gregg.
   Robb said through a spokeswoman that ``barring evidence of lying
or perjury,'' he is leaning toward confirmation.
   ``He wants to review all of the evidence and he plans to make a
conscientious decision,'' said Julia Sutherland, Robb's press
secretary.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., spearheading the Gregg probe,
complained that the Bush administration inadequately responded to a
request for documents and declared: ``We are being stonewalled by
the administration.''
   But Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., Gregg's chief defender on the
panel, said the administration responded fully and quickly and said
of the investigation: ``It is in fact trying to harm the president.''
   ``I think Don has submitted to intense questioning and held up
very well,'' McConnell said.
   Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., told Gregg: ``It seems to me we have
now shifted from you having done something wrong, to your being
wrong in judgment. I think these hearings will have a reverse effect
and you will be confirmed as ambassador. ... I do not think these
hearings have uncovered any wrongdoing.''
   A vote on the nomination will be held Tuesday and committee
members said it is likely to be close.
   Rodriguez was sent to El Salvador in 1984 with Gregg's help to
assist the Salvadoran government to quell a leftist insurgency.
   Gregg contends he had no inkling until August 1986 that Rodriguez
had been recruited to assist North's Nicaraguan Contra resupply
operation.
   All he knew then, he testified, was that Rodriguez told him that
unidentified ``gunrunners'' were ``ripping off'' the Contras and
should be stopped.
   ``Felix told me that North had somehow put the gunrunners and the
Contras together,'' Gregg said.
   But he said he had discounted Rodriguez's characterization of the
situation as a potential ``Watergate'' because he was not told
enough to realize the dimensions of the situation.
   Gregg said he did not put what he knew ``into context'' until
four months later when he learned of the extent of North's operation.
   But Cranston said Gregg was literally surrounded by people who
knew about the resupply operation and Rodriguez's role in it.
   ``You're trying to convince us of an elaborate conspiracy to
prevent you from knowing,'' Cranston said.
   ``Why didn't you know?'' Cranston asked.
   ``I don't think everybody did know from the outset,'' Gregg
replied.
   Gregg said that as the involvement of North and Rodriguez became
clear in December 1986 he twice offered to resign from Bush's vice
presidential staff, and Bush refused to accept the resignations.
   Much of the testimony centered on North's heavily censored
notebooks. Cranston said North hasn't complied with a subpoena for
versions of his notebooks which he said contain ``repeated January
1985 references to Felix Rodriguez which suggest North's involvement
in Rodriguez briefings of the vice president.''
   Notes made available to the congressional Iran-Contra committees
contain brief mentions of Rodriguez and indications of a meeting
with Bush but other parts were blacked out.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said an uncensored look at North's
notes might clear up much of the mystery and said: ``I'm willing to
vote for Don Gregg if we get the notebooks for these particular
days.''
   But other senators pointed out that Gregg does not control
North's notes and that North and his lawyers have resisted demands
they be made available in uncensored form.
</TEXT>
