<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PregnancyOptions     06-15 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pregnancy Options,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Ethical to Reject Aggressive Treatment in Some Pregnancies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors may ethically counsel women to reject
aggressive medical treatment during pregnancy if their newborns are
very likely to die or have severe brain damage, contends a report in
a medical journal.
   Aggressive treatments such as monitoring the fetus, using drugs
to stop premature labor and delivering the baby by Caesarean section
are often used in cases involving severely defective fetuses, the
report said.
   Using those treatments without telling the mother that doing
without them is a reasonable option may violate her decision-making
rights, said the report, published in Friday's Journal of the
American Medical Association.
   The report describes the outcome of 13 pregnancies in which women
chose nonaggressive management of their cases. Nine of the babies
were stillborn and two died within a month of birth, the report said.
   One child, with serious chromosome abnormalities, died at age 4,
and another, with a usually fatal disorder of the skeletal system,
remains alive at 26 months, though dependent on a respirator, the
report said.
   It said choosing nonaggressive treatment should depend on two
criteria: Virtual certainty in the diagnosis, and a very high
probability that death or severe and irreversible brain damage will
occur in the newborn.
   Recent advances in diagnosis permit the detection of a wide
variety of fetal problems, said the report, by Dr. Frank A.
Chervenak of New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center and Laurence
B. McCullough of Baylor College of Medicine in Houston.
   The information usually leads to either aggressive treatment or
abortion, they said.
   Many fetuses with severe abnormalities face a high probability of
death immediately after birth, even with the most intensive care,
the authors said.
   Such intensive care often involves levels of physician-caused
disease, injury, pain and suffering ``that can reasonably be judged
to outweigh any benefits,'' they said.
   An accompanying editorial largely agreed with the authors in
their view that the wishes of the mother should be the main
consideration.
   The editorial, by Dr. Frederick R. Abrams of the University of
Colorado Graduate School of Public Affairs, said fairness ``demands
that in a situation in which there is a wide divergence of values
and no universally accepted source of truth, we ought to respect
patient autonomy.''
</TEXT>
