<FIRST>r a AM-TurkeyPoint-Drugs     06-15 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey Point-Drugs,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Power Plant Operator Arrested For Drug Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A utility engineer at the troubled Turkey Point
power plant, which includes nuclear reactors, and two other men were
arrested on charges they sold cocaine, the U.S. attorney said
Thursday.
   The FBI moved quickly on the case ``because of the potential
danger drug usage by employees of a nuclear power plant represented
to the south Florida area,'' U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said.
   Vernon Rice, an operator at the complex's fossil fuel section,
and the others were arrested Wednesday on a five-count indictment
handed up Monday by a federal grand jury, said Lehtinen.
   Florida Power &amp; Light Co. notified the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory
Commision of Rice's arrest even though he didn't have clearance for
the containment building, the two reactors inside or the control
room, utility spokeswoman Stacey Shaw said.
   But Lehtinen said, ``A control room operator, an engineering
watch officer in a nuclear power plant, whether its fossil or
nuclear, has access to all of it. It's clear the evidence will show
he was associating with other employees and they were commonly using
drugs.''
   The prosecutor said there was evidence drugs were used at the
plant, but didn't specify if that included nuclear reactor areas.
Both reactors are shut down.
   Ms. Shaw said there were no indications cocaine was sold at the
plant.
   Rice, 31, and Paul Muni, 28, both of Homestead, and David Wetzel,
26, of Leisure City are accused of selling cocaine in May and June.
   Authorities did not say how much cocaine was involved, but the
indictment said 3 ounces of the drug were found at Muni's home.
   Florida Power &amp; Light screens all employees for drugs when they
are hired, and randomly tests workers at Turkey Point's nuclear
section.
   The reactors are shut down partly due to a series of problems
that led the Washington-based Public Citizen group to label Turkey
Point the worst nuclear plant in the nation.
   The plant is operating under special NRC supervision for six
months because of its history of safety violations and
administrative problems.
</TEXT>
