<FIRST>r i AM-India-SriLanka     06-15 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Sri Lanka,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Fears Indian Soldiers May Stay Permanently</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday it fears
the 45,000 soldiers India sent to help end an ethnic civil war are
on the island to stay despite the president's request that they
leave.
   ``It is regretted certain statements have been made both here and
abroad to support the continued presence of the Indian troops in Sri
Lanka,'' a Foreign Ministry statement said.
   ``Such pronouncements will only have the unfortunate effect of
confirming the fears in the minds of the people of Sri Lanka that
Indian troops have come to this country to remain and not to
return,'' it added.
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi of India said Wednesday the soldiers
could not leave until terms of the 1987 India-Sri Lanka peace
agreement were met, primarily granting local autonomy to the Tamil
minority.
   Gandhi said Wednesday his country has a responsibility for the
safety of Tamils in Sri Lanka, where they make up 18 percent of the
16 million people. Tamils, who are predominantly Hindu like India's
population, claim discrimination by the majority Sinhalese, most of
whom are Buddhists.
   Gandhi's government has said it does not want the soldiers to
remain permanently in Sri Lanka, which is just off the southern tip
of India, but has made clear there will not be a hasty withdrawal.
   According to the Foreign Ministry statement, the only requirement
for withdrawal under the pact is a request by Sri Lanka, and the one
``made by the president of Sri Lanka to the prime minister of India
has already satisfied this condition.''
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who took office in January, has
said the Indians should leave by July 29, the second anniversary of
the peace agreement.
   The accord, signed by Gandhi and former President Junius R.
Jayewardene, provided for deployment of Indian troops to supervise
the surrender of arms by Tamil rebels, who began fighting in 1983
for an independent nation in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
   It promised the rebels limited autonomy in exchange, but failed
when the largest Tamil militia refused to go along.
   India became involved because it is the region's major power and
has 60 million Tamils of its own.
   India has said premature withdrawal would lead to even greater
violence in a nation where ethnic strife has claimed 12,500 lives in
six years.
   At least 9,000 people have been killed in the Tamil war and about
3,500, most of them supporters of the government, by Sinhalese
extremists who oppose any concessions to Tamils.
</TEXT>
