<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets' Money Tied Up As Lawmakers Remain Apart on Spending</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spending bill providing emergency money for
veterans' programs and other programs was threatened with further
delays Thursday as House and Senate negotiators failed to reach
agreement on whether to increase spending for drug enforcement.
   The House-Senate conference committee reported the bill back to
the two chambers with agreement on most items but not on the most
contentious one: $820 million in additional drug-fighting money for
this year approved by the House but rejected by the Senate.
   The spending bill, which could add more than $4 billion in
additional fiscal 1989 appropriations, has been delayed for weeks as
the House, Senate and White House jostle over its provisions.
   There has been no major disagreement over the underlying $1.2
billion for veterans programs, including health care. However,
lawmakers have refused to pass the bill without boosting other
favored programs and local projects for their constituents.
   The House could take up the bill again next week with a separate
vote possible on the new drug enforcement money for the Justice
Department and Customs Service. The White House says the money could
not be spent efficiently before the fiscal year ends Sept. 30.
   Fights also are possible in the two chambers on some budget
gimmicks in the bill, such as an accounting change in housing
programs that could increase spending up to $5.8 billion by evading
budget limits.
