<FIRST>u w AM-US-Austria     06-15 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Austria,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austria Asks United States to Lift Ban on Visits by Waldheim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austria has asked the United States to lift its
ban on visits by President Kurt Waldheim but ``our position hasn't
changed,'' a U.S. official said Thursday.
   The United States bans Waldheim because of his complicity in Nazi
war crimes during World War II, said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, and ``we received a communication from the
Austrian Embassy asking if we could reconsider his status.''
   ``Our position hasn't changed,'' the official added, and a
response to that effect will be given to the Austrian government.
   The United States decided in April 1987 to place Waldheim, who
was secretary general of the United Nations in the 1970s, on its
so-called watch list of undesirable visitors.
   The Austrian Embassy confirmed it had conveyed a note from its
foreign ministry to the State Department but denied it had asked
that Waldheim be removed from the watch list.
   ``We simply reiterated our view that his being placed on the list
contravenes international law,'' said embassy spokesman Ulf Pacher.
   President Bush said when he was running for the White House last
year that he supported the Reagan administration's decision to bar
Waldheim, who served as an intelligence officer in the German army
in the Balkans.
   Chancellor Franz Vranitsky, who heads Austria's Socialist Party,
told reporters here last month that he did not raise the Waldheim
matter in talks with Bush and other U.S. officials during a visit.
Foreign Minister Alois Mock is a leader of Austria's conservative
People's Party with which Waldheim was allied.
   An international commission of historians appointed by the
Austrian government issued a report in February 1988 that said
Waldheim was ``in close proximity'' to some war atrocities, knew
they were going on and made no attempt to stop them.
   The Justice Department said it has evidence that shows Waldheim's
complicity in the deportation of Jews from Greek islands under
German occupation to Nazi concentration or death camps, as well as
the execution of allied prisoners.
</TEXT>
