<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ChildCare     06-15 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Opens Debate on Child-Care Package; Partisan Differences Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate opened debate Thursday on a
multibillion-dollar child-care package revised to accommodate
various Republican concerns but still opposed by President Bush.
   ``This package embodies a truly bipartisan and comprehensive
approach to this nation's child-care crisis,'' said Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., co-author of major elements of the legislation.
``It's not a complete answer, but it's a very solid beginning.''
   The centerpiece of the package is a revised version of Dodd's
proposed Act for Better Child Care, a $1.75 billion program
including subsidies to poor families and grants and loans to
encourage establishment of new and expanded child-care centers.
   Tacked onto the measure was a separate set of tax credits for
poor families, drafted by Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, and a
provision designed to make clear the legislation was not aimed at
eliminating church-based child care.
   Also included is an amendment unrelated to child care that would
delay the implementation of a law requiring business to test benefit
programs for discrimination. Business interests have been lobbying
heavily for the delay and by attaching it to the child care package
Democrats hope to increase support among Republicans.
   Indeed, several key Republican senators endorse the thrust of the
package although they disagree with certain elements. But Senate
Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas was not among them and said he
would fight to quash Dodd's financing approach in favor of a
Bush-supported measure relying almost exclusively on tax credits.
   ``This is a necessity,'' Dole said. ``It is a high priority with
the president. It is a high priority with the administration. But we
believe there is a better way to go.''
   Dole said he hoped to sway Democrats during what likely will be
several days of debate and dozens of attempts to amend the measure.
Democrats said they would negotiate with the administration but were
committed to having the ABC framework in the final bill.
   The compromise version of Dodd's bill, co-sponsored by Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, leaves virtually all regulatory decisions at the
state level. Federal regulations proposed in the initial bill drew
stiff opposition from Republicans. As revised, the legislation
establishes health and safety categories for which states must adopt
standards.
   Seventy percent of the money would go to parents to help pay for
child care, 22 percent would go to training and grant and loan
programs designed to improve the quality and supply of child care
and 8 percent would go to states to administer programs and enforce
standards.
   The seperate Bentsen tax credits package makes changes in the
dependent care tax credit already provided to some families _ making
it available even if they owe no federal taxes.
   It also establishes a new tax credit of up to $500 to help pay
for health insurance for children. Families with annual incomes of
$21,000 or less would qualify for that credit.
   Over a five-year period the estimated cost of those credits is
$10.3 billion.
   The third component stipulates that any financial assistance
provided under the measure be used ``in a manner consistent with the
Constitution,'' language designed to allow parents to use subsidies
to pay for child care at church-run centers provided government
funds are not used for religious purposes.
   Dole said Dodd's financing approach left too much of the money in
government hands and that the GOP tax credit package, which is
similar to Bentsen's proposals, would put the money directly in the
hands of parents.
   ``They're the ones who are going to make the decisions, not some
institution, not some bureaucrats,'' Dole said.
   But Democrats said there was no guarantee parents would use tax
credits to pay for child care, and that tax credits alone would do
nothing to improve the quality and availability of care.
</TEXT>
