<HEAD>Syrian Artillery Set Afire Tanker Bound for Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout on later war action. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian artillery fire on Thursday set
ablaze a tanker loaded with gasoline for the besieged Christian
enclave north of Beirut, and scuba divers blew up three boats
carrying badly needed food there, police said.
   A police spokesman said the Timex Star, carrying 660,000 gallons
of gasoline, was hit at 9:30 p.m. off Tabarja, 15 miles north of
Beirut.
   The spokesman, anonymous under standing regulations, did not
identify the tanker's owners or registration. He said 19 crewmembers
were rescued but he gave no details.
   ``The ship is ablaze and sinking. It was hit by an artillery
barrage fired from west Beirut as it was 500 yards from the coast,''
he said.
   The blaze lit up the night sky over Tabarja and the nearby
Christian port of Jounieh as thousands of frightened residents
rushed to underground bunkers.
   The enclave's 1 million residents are enduring an acute gas
shortage because of a 3-month-old Syrian artillery blockade. roke out March
8 between Aoun's mainly
Christian army units and Syrian forces in Lebanon and the allied
Druse militias.
   Arab League nations have been trying to enact a truce in the
fighting, the latest violence in the 14-year-old civil war that has
split Lebanon into rival Moslem and Christian governments.
   Syria, with an estimated 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976
Arab League peacekeeping mandate, began shelling the Christian
heartland after Aoun imposed a March 6 blockade on illegal ports run
by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut. The ports were diverting
customs fees from government-run ports.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army command said two of its soldiers
were slightly wounded Thursday when guerrillas fired mortars on an
Israeli army unit in the Jewish state's self-proclaimed security
zone in southern Lebanon.
   It said the attack occurred in the eastern sector near the
Lebanese village of Kaoukaba, eight miles north of the Israeli
border.
   The Israeli unit responded with fire, the command said.
   The firefight came a day after Israeli warplanes bombed a base of
a Syrian-based faction of the Palestine Liberation Front near Beirut.
   The security zone is a six-to-10-mile-wide strip across the
border which Israel carved out in 1985 when it withdrew the bulk of
its troops from Lebanon. Israel invaded Lebanon in 1982 to drive out
Palestinian guerrillas.
