<FIRST>u a AM-DogExtortion 1stLd-Writethru a0718 06-15 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dog Extortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dogged Police Work Produces Four Arrests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, `A fourth ...,' to CORRECT spelling of name
to Entsminger, sted Enstminger.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A neighbor who found a woman's missing
dog forced her to increase her reward fourfold and set up a
nighttime drop at a gas station, police said.
   But dogged police work resulted in the capture of four people on
extortion conspiracy charges, and Sheila Hawkins got back her
5-year-old miniature Yorkshire terrier, Bentley, in good condition.
   The neighbor, 18-year-old construction worker Ronnie Blackwell,
told police he'd grown fond of the shaggy little dog he said he
found by the public library nearly a half mile from Ms. Hawkins'
home in this northwestern South Carolina city of about 44,000 people.
   ``He said he had become really attached to the dog and felt if he
kept upping the price, the lady would just think the dog wasn't
worth it,'' city police Detective Audrey McNair said Wednesday.
   Bentley had been missing since June 8. Ms. Hawkins, a 30-year-old
hairstylist, put out fliers offering a $50 reward for the dog's
return.
   On Sunday, she received a phone call from a man who said he had
the dog, and promised to bring him to her house for the reward,
authorities said.
   Bentley never arrived. Instead, a woman called three times
Sunday, told Ms. Hawkins, ``We have the dog,'' and said $50 wouldn't
be enough, according to a police report. The woman identified
herself as a mother whose son had found the dog and was very
attached to him.
   During one call, a man said Bentley's captors wanted $200, the
report said.
   Ms. Hawkins agreed to the price, but the dog wasn't returned. She
said she offered the callers a puppy the next time she had Bentley
bred, but they weren't interested.
   On Tuesday, one of the captors' relatives saw a television news
report on the missing dog, and apparently persuaded the four they'd
better return it, authorities said. They called Ms. Hawkins to say
they'd return him that night.
   That evening, she got a call instructing her to go to a gas
station to get her dog, but no money was demanded at that time.
   Detective McNair was at Ms. Hawkins' home when the call came. She
accompanied her to the gas station, where the three people waiting
were arrested.
   A fourth person, 18-year-old Rebecca Entsminger, was arrested
when she showed up at the police station later.
   She, Blackwell, Blackwell's 19-year-old sister, Theresa; and
Kipling Messer, 19, were all charged with conspiracy to commit
extortion, which carries a maximum penalty of five years in prison
on conviction.
   McNair said Entsminger, who is Blackwell's girlfriend, had posed
as his mother in one of Sunday's phone calls.
   The detective said police couldn't determine whether Blackwell's
story that he found the dog was true. Ms. Hawkins said she felt from
the beginning that Bentley hadn't just run away.
   ``I was just hoping whoever had him wouldn't mistreat him,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
