<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Personnel     06-15 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Personnel,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coloradan, Texan Chosen For Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday announced
nominations for two Energy Department posts and the U.S. ambassador
to the Organization of American States.
   The White House said the president selected J. Michael Davis to
be assistant secretary for conservation and renewable energy. He
would succeed John R. Berg.
   Davis has been president of GlowCore Colorado Inc., based in
Englewood, Colo., since 1986. He was a division manager in the
Energy Department from 1977 to 1980.
   Stephen A. Wakefield was chosen to be general counsel of the
Energy Department, succeeding Francis S. Ruddy. Wakefield has been a
senior partner in the Houston law firm of Baker and Botts since
1986. He was an Energy Department aide in 1974.
   Bush picked Luigi R. Einaudi to be the U.S. permanent
representative to the rganization of American States, succeeding
Richard Thomas McCormack.
   Since 1977 Einaudi has been director of the office of policy
planning coordination at the State Department's bureau of
inter-American affairs.
