<FIRST>r a AM-People-Lowe     06-15 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Lowe,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Accused in Court Document of Sex with Minor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Rob Lowe had sex with a minor while using
illegal drugs, a lawyer charged in a document filed in U.S. District
Court to support a lawsuit by the girl's mother.
   The affidavit filed Wednesday by Athens lawyer J. Hue Henry on
behalf of Lena Arlene Wilson added to the seriousness of the
allegations that have led to a criminal investigation of Lowe's
activities at an Atlanta hotel last summer.
   Ms. Wilson is suing Lowe for damages for emotional stress she
says followed Lowe's alleged seduction of her daughter, Jan Parsons,
then 16. The lawsuit has been moved from state to federal court at
Lowe's option as an out-of-state resident.
   A sexually explicit videotape has circulated showing Lowe, 25,
with Miss Parsons and another woman, but it does not show the
alleged intercourse between the actor and the 16-year-old.
   In the affidavit, Henry said he told Dale Kinsella, Lowe's
California lawyer, ``in essence that I believed that the film
depicted sufficient debauchery to sustain a claim for seduction of
an unmarried daughter under Georgia law.'' The affidavit mentioned
illegal drugs but did not identify them.
   Lowe's attorneys have denied that he ``has committed any wrongful
acts giving rise to liability.'' Richard North, one of Lowe's
Atlanta attorneys, said after Henry's filing Wednesday, ``We stand
by our previous pleadings.''
   ``Before filing this lawsuit, I interviewed a witness who stated
that she saw Mr. Lowe engage in sexual intercourse with Ms. Wilson's
daughter,'' Henry's affidavit said.
   He said the witness told him and Pamela Guest, a lawyer
representing Jan Parsons and her father, John, that one of Lowe's
Atlanta-area lawyers was aware of the witness' statements.
   The affidavit denies charges filed earlier by Lowe's attorneys
that Ms. Wilson and her former husband attempted to blackmail the
actor before suing.
   Henry said another California lawyer, Barry Hirsch, invited him
to propose a settlement offer and that he replied that he would
discuss settlement options and that his client would consider any
offer Lowe's lawyers cared to make.
   Henry denied making a settlement demand of $500,000. He said his
client rejected a ``take it or leave it'' settlement offer of
$35,000 in February. He did say he told Kinsella he would recommend
acceptance of a $500,000 offer if Kinsella were to make such an
offer but that he did so at the urging of Kinsella.
   Henry, in his affidavit, repeatedly denied suggesting that Lowe's
acting career could be damaged by criminal or civil actions and
denied suggesting that he could get criminal charges dropped.
   Lowe is under investigation by Fulton County authorities on
possible criminal charges of sexual exploitation of a minor, a
felony that carries up to 20 years in prison.
</TEXT>
