<FIRST>r w AM-Capitol-Police     06-15 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capitol-Police,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Wants Capitol Police to Confront Drug Dealers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police who guard the U.S. Capitol and
the White House are needed in the most drug-plagued neighborhoods in
the nation's capital to help local officers fight the District of
Columbia's crime wave, city police officials said Thursday.
   District Police Chief Isaac Fulwood, departing from previous
statements by city officials that they want federal officers for
help only with administrative tasks, said they could be better used
on the streets.
   ``It was never my intention to have the Capitol police serve in
administrative functions ... to not use them in a front-line mode,''
Fulwood told the House Administration personnel and police
subcommittee. ``We're talking about areas where bad things are
happening _ I can't soften the blow.''
   Fulwood asked the panel for 500 federal officers from the U.S.
Capitol Police, U.S. Park Police and the uniformed division of the
Secret Service, which guards the White House. The Capitol force, the
largest of the three with 1,250 officers, would make the largest
contribution.
   The request comes during a drug-related crime surge that has
given Washington the highest murder rate in the nation. Through
Thursday, 202 persons had been killed here in 1989, compared with
133 at this time last year. There were a record 372 homicides in the
district in 1988.
   Mayor Marion Barry said earlier this month that if federal
officers were put on detail to the city police department, they
would likely handle desk duties while city officers bolster street
patrols.
   Several committee members were taken aback by the idea that
officers who now patrol Capitol Hill hallways filled with
congressional aides and tourists should be put into action against
gun-toting criminals.
   ``That sounds to me like it's damn serious and life-threatening,
said Rep. Pat Roberts, R-Kan. ``I'm not sure every Capitol police
officer is a warrior.''
   Fulwood said the officers would be used only until the city can
recruit and train additional officers.
   The House earlier this week passed a measure that would authorize
$127 million in federal spending over five years to help the city
hire 700 additional police officers. The city police force now
numbers slightly more than 3,900 officers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
