<HEAD>Reporter Unhindered By His Age At Gorbachev News Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spunky 12-year-old boy may have been
the smallest reporter at a news conference with Mikhail S. Gorbachev
on Thursday, but that didn't stop him from firing off a question and
asking for an autograph.
   Alexander Blume, a Hanover student who works for a West German
youth magazine, asked the Soviet president: ``What do you especially
want to say to the youth in Germany?''
   Gorbachev smiled at Alexander and replied he wanted to appeal to
youth to help ensure international trust in the future.
   Alexander duly recorded the answer on a handheld tape recorder.
   After the news conference Alexander maneuvered his way to where
Gorbachev was exiting the room and pushed out a copy of Gorbachev's
book on Soviet reforms, ``Perestroika,'' for an autograph. The
Soviet president consented.
   ``I'm the youngest political journalist in the Federal Republic
(West Germany),'' said the proud youngster as he disappeared among
his adult colleagues while making his way out of the room.
