<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Ivory     06-15 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Ivory,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Banning Imports of African Ivory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada will ban ivory imports from Africa to help
protect elephants which are being slaughtered for their tusks at a
rate of 70,000 a year, the federal government said Thursday.
   ``This action should serve to indicate Canada's desire to
discourage any further speculative slaughter of these magnificent
animals,'' External Affairs Minister Joe Clark said in a statement.
   He said Canada also is supporting efforts to ban commercial
trading in African elephant ivory under the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species.
   ``We are delighted that they have acted,'' said Ron Orenstein, a
spokesman for the African Elephant Emergency Network.
   The Canadian group, whose sponsors include the World Wildlife
Fund and Toronto Zoo, has been lobbying for bans to choke the ivory
market.
   Orenstein said poachers have killed more than 1.25 million
African elephants in the past decade, reducing the continent's
elephant population to 750,000.
   ``About 80 percent of the elephant ivory imported to the West
comes from poachers,'' he said. ``At this rate the elephants will be
extinct in 10 to 12 years.''
   Poaching has increased, he said, because prices for ivory have
gone up from $2.70 a pound in the 1960s to $136 a pound.
   He said the United States, France, West Germany, Britain and
other countries already have taken similar action.
   Officials could not immediately estimate the value of ivory sales
in Canada.
</TEXT>
