<FIRST>u a AM-DrugTesting     06-15 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Testing,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. District Judge Bars Random Testing of U.S. Investigators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Thursday prohibited
random drug testing of the U.S. government investigators who conduct
background checks and oversee drug testing of other federal
employees and job applicants.
   In a nationwide ruling, U.S. District Judge D. Lowell Jensen also
barred mandatory post-accident drug testing of all 5,500 employees
of the Office of Personnel Management, or OPM, but allowed testing
of individual employees based on a supervisor's ``reasonable
suspicion'' of illegal drug use.
   Jensen said U.S. Supreme Court rulings in March, allowing drug
testing of certain Customs Service employees and post-accident
testing of railroad workers, did not necessarily authorize testing
of government employees in less-sensitive or less-risky jobs.
   The decision ``takes some of the sting out of the prior
rulings,'' said Lawrence Pulgram, a lawyer for workers affected by
the tests. He called it ``a good first step toward limiting the
government's campaign to implement these drug testing programs
throughout the government.''
   The ruling was issued after government lawyers had left for the
day. It could be appealed to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   The OPM is the successor to the U.S. Civil Service Commission.
Besides supervising the federal civil service system, it directs
other federal agencies giving drug tests to workers under an
executive order by former President Ronald Reagan.
   Jensen's decision halts drug testing that began last September in
the OPM's Washington, D.C., office. Testing inother offices has been
suspended while the lawsuit is pending.
   The random drug testing order applied to about 650 investigators
who conduct background checks on applicants for sensitive civil
service jobs and for private jobs with military contractors.
   They were to be required to submit to urine testing at any time
with two hours' notice. The employees' lawsuit said testing without
grounds to suspect individual drug use violated the constitutional
ban on unreasonable searches.
   OPM investigators have less-sensitive jobs, which do not
ordinarily subject them to possible bribery or physical threats, and
can be subjected to an unlimited number of drug tests under the
random testing program, Jensen said.
   He also prohibited post-accident testing, which covered any of
OPM's 5,500 employees involved in an accident that caused injury
requiring hospitalization or more than $1,000 in property damage.
   Jensen said the Supreme Court ruling in the railroad case, which
allowed post-accident testing without individual suspicion of drug
use, was based on justifications that did not exist in the OPM case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
