<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     06-15 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Pardon `Dirty War' Generals; Menem To Assume Power
July 8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Thursday
refused to pardon ex-President Leopoldo Galtieri and three other
generals charged with human rights abuses during Argentina's 1976-83
military dictatorship.
   The decision complicates an issue that sparked three rebellions
against President Raul Alfonsin and threatens to undermine the
government of President-elect Carlos Menem, who is to take office in
three weeks.
   Alfonsin will hand power to Menem on July 8, the two men
announced Thursday, making a decision reportedly delayed by the
problem posed by some 20 generals facing charges connected to the
military's ``dirty war'' against leftists.
   Also unresolved are the cases of several hundred officers and
soldiers who took part in April 1987 and January 1988 uprisings and
a December 1988 barracks revolt.
   Menem clearly wants Alfonsin to resolve the matter and take the
political heat a decision will generate.
   Alfonsin's term was to expire Dec. 10 but he said Monday he wants
to leave office early because his outgoing government cannot resolve
Argentina's economic crisis.
   Attorney General Andres D'Alessio had asked the Supreme Court to
determine whether the four generals could be sheltered from
prosecution by partial amnesty laws.
   Court spokesman Antonio Lopez de Tejada said the court ruled
Thursday that Galtieri and Gens. Santiago Riveros, Luciano Jauregui
and Ramon Bessone must stand trial.
   About 20 generals face charges of kidnapping, torture and murder
in some of the arrests and disappearances of nearly 9,000
Argentinians between the March 1976 military coup and Alfonsin's
election in October 1983.
   The high command wants the courts to stop the trials and free
officers convicted in December 1985.
   The issue is sensitive. Politicians and military officials talk
vaguely of ``national reconciliation,'' ``healing wounds'' and
``vindicating'' the army's role in what was a ``war.''
   Human rights groups charge the military committed genocide and
demand the generals be tried.
   Gen. Galtieri, who ruled from December 1981 to June 1982, is in
jail for mishandling the 1982 Falklands Island war against Britain.
He is accused of ordering the death of 13 opponents who defense
attorneys say were shot as they tried to escape.
</TEXT>
