<FIRST>r i AM-PLO-US     06-15 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-US,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador, PLO Envoy Meet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Robert H. Pelletreau Jr.,
the only authorized channel for American contacts with the PLO, met
with the PLO envoy to Tunisia, Hakam Balawi, the official
Palestinian news agency said Thursday.
   It said the two discussed ``the latest developments in the
Palestinian cause and efforts to push ahead on the road to peace''
in the Middle East at a meeting Wednesday at the U.S. Embassy.
   The United States began a dialogue with the Palestine Liberation
Organization in December after the PLO took steps to recognize
Israel, renounce terrorism and opted for a two-state solution to the
conflict with the Israelis.
   Israel refuses to talk with the PLO, calling it a terrorist
organization.
   A U.S. delegation headed by Pelletreau has held three formal
meetings with a Palestinian delegation in the Tunisian capital, in
December, in March, and again June 8.
   Pelletreau and Balawi have met on other occasions, however.
   Western diplomats said meanwhile in Paris on Thursday that
UNESCO's Executive Board has decided to put off for the time being a
debate on whether to admit Palestine as a member.
   They said that under a compromise agreement reached after three
weeks of negotiations, the issue will go on the agenda of the
General Conference, UNESCO's highest decision-making body, which
meets this fall. But they added it may not come up for a vote.
   The diplomats spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   A two-thirds majority of the 158 member nations of the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization would be needed to
admit Palestine as a member.
   Another U.N. body, the World Health Organization, decided on May
12 to put off the issue until next year.
   The United States says if Palestine is admitted as a UNESCO
member, this would effectively finish any chance it might return to
the organization.
   The United States withdrew from UNESCO at the end of 1984,
holding it had become overly political and was mismanaged. Britain
followed suit a year later.
</TEXT>
