<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Slaying,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Former Security Chief Pleads Innocent In Journalist's Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico's former federal security chief pleaded
innocent Thursday to charges he ordered the murder of a prominent
journalist and denied links to a Mexican drug kingpin, blaming it
all on ``pure gossip.''
   Jose Antonio Zorrilla Perez, 47, was charged with first-degree
murder in the parking garage shooting of newspaper columnist Manuel
Buendia, who exposed drug trafficking, gunrunning and wrongdoing in
high places.
   Buendia, of the daily Excelsior, was killed in Mexico City on May
30, 1984.
   ``I am innocent of all these charges,'' Zorrilla, a former
director of the Mexican equivalent of the FBI said at his
arraignment in Criminal Court.
   ``There is no evidence for the (city) attorney general to send
this case to trial. Because of pure gossip and elaborate work, a
tale was created to have me declared responsible for these crimes.''
   Shortly after the hearing, prosecutors announced the filing of
additional charges of obstruction of justice, abuse of authority and
cover up in investigating the Buendia case.
   Zorrilla faces up to 40 years in prison on the murder charge and
22 additional years on the other charges.
   In testimony and depositions, witnesses and some associates swore
Zorrilla was linked to drug kingpin Rafael Caro Quintero and ordered
Buendia killed because he feared the columnist would expose him.
   Caro Quintero is awaiting trial in the 1985 torture-murder of a
U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
