<FIRST>a a PM-Counterfeiter Adv21   06-15 1051</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Counterfeiter, Adv 21,1079</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Wed PMs, June 21, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Admitted Counterfeiter Is Content To Stay in Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CIUDAD JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newton Van Drunen made millions of
dollars in just three years, but the government didn't like his
methods.
   When U.S. Secret Service agents and Mexican police raided his
suburban Juarez house in February, Van Drunen was running off $50
bills. The authorities seized $12.6 million in phony tens, twenties
and fifties.
   Van Drunen, 61, contends he was just eight months and $1 million
away from buying a paper-manufacturing plant and printing perfect
counterfeit U.S. currency. The Secret Service says he already was
pretty close.
   ``Printing American currency is a very difficult task,'' he said
in an interview at CeReSo prison. ``The Secret Service and Mexican
banking experts both tell me that other people have done better than
I have. I would like to meet those people. I would like to shake
their hand.''
   By the time of the raid, Van Drunen had circulated some $7
million in bogus bills, making him one of the most prolific
counterfeiters in history.
   The owlish, balding Van Drunen speaks slowly in a low, raspy
voice and stoops his 6-foot-5 frame to make himself heard over the
din in the prison's crowded, grimy visiting room. Though
considerably older, taller and grayer than most of the inmates, he
seems to mix well; he uses Mexican hand gestures and, like most
Mexicans, stands closer than most Americans are used to.
   The search for Van Drunen began about three years ago after
counterfeit money turned up in the Denver area. Bill Driscoll, the
Secret Service agent in charge in El Paso, Texas, wouldn't give
details _ relations between U.S. and Mexican police are touchy _ but
the bills were traced to Juarez and to Van Drunen's house. Police
waited to hear the press before bursting in.
   Van Drunen said he intended to use the counterfeit millions to
build a saltwater desalinization plant on the Gulf Coast in
Tamaulipas state. It would have let him make legal profits to help
his adopted homeland.
   Van Drunen was born in Ontario, Canada, to American parents and
grew up in Illinois. He worked in his teens and 20s with Mexican
farmworkers in Illinois and learned Spanish; he says he feels most
comfortable around Mexicans. His wife, Alicia Zamorra, is a native
of Mexico.
   In 1975, he was convicted of smuggling Mexicans into the United
States. He spent 18 months in federal prison in Sandstone, Minn.,
where ``they just needed people in the print shop and they shoved me
in there. Isn't that ironic?''
   Van Drunen used the knowledge he gained in prison when he got
out, fabricating ``green cards'' _ permanent U.S. residency cards
for aliens _ and Social Security cards. Most of his customers were
Mexicans.
   He was caught, convicted of counterfeiting government documents
and spent almost three years in federal prison in Springfield, Mo.
He was released on parole in 1984 and moved to Chicago.
   There, Van Drunen accumulated 10 tons of printing and embossing
equipment. He and Alicia bought a used school bus for $400,
decorated it with curtains and plastic flowers in the windows, and
loaded the equipment inside.
   ``On the 19th day of January, 1986, we invoked the Lord's
blessing on our enterprise and began our pilgrimage,'' said Van
Drunen, who tends to temper his formal, stilted language with a
droll tone of voice.
   A week later, they were house-hunting in Juarez. ``It was not a
spur-of-the-moment thing. I'm somewhat deliberate in everything I
do.''
   He chose to live in Mexico because officials would ask fewer
questions. He picked Juarez to be close to U.S. ink, paper and
equipment supplies and because there are so many U.S.-owned
factories ``that an American passes on the street and no one turns
his head.''
   They bought the house in Alicia's name and persuaded the city to
install heavy-duty power lines. As expected, no one asked questions.
   Van Drunen figured it would take five batches to perfect his
counterfeits. The first couple of lots were of low quality and he
sold them at five cents on the dollar. Most of it _ about $7 million
_ was circulated around Monterrey.
   ``I am afraid that some of it circulated in the United States,''
he said mournfully. ``There was an agreement that none of it would
be circulated in the United States, but I'm afraid they broke their
end of the agreement.
   ``There is not much honor among thieves, son.''
   Still, Van Drunen refuses to talk about the partners and
customers who indirectly contributed to the arrest that ended a
nearly idyllic lifestyle. The couple visited 24 of Mexico's 31
states in a 1974 Chevy pickup truck modified with a heavy-duty
radiator and a seat built to relieve his sciatica.
   ``We went to see things that the tourist never sees. We even
found a race of mule-footed hogs 7,000 feet up in the mountains of
Guerrero. We had a good time. Every time we'd find a flower we were
unfamiliar with, we'd bring it back and see what we could do with
it. I'm crazy about flowers.''
   During fall and winter, when humidity is low and printing
conditions best because paper doesn't swell with moisture, Van
Drunen would make money.
   The job entailed sending paper through a Heidelberg sheet feed
press 10 times, then through an embossing machine to give the paper
its texture. U.S. currency has tiny blue and red threads woven into
it that make it difficult to counterfeit. Van Drunen was printing
tiny lines on his currency to mimic the threads, but he had a
grander plan to buy a paper factory and make currency paper
indistinguishable from the real thing.
   He could have bought the plant with $1 million and could have had
the paper in October, he said. ``The next step was perfection.''
   But Van Drunen likely won't get to achieve perfection; he expects
to spend years in CeReSo. Meanwhile, he and some large-scale drug
dealers intend to bring some type of industry to the prison to give
inmates something to do.
   ``Who knows?'' he said, a devilish grin flitting across his face.
``Maybe we'll set up a print shop here.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 21</NOTE>
