<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1140EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-FirstBorn ADV16   06-15 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-First Born, ADV 16,0783</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, June 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tedious `First Born' on A&amp;E</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been a bad day for Gordon. He's just learned
his mother is an ape, the local priest has informed him that he is
``an insult to God,'' and to top it all off, the woman he loves
turns out to be his sister.
   Who wouldn't run amok in the forest and run smack into a tree?
   Despite coming from the same team who produced the delightful
``Life and Loves of a She-Devil,'' the three-hour miniseries ``First
Born'' is a silly melodrama airing in three parts, an hour a week,
beginning Saturday on the Arts &amp; Entertainment Cable Network.
   ``First Born'' at least proves that the esteemed BBC is capable
of producing remarkably tedious drivel. Even the fine Charles Dance
is adrift in this self-important tale of a scientist who creates a
half-man, half-gorilla. The film was based on the Maureen Duffy
novel ``Gor Saga.''
   Dance plays Dr. Edward Forrester, a geneticist struggling to
create the new species, coveted by the military for its potential as
a fighting force.
   The film opens with the birth of his seventh attempt at creating
the hybrid _ through in vitro fertilization, thank goodness. No
attempt at major special effects here. The bouncing baby whatever is
a human infant with hair stuck all over him. The mother, a lowland
gorilla named Mary, rejects the baby, and he is raised by a human
foster mother.
   Forrester at first covers up the top-secret experiment by
explaining that he is seeking to cross a gorilla and an orangutan _
though no one at the laboratory seems at all fazed by the baby's
obviously human face.
   Forrester tells the military that the experiment has been
terminated, then concocts a story about the child's parents being
killed in a car wreck and sends ``Gor,'' short for Gordon, packing
off to military school.
   The grown Gor, played by the wide-eyed Jamie Foster, has turned
out to be quite a perfect gentleman. At military school, he proves
to be a fine athlete, but can't bring himself to harm another
creature. He decides to join the priesthood. This doesn't bother
Forrester _ but Gor's budding infatuation with Forrester's daughter
does.
   Everyone involved seems to take the production terribly
seriously, even dressing it up with a lot of religious overtones.
Mary, indeed. For fans of inadvertent comedy, however, the laughable
conclusion recalls the daffy kitsch of the ``Omen'' movie series and
might be worth the wait.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   C-SPAN COVERS PARLIAMENT _ C-SPAN plans to commence in November
carrying portions of the proceedings of the British House of
Commons, now that that parliamentary body has approved television
coverage. The House of Commons is where the action is in the British
government. The House of Lords, which carries out mostly ceremonial
proceedings, has allowed television coverage for three years. C-SPAN
expects to begin coverage with the traditional opening address to
the House of Commons by Queen Elizabeth II. C-SPAN has covered the
U.S. House since 1979 and the Senate since 1986. C-SPAN is a
non-profit service funded by the cable industry. ...
   ONE LAST LOOK? _ CBS will begin airing original episodes of three
canceled series, ``The Cavanaughs,'' ``Coming of Age'' and ``The
Equalizer'' beginning Thursday, June 29. The three series will air
in place of ``Paradise,'' which is moving to Saturday, and ``Knots
Landing,'' which is on hiatus for the summer. ...
   CASTING NEWS _ John Heard, Mel Harris (``thirtysomething''),
Lloyd Bridges and David Morse (``St. Elsewhere'') will star in the
NBC miniseries ``Cross of Fire,'' a fact-based, four-hour drama
about the operation of the Ku Klux Klan in 1920s Indiana, currently
in production in Kansas. Heard (``Beaches'') plays the charismatic
KKK Grand Dragon, and Harris a woman who falls in love with him, but
later turns on him and is murdered. Morse plays a prosecutor and
Bridges a defense attorney. The miniseries will air in the 1989-90
season. ...
   KIDS BACK IN THE HALL _ HBO is making ``The Kids in the Hall'' a
weekly, 20-part series beginning next month. The Toronto comedy
troupe, whose often dark humor satirizes all aspects of contemporary
society, was discovered by ``Saturday Night Live'' executive
producer Lorne Michaels. Michaels is executive producer of the
series and produced the ``Kids in the Hall'' ``On Location'' special
for HBO last October. ``The Kids in the Hall'' are Dave Foley, Bruce
McCulloch, Kevin McDonald, Mark McKinney and Scott Thompson.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, June 16</NOTE>
