<FIRST>a i PM-SuperblockSeven Adv20   06-15 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Superblock Seven, Adv 20,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs June 20 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Colombian Housing Project Reflects Kennedy-Era Dream</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Built more than a quarter century ago, a
U.S.-style housing project in a Bogota's biggest suburb endures like
a living if somewhat seedy monument to a lost Pan-American dream.
   When built, the project called Superblock Seven was proclaimed by
politicians and planners from a host of countries as a bold first
step toward a grand goal _ the eradication of homelessness and
extreme poverty in the region.
   It grew out of President John F. Kennedy's Alliance for Progress,
a program intended to counter the spread of Fidel Castro's
revolution throughout Latin America.
   Now the lives of its 8,000 middle-income and working-class
occupants reflect a more complex reality in which social chasms
persist. They grapple with graffiti and trash, drug use and crime.
And they sometimes wistfully recall the community's hopeful origins.
   ``This was an extraordinary thing _ nowadays you don't find such
ambitious projects,'' said Francisco Lozano, a civil servant in his
40s who has lived in Superblock Seven for 17 years. ``The state
doesn't get that involved anymore. Now it's all free enterprise, and
the private sector.''
   Superblock Seven was planned as a suburb of state-subsidized
housing south of Bogota for the masses of impoverished Colombians
crowding into the city.
   A pilot project for all of Latin America, the suburb was named
Kennedy City.
   When ground was broken for Superblock Seven in 1961, the area was
little more than open farmland. The project, with its 1,248
apartments in 42 buildings and 214 one-story rowhouses, was to be
the hub of Kennedy City and a magnet for more such construction.
   A magnet it was, but development exceeded planners' expectations
in both pace and scale.
   Shacks began to sprout as people, many of them peasants from the
countryside, streamed in faster than proper homes could be built. In
all about forty superblocks were built, some of them much bigger.
But they hold only a fraction of the suburb's population, estimated
to exceed 1 million and still growing.
   The poverty that planners dreamed of erasing came to occupy the
suburb's fringes just as it persisted in other marginal sections of
Bogota. As in other Colombian cities, violence and political
extremism grew rather than declined, fueled by a new activity _ drug
trafficking.
   As Kennedy City grew the Alliance for Progress lost momentum in
Latin America, and a world recession in the 1970s put the squeeze on
state support for ambitious public projects. Also, a new approach to
development began taking hold, with the state role shrinking and
more emphasis on private funding.
   The area around Superblock Seven became a commercial center,
transforming the project into a kind of strange island: designed by
U.S. architects, its sturdy brick buildings, broad grassy
quadrangles, basketball courts and asphalt parking lots seem more
appropriate to an aging New Jersey suburb. Latin America housing
tends to be more tightly packed.
   ``We knew we were a kind of guinea pig,'' said Carlos Paz Elias,
the 65-year-old president of the project's association of
homeowners. He is one of the original residents, who call themselves
founders.
   ``Kennedy City was supposed to spread out from here,'' he said.
``We were supposed to be at the center of a star, reaching out along
eight avenues. We were suppose to reach out, not be enclosed like a
prison.
   ``But that's what we are like now _ a prison, trying to keep the
the city out.''
   Three city blocks wide by five blocks long, the Superblock has
been gradually closing off its entrances with chain-link fences and
padlocks. Too many people are coming in to dump trash, use drugs,
mug and rob.
   ``The problem is mostly at night,'' said Horacio Valencia Marin,
50, a telephone company workers who has lived 22 years in the
superblock. ``If you come home late, they're sure to mug you.''
   Lozano's teen-age son, Francisco Jr., said, ``At night here, you
see lots of drug addiction. Twenty or 25 boys get together and smoke
marijuana. You can't walk around alone; they'll rob you.''
   The father blamed a general apathy among Colombians and said they
needed to become more socially aware and active. But he also
criticized what he saw as a more confrontational U.S. attitude
toward Latin America.
   ``They used to give us aid, and now look at this problem of the
foreign debt. ... They are squeezing us,'' he said.
   ``Now they sell us weapons. President Kennedy was special. It was
so much better to talk of the Alliance for Progress, than this talk
of an alliance for war.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs June 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
