<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv19   06-15 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 19,0737</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, June 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tomatoes Seek Revenge _ but Fail _ When Insects Eat Them</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   DAVIS, Calif. AP) _ When a bug starts to eat a tomato, it seems
the fruit tries to counterattack by releasing chemicals to stunt the
insect's growth.
   The mechanism fails because the chemicals counteract each other,
but the discovery holds promise for biological alternatives to
insecticides, said Sean S. Duffey, a University of California,
Davis, entomologist. Plants might be genetically engineered to give
them defenses against bugs, he said.
   Duffey and his colleagues studied larvae of the tomato fruitworm
and beet armyworm. Some of the worms were raised on artificial
diets, while others were raised on tomato plants. Duffey measured
the growth of the worms and monitored the chemical properties of the
worms and the tomato plants.
   When tomato cells were damaged by an insect, they released
chemicals called proteinase inhibitors, which interfered with the
insects' digestion of protein. The damage also allowed chemicals
called phenolics to react with others known as polyphenol oxidase
enzymes. That let the phenolics ``bind up'' protein in the tomato so
it was less available for the insect to digest.
   ``Laboratory tests indicated that these reactions, individually,
are potent defenses, dramatically decreasing the growth rate of the
worms,'' a university news release said. ``However, Duffey's work
shows that these two methods of defense work at cross purposes,'' so
the insects can eat with impunity.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Scientists Seeking More Bang for the Bacteria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bacteria could offer an inexpensive
method of cleaning up explosives storage sites, say researchers who
already have found a naturally occurring organism that can break
down nitroglycerin.
   ``For every dollar spent on this method, it will take between $10
and $100 with so-called dump truck technology _ hauling off the
explosives and burning or burying them,'' said Pat Unkefer of Los
Alamos National Laboratory.
   Unkefer and her husband, Cliff, both biochemists, found a
bacteria that breaks down nitroglycerin into water and carbon
dioxide. The Unkefers and technologist John Hanners say it will be
more complicated to find microbes capable of degrading TNT and other
explosives that are more complex than nitroglycerine.
   They say bacteria applied to explosives-tainted soil could
degrade the toxic substances into harmless residue in as little as
six months.
   The researchers collect bacteria samples near munitions plants
and explosives staging sites, return them to the laboratory and grow
them in a culture with nitroglycerin to isolate those with an
ability to live off the normally toxic explosive.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>New Mexico Petroglyph Bolsters Argument Indians Saw Supernova</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rock painting discovered in New Mexico
last year provides more support for researchers who believe American
Indians witnessed the extremely bright explosion of a star 935 years
ago.
   Many anthropologists are skeptical that 11th-century Indians
would have recorded the supernova, even though it appeared twice as
bright as the planet Venus. But the rock painting, or petroglyph, is
at least the 22nd example found in the West since the 1950s of
American Indian art depicting a bright object near a crescent moon,
said University of Colorado astronomer Jack Brandt.
   The latest was found by amateur astronomers from Illinois in New
Mexico's Chaco Canyon, which may have been a Pueblo sun-watching
site, Brandt said.
   Only two of the 22 rock paintings or carvings have been ruled out
as records of the gargantuan blast in the year A.D. 1054, he said.
   Ancient Chinese and Japanese historical records reported the
exploding star that formed the Crab Nebula was visible for 653
nights and in daylight for 23 consecutive days.
   Astronomical calculations show that a crescent moon next to the
supernova would have been visible only from what is now the western
United States, he said. No planets or other bright objects would
have been near a crescent moon during the 11th century in western
North America.
   Crescent moons are rare in Indian rock art, supporting the
argument that the Indians saw and made artistic records of the
supernova. ``Almost every time crescent moon rock art is found,
there is a bright object depicted near it,'' Brandt said.
   Such depictions have been found in Arizona, California, New
Mexico, Texas, Utah and Baja California, Mexico.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 19</NOTE>
