<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0766</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled House failed to
override President Bush's veto of legislation to raise the minimum
wage, giving the White House a win in its first legislative clash
with Congress.
   House members voted 247-178 to override on Wednesday, but that
was 34 votes shy of the two-thirds needed. Thus, Bush's veto stands
of a bill that would have increased the hourly minimum wage from
$3.35 to $4.55 by October 1991.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early-June sales of domestically made cars and
light trucks crept up 1.1 percent compared with last year after
automakers extended incentives to entice late-spring buyers.
   The eight major automakers said Wednesday they sold vehicles at
an average daily rate of 34,994 during the June 1-10 period this
year compared with 34,621 during the same time last year. Car sales
were up 1.3 percent and truck sales rose 0.7 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business sales rose 1.7 percent in April, the
steepest gain since March 1988 and far faster than a 0.6 percent
jump in inventories, the government said.
   Analysts expect sales to soften but say the Commerce Department
report released Wednesday showed no sign of any buildup in
inventories of unsold goods that could herald a recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan
said U.S. banks must be allowed into the securities business if the
United States is to compete successfully against Europe and Japan.
   Greenspan, testifying Wednesday before the Senate Banking
subcommittee on securities, said the 55-year-old Glass-Steagall law,
which separated commercial banking from the securities industry, is
hampering U.S. institutions from competing in what is becoming an
increasingly global financial system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers are losing confidence in the nation's
financial institutions and their skepticism is rising about the
government's ability to handle the problem and protect their
deposits, according to a survey.
   The survey, sponsored by the banking consulting firm Alex
Sheshunoff &amp; Co. and released Wednesday, found a widespread belief
that the nation's thrift crisis will lead to a increase in personal
income taxes and push more banks and S&amp;Ls into foreign ownership.
