controls on natural gas, a move supporters say will help ensure
adequate supplies of the fuel used by 48 million American
households, even if consumers must pay more.
   Wednesday's vote was 82-17 after the bill's chief opponent, Sen.
Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, failed to win approval of four amendments
that he said would protect consumers from what he called a certain
trend toward higher prices.
</TEXT>
