<FIRST>r f PM-Greenspan-Securities     06-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenspan-Securities,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Chairman Says Law Hampers Competition With Europe, Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. banks must be allowed into the securities
business if the United States is to compete successfully against
Europe and Japan, Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan told
a congressional panel.
   Greenspan, testifying Wednesday before the Senate Banking
subcommittee on securities, said the 55-year-old Glass-Steagall law,
which separated commercial banking from the securities industry, is
hampering U.S. institutions from competing in what is becoming an
increasingly global financial system.
   ``There is no question we are being significantly suppressed by
the Glass-Steagall restrictions,'' Greenspan said.
   ``My concern is that as we continue to internationalize ... that
we are in effect inhibiting our institutions from fully
participating in that,'' he said.
   Last year, the Senate, with Federal Reserve support,
overwhelmingly passed legislation granting banks broad new
securities powers, but the bill died in the House.
   ``Had we had congressional passage of the bill that passed the
Senate last year, I would argue our competitive capabilities in the
world market would be significantly enhanced,'' Greenspan said.
   Treasury Undersecretary Robert Glauber said in a speech last
month that the administration intends to revive its push to revamp
Glass-Steagall later this year.
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of the subcommittee,
said his panel will turn its attention to the issue once Congress
passes President Bush's savings and loan bailout.
   ``It's unacceptable to most Americans that we should end up
playing second fiddle in financial services,'' Dodd said. He said
only one U.S. banking company, Citicorp, is among the world's 10
largest and only one securities firm, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
is among the five biggest.
   Banks in Great Britain and West Germany already have securities
powers. But Sen. James R. Sasser, D-Tenn., noted that Japanese banks
have managed to retain their world standing even though they operate
under restrictions similar to the Glass-Steagall law.
   Greenspan replied that Japanese banks lag in profitability, but
not size, and he noted that Japan is moving to reform its banking
laws.
   ``I should trust we wouldn't be the laggard in that area,'' the
central bank chairman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AdSpending     06-15 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ad Spending,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Forecaster Boosts Spending Projection for 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong spending by national advertisers and an
improving economic climate were cited as a prominent forecaster
raised his estimate of U.S. ad spending growth this year to 6.9
percent.
   That still would leave growth in domestic ad spending below the
rises of 7.4 percent to 7.9 percent posted in each of the past four
years and well below the double-digit increases earlier in the
decade.
   But Robert Coen, director of forecasting for the ad agency
McCann-Erickson, said Wednesday that domestic ad spending growth for
this year should exceed the 6.1 percent rise he projected last
December.
   ``National marketers' ad budgets are now keeping pace with
economic growth and, although local retail activity is still
depressed, signs of gradual improvement are becoming evident,'' he
said.
   He said magazines, radio, cable TV and syndicated programing were
seeing bigger-than-expected ad growth, but that expected growth for
newspapers was dismal and network television ad revenues would
barely exceed last year's results.
   He said total U.S. ad spending should reach $126.2 billion this
year, up from $118.1 billion in 1988.
   Spending by national advertisers was expected to rise 7.6 percent
to $70.6 billion, while local ad spending was expected to grow 6
percent to $55.6 billion. Six months ago, Coen forecast a 6.5
percent rise in national ad spending and a 5.6 percent increase in
local ad spending.
   None of the percentage increases is adjusted for inflation. Coen
expects the economy to grow at a 7.5 percent clip this year,
including inflation.
   At a news conference, Coen said the falloff that traditionally
follows an election and Olympic Games year may not be as sharp as he
had expected. Domestic ad spending rose 7.7 percent in 1988.
   Some marketers beef up their ad spending in connection with the
Olympics; election years mean regular advertisers must compete with
political candidates for commercial time and space.
   In 1985, for example, domestic ad spending growth tumbled to 7.9
percent from 15.1 percent in the election and Olympic year of 1984.
   Network television ad revenues were off 4 percent in the first
four months of this year compared with the same period in 1988, but
Coen expects a 1 percent rise for the full year.
   He said ABC's revenues were off 23 percent, compared with last
year when it broadcast the Winter Olympics. But ad revenue was up 5
percent at CBS and 10 percent at NBC in the first four months of
1989.
   ``As the year unfolds, the comparisons will improve until the
months corresponding to last year's Summer Olympics telecast,'' he
said.
   Among the big network advertisers, Coen said fast-food marketers
boosted spending by 29 percent in the first quarter after an 18
percent rise last year. Advertising spending on cable TV, syndicated
programming, magazines and radio all were stronger than expected, he
said. Direct mail and Yellow Pages advertising are expected to grow
10 percent each.
   But Coen said the growth prospects for newspapers were ``quite
dismal,'' projecting a 5 percent rise in local ad spending and a 3
percent increase in national ad spending. Local retail lineage was
down in the first quarter and local classified lineage ``looks
terrible in comparison with last year's highs,'' he said.
   Local ad spending growth also remains sluggish, he said.
   Coen said ad spending overseas was expected to grow faster than
domestic ad spending for the fifth consecutive year, but he scaled
back his December estimate to 10 percent from 12 percent. Foreign ad
spending is expected to reach $133.5 billion in 1989.
   In first estimate of growth for 1990, Coen said he expects U.S.
ad spending to grow 7 percent to $136 billion next year, while
foreign ad spending rises 9 percent to $146 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
