<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     06-15 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales of Cars and Light Trucks Up Slight 1.1 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incentive packages generated only modest buyer
interest in early June, as automakers reported a lackluster 1.1
percent rise in car and light truck sales from year-earlier levels.
   ``You used to get a spike when these things (incentives) came
out, and now it's a yawn,'' analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. of New York said Wednesday.
   The eight major automakers with U.S. production reported that
they sold cars and trucks at an average daily rate of 34,994 during
the June 1-10 period this year, up slightly from the
34,621-vehicle-a-day average during the same time last year.
   Early June car sales rose 1.3 percent. Truck sales increased 0.7
percent.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. began new
incentive programs in early June to replace those in effect since
late March and early April. The new programs generally increased the
number of cars and trucks offering rebates or low-interest financing.
   But, Healy said, ``Their effect is weakening.''
   Incentives are offered in part to shrink inventories. According
to this week's edition of Ward's Automotive Reports, an industry
journal, the eight domestic automakers had a 67-day supply of new
cars on hand on May 31. That compares with a 56-day supply on the
same date last year.
   ``Inventories, although not a disaster, are kind of high now,''
Healy said. The early-spring incentives had been offered after the
sales year began with a sluggish start.
   Through June 10 this year, the domestic automakers said they were
selling cars and trucks at a rate of 37,935 a day, down 3.3 percent
from last year's daily rate of 39,235. Car sales were down 4.6
percent and truck sales were off 0.9 percent.
   During the first 10-day period of June, Ford's car sales were up
5.2 percent, GM's declined 0.7 percent and Chrysler's were down 6.7
percent. On the truck side, GM's sales rose 3.8 percent, Chrysler's
went up 4.6 percent and Ford's fell 3.9 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The sale report also includes cars made in the United States by
Honda, Toyota, Nissan, Mazda and Mitsubishi, all Japanese companies.
It does not include cars imported by any of the eight companies for
sale here.
</TEXT>
