<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0742EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GasDecontrol     06-15 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gas Decontrol,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Price Decontrol Bill Wins Easy Senate Approval</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires. With PM-Coal Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate approved legislation to end 35 years
of federal price controls on natural gas, with critics predicting
that decontrol would set the stage for a damaging round of price
increases in the early 1990s.
   The 82-17 vote in the Senate on Wednesday followed House approval
in April of a similar bill. Reltively minor differences between the
two are expected to be worked out fairly quickly to allow President
Bush to sign a bill into law this summer.
   Bush has made natural gas decontrol one of his top energy policy
priorities.
   Supporters of decontrol say it will help the energy industry by
spurring more drilling activity. Consumers will benefit because
supplies will increase, they say.
   But opponents, led on Capitol Hill by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, contend the legislation will lay a foundation for price
increases in a few years that would mean financial hardship for some
of the 48 million households heated by natural gas.
   ``The gas producers want to ride that rocket as far as it will
take them,'' Metzenbaum said in a floor speech before the vote.
``The consumers of this country are going to be hurt.''
   Ed Rothschild, assistant director of the Citizen-Labor Energy
Coalition, said the legislation was a cave-in to the financial
interests of the gas industry.
   ``The vote of a majority of the Senate gives gas producers
everything they've ever wanted and is making consumers pay for it,''
he said, adding that within two years natural gas prices probably
would be about 15 percent higher than today.
   About two-thirds of U.S. natural gas was decontrolled by the 1978
Natural Gas Policy Act. Of the remaining gas that still is
controlled, most is selling in the open market at prices below the
federal ceilings. So enactment of the decontrol legislation is not
expected to have much immediate effect on consumer prices.
   But many industry analysts believe prices will start rising
significantly in the early 1990s as a supply glut that has persisted
for much of this decade disappears.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., chief sponsor of the bill, said
consumers have nothing to fear from removal of the remaining
controls, since deregulation would fix ``dislocations'' in the
marketplace that serve to limit natural gas exploration.
   ``There'll be more drilling. More jobs will be produced in the
natural gas industry,'' he said, stressing that gas-producing states
such as his own would be major beneficiaries of a freer market.
   The gas industry, which lobbied hard for the legislation, cheered
the Senate vote.
   ``The Senate's passage of natural gas decontrol legislation is a
wonderful day for producers and consumers,'' said Nicholas J. Bush,
president of the Natural Gas Supply Association, the producers' main
trade group. He expressed confidence that the House and Senate
versions could be reconciled and sent to the president.
   The only significant difference between the bills is that the
House version provides for immediate decontrol of all gas produced
from wells drilled after March 23, 1989. The Senate bill contains no
such provision for ``new'' gas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
