<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FAA-Busey     06-15 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FAA-Busey,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Chairman Predicts New FAA Administrator Approval</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James B. Busey is headed towards quick Senate
approval as head of the Federal Aviation Administration, according
to Senators who ushered the four-star admiral through a congenial
confirmation hearing.
   They also told Busey on Wednesday that he could keep his status
as a retired military officer and collect his full pension even
though the law says the FAA administrator must be a civilian.
   Both Busey's confirmation and a bill that would provide an
exemption to allow him to collect the pension are likely to pass by
July 1, predicted Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the Senate
Commerce, Science and Transportation Committee.
   Busey told the committee on Wednesday that his priorities for
aviation would be safety, security and modernization of the civil
aviation system and pledged to keep a strong work force to monitor
the skies. He also pledged to listen to the advice of aviation
interest groups and others.
   ``I don't have any plans to do anything different from what is
done right now,'' Busey said, when asked by Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass,
if he would take additional steps to guarantee the safety of
financially troubled carriers such as Eastern Airlines.
   But Busey, who is retiring as commander of U.S. Naval forces in
Europe, pledged that ``any indication that safety procedures were
not being followed would trigger us into immediate action.''
   The former jet fighter pilot gave similar noncontroversial
responses throughout 90 minutes of questioning from a handful of
Senators.
   By the end of the hearing, only the committee chairman, Sen.
Wendell Ford, D-Ky., was left on the panel, and he predicted Busey
would win easy Senate approval.
   The FAA has been without an administrator since Allan McArtor
resigned in February. Busey apologized for the delay, saying the
time it took to be relieved of his overseas duties does not indicate
a lack of interest in the job.
   Both Democrats and Republicans on the committee expressed support
for Busey. No objections were raised to his nomination, and no
senator challenged anything the admiral said before the committee.
   Busey indicated much of his knowledge of issues affecting the FAA
had come from briefings he has received since being nominated by
President Bush.
   He said in written response to earlier questions from the
committee that he had no new suggestions for using the $6 billion
Airport Trust Fund, no proposals for improvement of FAA
procurements, no new initiatives for improving the air traffic
control system, no opinion on anti-collision systems or proposals
for head taxes at airports and was keeping an ``open mind'' on the
need for a national airliner noise policy and on the issue of
banning smoking on more commercial flights.
   Asked about proposals to make the FAA an independent agency,
separate from the Transportation Department, Busey said he has
agreed to work together with Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner.
   ``I do not come to this position seeking autonomy or
independence,'' he said in his written answer.
   Ford, who plans to introduce legislation giving the FAA autonomy,
asked Busey during the hearing to at least remain neutral on the
bill.
   Ford also advised Busey not to appoint a chief of staff who would
have authority over career officers in the agency and suggested that
he look into new FAA rules allowing airlines to maintain their
planes at foreign repair stations.
   Busey gave no response to the first suggestion. Addressing the
second, he said he would not approve overseas facilities where the
FAA could not assure their reliability and would revise the rules if
there is any indication safety might be compromised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
