<DOCNO> AP890615-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0744EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EnquirerCuts     06-15 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Enquirer Cuts,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Enquirer's New Owners Cut Staff, Xmas Display</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new owner of the National Enquirer and
Weekly World News said it would lay off 47 employees to cut costs
and would turn out the lights on the town's Christmas tree unless it
got some help.
   Michael Boylan, president of Macfadden Holdings Inc., said 20 of
270 employees would be laid off immediately at the Lantana
headquarters of the two supermarket tabloids. Departments affected
will include editorial and advertising, he said.
   Twenty-seven more employees will be laid off when the Pompano
Beach plant that prints the News closes July 19, he said. Printing
of the News, which sells about 1 million copies a week, will move to
Atlanta.
   Boylan also said the company can't afford to continue its annual
Christmas tree display without financial support from the community.
The display, which reportedly costs as much as $1 million, was begun
by the tabloids' former owner, the late Generoso Pope Jr.
   ``There's no way in the world we can throw a million-dollar
Christmas party on our own,'' Boylan said. ``Mr. Pope was Santa
Claus, and we just can't afford to be.''
   Macfadden bought the News and the Enquirer _ which sells 4.3
million copies weekly _ in April for $412.5 million. The company was
put up for sale after Pope died of a heart attack in October.
   Macfadden, whose titles include True Story, True Confessions and
Modern Romance, bought the News and the Enquirer with the financial
backing of Boston Ventures, a New York venture capital company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WeirtonStock     06-15 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weirton Stock,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weirton Steel Offers Stock on NYSE</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEIRTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its first day of trading on the big
board, Weirton Steel Corp.'s stock rose 63 cents a share to $15.125,
and more than 1.2 million shares traded hands.
   Weirton Steel went public Wednesday by offering 4 million shares
of its common stock for trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Employees of the nation's seventh-largest steelmaker and largest
worker-owned company in March approved a plan that reduces their
profit-sharing from 50 percent to 35 percent of the company's
after-tax income.
   The plan, which guarantees employee control of the company, also
allowed the public sale of stock.
   Weirton Steel stock opened at $14.50 a share and closed at
$15.125.
   The company announced the plan to go public in January. Officials
said it was part of a plan to fund a $650 million modernization
project. Under that 3-year project, the company will renovate its
continuous slab caster, blast furnaces and finishing mills and
complete its hot mill renovations.
   Weirton Steel produces and sells flat-rolled and coated carbon
steel. In 1988, it reported net income of $150 million on sales of
$1.4 billion.
   The company, which has about 8,000 employees, gives stock to
employees and former workers based of their annual earnings and the
coporation's earnings.
</TEXT>
