<FIRST>r f PM-Hunts-Bankruptcy     06-15 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hunts-Bankruptcy,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunt Brothers File Liquidation Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will stand. Hearing scheduled for 2 p.m. CDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uncle Sam would receive the lion's share of the
proceeds from the liquidation of the multimillion dollar holdings of
William Herbert and Nelson Bunker Hunt, but the former billionaires
would remain wealthy under their proposed settlement plans.
   The sons of wildcatter H.L. Hunt, pushed into bankruptcy by
lawsuits and Internal Revenue Service claims, want U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Harold Abramson to allow creditors to vote on the plan, which
would create liquidation trusts for each brother.
   A hearing was scheduled for today in Abramson's downtown Dallas
courtroom, but he is not expected to rule immediately.
   The brothers filed for protection from their creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code last year after a Peruvian
mining company won a $196 million judgment against them for their
attempt to corner the silver market in 1979 and 1980.
   The IRS also has multimillion-dollar claims against the brothers,
charging taht Bunker and his wife, Caroline, owe the government $600
million while Herbert and his wife, Nancy, owe $300 million.
   Bunker and Caroline Hunt have said they have about $258.83
million in assets to cover debt of more than $1.2 billion; Herbert
and Nancy value their assets at $169.38 million and debts of $887
million.
   Attorneys for some creditors objected to a similar plan presented
in April. Especially objectionable, they said, were provisions that
would allow the brothers control over the trusts and leave them with
millions of dollars in assets.
   ``The real creditors don't want the Hunts managing this,'' said
Hugh Ray, attorney for Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. of New York,
which claims the brothers owe the bank $36 million.
   The plans, filed Wednesday, contain the most detailed look yet at
the brothers holdings, ranging from Bunker Hunt's $10 silver
Churchill Commemorative Coin to his $19 million coin collection,
``the largest and most valuable privately held collection of ancient
coins in the world.''
   Besides the coins and another $3 million in vases, art,
porcelain, statues and jewelry, Bunker Hunt's holdings are a maze of
partial interests in Dallas-area real estate, oil and gas properties
worldwide and $7.36 million in cash.
   Herbert Hunt's assets include $3.95 million worth of producing
oil and gas leases, a $3.5 million collection of ancient bronze
statues and artifacts, $2 million worth of Byzantine coins, a home
worth $1.25 million and $1 million interest in the Dallas Bowling
Center.
   While the brothers' plans differ in detail, they both suggest
creating of a liquidation trust, which would sell off their holdings
over a six-year period to pay down their debts.
   In both plans, the IRS would get the largest chunk of the
proceeds _ 70 percent of Bunker Hunt's, 60 percent of Herbert Hunt's.
   On Wednesday, Abramson granted the brothers' request to dismiss
from the bankruptcy proceedings 601 claims from people who say they
lost $87.7 million because of the brothers' attempts to corner the
silver market.
   The ruling did not affect almost 600 claims amounting to about
$360 million stemming from the brothers' silver speculation.
Included in that is a reduced $134.6 million judgment in favor of
Minepaco, S.A., a Peruvian mining company.
   It was the judgment last year in favor of Minepaco that prompted
the brothers' Chapter 11 filings.
</TEXT>
