<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0841EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HiltonHotels     06-15 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hilton Hotels,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hilton Hotels Seeks To Boost Stock Price</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Hotels Corp., in a move that
could lead to the sale of all or part of the company, announced it
will explore strategies to boost its stock price.
   The action had been widely expected since the company's chairman,
Barron Hilton, won voting control of about 25 percent of Hilton
stock five weeks ago. He had been embroiled in a long legal battle
over the estate of his father, Conrad Hilton.
   Hilton stock jumped $3.12{ a share to close at $95.12{ on the New
York Stock Exchange Wednesday. The stock has climbed steadily from
$63 a share on May 8, the day the estate dispute was settled.
   According to a statement issued Wednesday, the company will hire
a financial adviser to help its board evaluate strategies ``to
optimize shareholder value.''
   Although several parties have expressed interest in the company
over the last five weeks, there have been no formal offers, said
Hilton vice president Roy Judge. He declined to name the prospective
investors.
   An investment adviser would be chosen in a week to 10 days, Judge
said.
   In addition to selling all or part of the company, Hilton could
opt to borrow money to pay stockholders a big dividend. Another
option analysts have suggested would be selling the company's hotels
and keeping its casinos in Las Vegas.
   ``My guess is they'll wind up selling the whole company because
tax law favors that alternative,'' said Daniel Lee, an analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York. ``Barron's made some big
hints that he was likely to sell the company.''
   The estate settlement ended a legal battle between Barron Hilton
and the Conrad N. Hilton Foundation over control of 13.5 million of
the company's 48.7 million stock shares. The foundation supports
travel and drug education and Roman Catholic nuns around the world.
   Conrad Hilton left the stock to the foundation when he died in
1979, but his son maintained through a nine-year legal wrangle he
was entitled to buy it at its 1979 market value.
   The settlement provided Barron Hilton with 4.1 million shares,
the foundation with 3.5 million, and the rest went into a trust with
income to be split 60-40 between Hilton and the foundation for the
next 20 years. Barron Hilton gets to vote the shares in the trust.
That, combined with his other holdings, gives him control of about
25 percent of the company.
   Hilton owns 11 hotels, including the Waldorf Astoria and the Las
Vegas and Flamingo Hiltons in Nevada, and manages 13 hotels it owns
in partnerships with others, including the Hilton Hawaiian Village
in Honolulu and Hiltons in San Francisco, Chicago, New York and
Washington. The company manages 21 hotels it doesn't have any
ownership interest in and franchises 225 Hilton Inns.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
