<FIRST>r f PM-HollyFarms     06-15 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Clears Way For Holly Farms Merger Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware Chancery Court has denied
Tyson Foods Inc.'s request to block ConAgra Inc.'s $1.3 billion
offer for Holly Farms Corp., essentially clearing the way for the
combination.
   Judge Maurice Hartnett on Wednesday also denied Tyson's bid to
force Holly Farms to redeem its poison-pill anti-takeover defense.
   ``Naturally we're pleased by the decision,'' said ConAgra vice
president Walt Casey.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry processor which has been
trying to acquire Memphis-based Holly Farms since last October, said
it still was not calling it quits.
   ``We have not given up and we have not lost our desire to try to
compete for Holly in some kind of fair environment if we can find
one,'' said Jim Blair, general counsel for Tyson.
   Tyson, based in Springdale, Ark., has offered $63.50 a share in
cash, or $1.1 billion for Holly Farms. That offer has been rejected
in favor of ConAgra's $70-a-share stock swap offer valued at $1.3
billion.
   Hartnett agreed with Tyson's argument that Holly managers favored
ConAgra in an auction for the company, but he said behind-the-scenes
dealing between Tyson and ConAgra justified such actions.
   ``It is the interest of the Holly Farms shareholders which must
be primarily considered,'' Hartnett said.
   Hartnett was told at a hearing earlier this month that Tyson
agreed to pay ConAgra $50 million to get out of the bidding for
Holly Farms but the deal fell through.
   In ruling to leave Holly Farms' ``poison pill'' intact, Hartnett
said there was no assurance Holly and ConAgra shareholders would
uphold the latest merger proposal and he said Tyson might be able to
buy enough Holly stock to block it.
   Shareholders are expected to vote on ConAgra's proposed merger
with Holly Farms next month.
</TEXT>
