<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 0937EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Paramount     06-15 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Paramount,0464</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Stock Continues Fluctuating As Company Remains Silent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. stock continued to fluctuate in the
absence of any word from the media giant on how it will fight
Paramount Communications Corp.'s unwanted $10.7 billion takeover bid.
   Time stock _ which rose $5 on Tuesday on speculation about a
higher bid from General Electric Co. _ fell $4.87{ to $175.12{ a
share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, Paramount rose $1.75 to $59.50 a share and Warner
Communications Inc., which still hopes to preserve its own pending
merger agreement with Time, was up 75 cents to $55 a share.
   Traders apparently speculated that Paramount might itself receive
a takeover bid and weren't discounting the possibility another
suitor might make an offer for Time higher than Paramount's
$175-a-share bid, said J. Kendrick Noble, an analyst with
PaineWebber Inc.
   Time gave no hint as to its plans, leaving investors to buy on
speculation alone.
   The board was expected to meet sometime this week to discuss the
media giant's strategy, but spokesman Edward Adler refused to
comment on whether the board met Wednesday.
   Even if no formal meeting was scheduled, it was likely the
directors were in contact about the situation.
   Among the options the Time board was believed to be considering
were a recapitalization of the company, a cash tender offer for
Warner, a cash tender offer for Paramount or a continued pursuit of
its planned merger with Warner. Warner also could launch a cash
tender offer for Time.
   ``I really feel the picture is unpredictable at this point,''
Noble said, but he added, ``I think the original merger as proposed
is probably dead.''
   The Time-Warner merger likely would have to be renegotiated
because of the surge in Time's stock price since the Paramount bid
was announced last week. Time shares were trading at $126 before
Paramount announced its offer, and the Time-Warner agreement was
based on the lower stock price.
   Under the planned merger, Time stockholders would get a share in
the new company for each share they own while Warner shareholders
would get 0.465 of a share of the new company for each of their
Warner shares.
   On Tuesday, Time _ in one of the few public moves the company has
made since the Paramount bid was announced last week _ asked the
Federal Communications Commission to deny a Paramount request to
create a voting trust for Time stock.
   The trust would allow Paramount to purchase Time's shares pending
FCC approval of the transfer of cable television franchises and
licenses held by Time's 82-percent-owned cable TV unit, American
Television and Communications Corp.
</TEXT>
