<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-MCorp 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-MCorp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Holding Company Reports Loss of Nearly $1 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS in lede and 6th graf to show that banks had $13.4 million
loss, sted profit, in 1st quarter.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp lost nearly $1 billion last year, but the
five banks that it retains narrowed their loss to $13.4 million in
the first quarter, according to the bank holding company.
   Federal regulators seized 20 of the company's 25 subsidiary banks
in March, pushing it into protection from creditors under Chapter 11
of the bankruptcy code. The five remaining banks are profitable and
solvent, although some do not meet federal capital requirements.
   MCorp's loss last year totaled $977.9 million, a figure that was
held down by a $215.5 million gain from the sale of Dallas-based
MCorp's 80 percent interest in MTech, a data-processing company, in
the second quarter last year.
   MCorp said it lost control of the 20 banks last Oct. 1, and
write-offs in connection with their closing account for a large
portion of the losses.
   MCorp said in a news conference Wednesday it is confident it can
emerge from Chapter 11 as a profitable company.
   Joe Stroop, a spokesman, said the banks' $13.4 million loss in
the first quarter does not reflect MCorp's fully earning potential.
   The first-quarter bank figures, obtained from Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. reports, also do not include performance of other
holding company subsidiaries, including a trust bank that probably
earned a profit, said Frank Anderson, bank analyst with Stephens
Inc. in Little Rock, Ark.
   The financial services company's 1988 loss was nearly four times
the $258 million shortfall for the previous year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
