<FIRST>r f BC-BPCoalSale     06-15 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BP Coal Sale,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>BP Offers Most Coal Reserves for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a move designed to focus more closely on its
core oil business, British Petroleum Co. PLC announced Thursday that
it has put most of its worldwide coal operations up for sale.
   BP said in a statement it hoped to sell its Cleveland-based BP
Coal subsidiary to a single buyer but would consider selling some
properties individually. The company has retained Chase Manhattan
Bank is its financial adviser.
   BP Coal has 3,350 employees and reported 1988 revenues of $959
million. Last year the company produced 32 million tons of coal.
   ``In line with BP's strategy of focusing increasingly on oil,
gas, chemicals and the varied opportunities presented in the
nutrition sector, we believe we have now reached the point where our
coal interests are likely to offer greater value to a company in the
coal or mining sector,'' said BP Managing Director Patrick Gillam.
   London-based BP said it hoped the sale would be completed by the
end of the year.
   BP Coal has 2.1 billion tons of extractable coal reserves,
including operations in the United States, Australia, South Africa
and Europe.
   About 40 percent of the reserves are in the United States, where
BP Coal's production totaled 17.9 million tons last year, or 56
percent of its total.
</TEXT>
