<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed On Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and wheat futures were mostly lower and
soybeans were narrowly mixed in early trading on the Chicago Board
of Trade, reflecting some profit-taking after the sharp gains of the
past two sessions.
   Losses in the corn and soybean markets were limited, though, by a
National Weather Service Forecast for warmer- and drier-than-normal
conditions in the Midwest next week.
   The forecast, issued late Wednesday, followed a similarly
warm-and-dry 30-day outlook for the region. The 30-day National
Weather Service forecast came out on Tuesday and sparked the
strongest one-day rally in 10 months Wednesday in the corn and
soybean markets.
   Selling of soybean futures was also limited by news of a
smaller-than-expected devaluation of the Brazilian currency. Brazil
is the world's second-largest soybean producer.
   Good harvest weather in the Great Plains kept pressure on wheat
futures prices.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.97 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1\ cents lower with July at $2.56} a bushel; oats were \ cent
lower to } cents higher with July at $1.68 a bushel; soybeans were 3
cents lower to 4{ cents higher with July at $7.29{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .05 cent higher with June at
70.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent lower to .08 cent
higher with August at 80.50 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to
.25 cent higher with June at 47.50 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .37 cent to .50 cent higher with July at 34.15 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
