<FIRST>r f PM-Dunkin'Donuts     06-15 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dunkin' Donuts,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Canadian Companies Launch Bid For Dunkin' Donuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Canadian firms, Unicorp Canada Corp. and Cara
Operations Ltd. launched a hostile $305.3 million tender offer today
for Dunkin' Donuts Inc.
   The $43-a-share offer replaces a friendly $298.2 million bid
rejected by Dunkin' Donuts last month. Richard Hart, Dunkin' Donuts
vice president and treasurer, said the company would not comment on
the offer announced today.
   Dunkin' Donuts stock was up 50 cents to $40.12{ a share in early
over-the-counter trading today.
   Unicorp's merchant banking arm, Kingsbridge Capital Group, owns
about 12 percent of Dunkin' Donuts' 7.1 million outstanding shares.
   Dunkin' Donuts, a Randolph, Mass.-based chain with approximately
1,700 franchise shops, has set up a series of takeover defenses,
including a ``poison pill'' shareholder rights plan and an employee
stock ownership plan.
   The company also has bought back more than 350,000 shares of its
stock and sold 28,000 shares of preferred stock for $28 million to
General Electric Capital Corp.
   Unicorp spokesman Eric W. Evans said his company would file a
lawsuit today in Delaware Chancery Court challenging the ESOP, stock
buyback and preferred stock sale. Dunkin' Donuts is incorporated in
Delaware.
   Evans said Unicorp and Cara Operations have formed an equal
partnership to make the cash bid. He said they do not yet have
financing commitments, but have ``had discussions with two large
banks that have givenus letters of interest'' in financing the deal.
   Unicorp. is Canada's 15th largest company, with assets of $5.8
billion Canadian dollars. It has three main businesses: natural gas
distribution and energy services; Lincoln Savings Bank in New York
City and a U.S. real estate portfolio; and merchant banking.
   Cara Operations is a food services company provides airline
catering and runs duty free stores in 12 Canadian airports. It has
two large franchised restaurant chains: 125 Swiss Chalet family
restaurants in the United States and Canada and 230 Harvey's
hamburger restaurants in Canada.
</TEXT>
