<DOCNO> AP890615-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-SEC-Herrlinger     06-15 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SEC-Herrlinger,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Bars Bogus Stock Bidder Herrlinger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has
barred a Cincinnati stockbroker from the securities business but
said he could be reinstated if he gets a clean bill of health from a
psychiatrist.
   The broker, P. David Herrlinger, caused an uproar on Wall Street
on June 23, 1987 when he called Dow Jones News Service and announced
a bogus $6.8 billion offer to buy Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson
Corp., one of the nation's biggest retailers.
   Speculators responding to the Dow Jones report of the purported
$70 a share bid sent the price of Dayton Hudson stock soaring by as
much as $9 a share in heavy trading. The price later tumbled after
Herrlinger's attorney reported the offer was a hoax.
   Herrlinger was fired by Capital Management Corp., an investment
counseling firm, the same day and subsequently hospitalized. He was
diagnosed as suffering from manic depression.
   The SEC sued Herrlinger in July 1987 for securities law
violations and alleged he profited by trading Dayton Hudson stock
options through his brother _ a stockbroker in Albuquerque, N.M. _
before and after making the bogus bid.
   Herrlinger also has been sued by several investors who claim they
lost money due to the false offer.
   Herrlinger's lawyer, Anthony Covatta, said Thursday that the SEC
seemed to understand that ``on the day of the big event Mr.
Herrlinger wasn't himself.''
   ``He didn't get off totally unsullied by the SEC, but certainly
the sanctions are less than they could have been,'' Covatta said.
   Herrlinger will be allowed to reapply for admission to the
securities industry in one year but must first obtain a
psychiatrist's certification that he is mentally stable, according
to the settlement agreement handed down Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-InsuranceTaxes     06-15 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Insurance Taxes,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Resolves Tax Dispute Between IRS and Insurance Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today resolved a tax dispute
between the insurance industry and the Internal Revenue Service in a
decision dealing a significant financial setback to many insurance
companies.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, ruled that the ``ceding
commissions'' a life insurance company pays when reinsuring another
firm's policies may not be claimed as deductions for the year they
are paid.
   Instead, the court ruled that any tax deductions for those
commission payments must be spread out over the anticipated life of
the policy.
   ``We have concluded that ceding commissions are costs incurred to
acquire an asset with an income-producing life that may extend
substantially beyond one year,'' Justice Anthony M. Kennedy wrote
for the court.
   ``General tax principles provide that such costs must be
amortized and capitalized over the useful life of the asset,'' he
said.
   The IRS refused to let Colonial American Life Insurance Co., a
Louisiana-based corporation, claim some $1.5 million in such
deductions for 1975 and 1976.
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the tax agency's
refusal, but other federal appeals courts had allowed such
deductions.
   Colonial American in 1975 and 1976 agreed to partially indemnify
Transport Life Insurance Co. policies. In return, Colonial American
became entitled to the same percentage of future premiums received
on the policies.
   The agreement required Colonial American to pay Transport ceding
commissions in consideration for the business acquired. The
commissions totaled $680,000 in 1975 and $852,000 in 1976.
   Colonial American then sought to deduct as business losses the
full amount of the commissions in the years they were paid.
   The court, calling the commission payments investments in the
future, today said the IRS correctly disallowed the immediate,
lump-sum deductions.
   Justices John Paul Stevens, Harry A. Blackmun and Sandra Day
O'Connor dissented.
   The case is Colonial American Life vs. Commissioner, Internal
Revnue, 88-396.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0256 </DOCNO>
