<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Buchanan-Penalities     06-15 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Buchanan-Penalities,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Firm Penalized For Bond Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Association of Securities
Dealers has penalized managers at the investment firm Buchanan &amp; Co.
for wrongdoing in the underwriting and sale of $250 million in
tax-free bonds that later defaulted.
   Robert M. Buchanan Jr., owner and chairman of the defunct
Jackson-based company, was fined $200,000, censured, suspended from
the NASD for two years and banned from control of any NASD-member
company.
   The penalties were imposed after company officials ``consented to
findings that they engaged in deceptive, dishonest or unfair
practices'' in the underwriting and sale of bonds, the NASD said in
a news release Wednesday.
   NASD spokesman Enno Hobbing said the officials' consent statement
neither admitted nor denied guilt and was similar to a
``no-contest'' plea.
   Company officials had insisted that they were innocent of any
wrongdoing.
   Buchanan's business plummeted after reports in 1987 that
thousands of investors had been left holding worthless paper from
bonds _ mostly for nursing homes and retirement centers _ that were
underwritten by the company.
   The company, which in its heyday had 150 employees in six states
and annual sales approaching $300 million, filed for
bankruptcy-court protection last December and has been sued by
numerous investors in several states.
   Besides Buchanan, the NASD imposed penalties on the company's
president, Robert C. Fairly, who was censured, fined $20,000,
suspended from the NASD for a year and prohibited from being a
principal in an NASD company for five years.
   Lesser penalties were imposed on branch managers Jonathan D.
Ulrich, Russell W. Clark, Murl D. Calton, Jeffrey D. Rhodes, Kenneth
C. Weber and Mary S. Nelson and on salesmen Kenneth E. Crowl,
Randall J. White, Lorin W. Surpless, Gerard P. Musto and William B.
Nelson.
   The NASD said Buchanan and Fairly were responsible for
misrepresenting and omitting facts in the sale of 10 municipal bond
issues worth $74.47 million.
   The NASD also found that ``the firm, acting through Buchanan and
Fairly, orchestrated a high-pressure, misleading retail sales
campaign for these bonds, as well as for other high-yield, non-rated
bonds.''
   Many of the bonds were sold to fixed-income investors at free
seminars in retirement areas such as Tucson, Ariz., and Tampa, Fla.
   A colleague of Buchanan's at another investment office where he
is currently working said he was out of town and unavailable for
comment today. Fairly's daughter also said he was unavailable for
comment today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
