<DOCNO> AP890615-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv16   06-15 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 16,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Friday June 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lower Rates Boost Bond Funds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent decline in interest rates has stirred
up new enthusiasm for mutual funds that invest in bonds.
   When rates decline, as they have since early spring this year,
prices of existing bonds naturally tend to rise. That gives owners
of bond-fund shares a shot at capital gains from the funds' rising
net asset values, on top of the interest they earn.
   For all but the wealthiest individual investors, financial
advisers widely recommend picking a mutual fund or other packaged
vehicle rather than shopping for individual bonds.
   ``We think smart investors should avoid individual issues,''
analysts at the Value Line Investment Survey say in a recent
commentary.
   For one thing, Value Line says, funds provide a diversified
portfolio for even the smallest investments. Diversification reduces
credit risk _ the potential losses you might suffer should an
individual bond issuer default.
   ``Diversification is especially important with long bonds _ even
governments, which have no credit risk _ because the manager has the
ability to select the mix of maturities and coupon rates he or she
considers the most desirable,'' Value Line observes.
   ``A long-term bond fund reduces transaction costs, especially if
the investor has limited his consideration to funds with no
front-end load, redemption or other charges.
   ``The major advantage the fund offers an individual, in addition
to professional management, is its buying power. One million dollars
is the typical trading unit.
   ``Because the fund managers are in the marketplace every day
dealing in large amounts with many brokers, they usually can obtain
advantageous prices on both sales and purchases.
   ``The individual owner of, say, $10,000 worth of bonds will
probably not do nearly as well.''
   Another advantage funds offer is automatic reinvestment in new
fund shares of dividends and any capital gains distributions that
shareholders decide not to receive as cash payouts.
   Investors pay a price for these benefits, of course, even in
funds which impose no sales or redemption charges. Operating
expenses and management fees are collected from the assets of a
fund, thus effectively lowering the yield that flows through to
shareholders.
   Another characteristic of bond funds that some people find
troublesome is their lack of a stated maturity date. Because fund
portfolios are continuously managed, their life span is indefinite.
   So, you cannot tell in advance what the dollar value of your
investment will be when you cash it in, whether you do that six
months or 30 years from now.
   An alternative to bond funds is a unit trust, a package of
securities assembled by a brokerage firm and resold to investors in
small pieces with a predetermined maturity date.
   ``When buying a unit trust, you know what securities are
contained in it, now and when it matures,'' says George Bernard,
senior vice president-unit trusts at the investment firm of Gruntal
&amp; Co.
   ``In the case of a bond unit trust, you'll know what it will be
worth at maturity.''
   Unlike no-load mutual funds, unit trusts typically are offered
with an up-front sales charge. If you hold them for a long period,
however, this cost may be offset by the lower operating expenses and
fees that come with the trusts' fixed portfolios.
   A big selling point with mutual funds is the ease of getting your
money in and out of them on short notice, whenever you wish.
   Most sponsors of unit trusts also state their willingness to cash
in some or all of your investment before maturity. In that
situation, the price you get for your units, as with mutual fund
shares, will be subject to the ups and downs of the credit markets.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday June 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
