<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-LisaJones     06-15 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-Lisa Jones,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies Ex-Drexel Trader Request for New Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has denied a request for a new
trial by a former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. assistant trader
convicted of perjury.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard B. Sand on Wednesday ruled that the
lawyer for Lisa Jones, 26, was too late in filing a request that the
judge declare a mistrial and order a new trial.
   Sand said the request had to be filed within seven days of the
verdict. Jones was convicted March 22 of five counts of perjury and
two of obstruction of justice for lying to a federal grand jury
investigating insider trading involving Drexel.
   Jones' attorney, Daniel Bookin, said in court last month that the
deadline for filing the mistrial motion had passed when he was hired
in mid-April to represent her.
   The request for a retrial was based in part on an allegation that
Bookin's predecessor, who also represented other Drexel employees,
had a conflict of interest in representing Jones.
   But Sand ruled he had found no reason to believe that Jones had
been denied a fair trial.
   ``What was truly damaging to Ms. Jones was her apparent inability
to tell the truth while sitting on the witness stand at trial,'' the
judge said.
   Jones faces a total of 35 years in jail and up to $1.75 million
in fines. Sentencing is scheduled for June 28.
</TEXT>
