<FIRST>r f BC-BoeingOrders     06-15 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing Orders,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing Gets $400 Million in Orders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. said it has received orders for four of
its aircraft from Lufthansa German Airlines and Maersk Air of
Denmark in deals valued at a total of around $400 million.
   Lufthansa converted three options for Boeing 747-400s to firm
orders valued at about $375 million, Boeing said Wednesday. The
planes are scheduled for delivery in 1991.
   The new orders bring to 15 the number of long-range 747-400s
ordered by Lufthansa. Four of those are combination models capable
of carrying passengers or being used to transport cargo only.
   Maersk Air, an independent Danish carrier, ordered one Boeing
737-500 jet valued at $24 million to $28 million.
   The airline had previously ordered three of the jets. The new
planes are scheduled for delivery in 1990.
   The jets will replace the carrier's fleet of 737-200s, said
Maersk Air President Bjarne Hansen.
   The Maersk Air order brings to 151 the total number of 737-500s
on order, from 17 customers.
   Orders for all types of Boeing jetliners for the year now total
604, valued at about $33.2 billion, the company said in a statement.
</TEXT>
