<FIRST>r f PM-Coleco-Hasbro     06-15 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coleco-Hasbro,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coleco To Sell Assets To Hasbro</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled toymaker Coleco Industries Inc.
has agreed to sell most of its assets to rival Hasbro Industries
Inc. for $85 million in cash, the companies announced today.
   Coleco, which is operating under bankruptcy court protection,
will also receive warrants to purchase a million shares of Hasbro
stock. A hearing on the agreement, which is subject to court
approval, will be held within 30 days.
   Under the agreement, Pawtucket, R.I.-based Hasbro will buy
certain accounts receivable and inventory of Coleco, the maker of
Cabbage Patch dolls. The deal is subject to the approval of
Appalachian Artworks Inc., creator of Cabbage Patch Kids, Coleco
directors and completion by July 17.
   Coleco and Hasbro, the nation's largest toymaker, also have
entered into a management consulting agreement providing for
Hasbro's active participation in Coleco's business operations up to
the closing of the transaction.
   The 57-year-old Coleco grew to be one of the nation's largest toy
companies during the past decade, propelled in part by the success
of its Cabbage Patch dolls.
   But demand for the dolls dropped in 1986, and Coleco failed to
make up for lost sales. Coleco filed for bankruptcy protection a
year ago, listing debts of $540.3 million.
   Coleco said its committee of unsecured creditors, which late last
month dropped a $71 million lawsuit against the company's largest
creditors, has approved the agreement with Hasbro.
</TEXT>
