<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1353EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-S&amp;Ls 3rdLd-Writethru   06-15 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0926</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Defeats Attempt To Weaken Bush S&amp;L Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with House defeating Hyde amendment, picking
up 3rd pvs, It was; CORRECTS figure to $44 billion sted $50 billion in
13th graf, Foley predicted; CORRECTS number of senators to 41 sted 42 in
14th graf, However, budget; trims below for length; moving general news
wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today defeated an attempt to blunt
the key reform in savings and loan bailout legislation after
President Bush threatened to veto a watered-down bill.
   The vote was 326-94, with 114 Republicans and 212 Democrats
supporting the president. Fifty-six Republicans and 38 Democrats
opted to support the S&amp;L industry on the heavily lobbied issue of
capital.
   Bush is insisting that the government force S&amp;Ls to back their
lending with more of their own capital.
   Rep. Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., tried unsuccessfully to provide an
exemption for S&amp;Ls that previously received an accounting break,
known as ``supervisory good will,'' in exchange for taking ailing
institutions off the government's hands in the early 1980s.
   The accounting break allows some of the acquiring S&amp;Ls to operate
without risking any of their owners' money. Hyde's amendment would
have permitted 241 S&amp;Ls that would fail tougher capital standards to
appeal administratively for an exemption.
   ``No result is mandated'' in the hearings, Hyde said, ``just a
chance to make your case ... before the scarlet letter is painted on
your forehead.''
   However, critics complained the procedure would burden regulators
and effectively delay Bush's key reform by 18 months for a
significant portion of the industry.
   ``Make no mistake about it. This amendment guts the bill. ...
What this amendment does is allow those very weak institutions to
delay and delay and delay the day of reckoning. And while they delay
and delay and delay, the taxpayers will pay and pay and pay,'' said
Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a member of the House Banking
Committee.
   Bush, in a letter to House Republican Leader Bob Michel of
Illinois, made it clear he would veto the S&amp;L bill if it included
Hyde's proposal.
   ``Giving recognition to good will as capital or creating
procedural changes that could have the same effect is not
justifiable,'' the president wrote. ``Each of the amendments to the
tough capital standards ... would render this bill unacceptable to
me.''
   It was the first time that Bush made the veto threat, although
his advisers have said previously they would recommend that action
if Congress watered down the president's capital reforms.
   ``There should be no mistake. This matter goes to the very heart
of my determination to clean up the abuses of the past among the
savings and loans, about which every voter is entitled to be
outraged,'' Bush wrote.
   Meanwhile, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said he would
keep the House in session late tonight and that he was determined to
pass the bill by Friday.
   Foley predicted the House also would pass an amendment forcing
the administration to count $44 billion in S&amp;L bailout spending as
part of the budget deficit, setting up a conflict with the Senate.
   However, budget director Richard Darman told reporters today,
``It may be that it's an utterly academic question.'' Sen. Phil
Gramm, R-Texas, has collected signatures from 41 Republican senators
pledging to support Bush's funding plan.
   That effectively scuttles Democratic attempts in the House to
alter it, because any change must be approved by 60 out of 100
senators.
   The president met with congressional leaders on Wednesday, for
the first time lobbying in person to perserve his capital reforms.
Thumping the table in the Cabinet Room, he said, ``Every American
citizen has every right in the world to be disturbed and shocked by
this situation.''
   Bush's bill, the largest government bailout in history, would
spend $285 billion over 30 years _ $157 billion from taxpayers _ to
protect S&amp;L depositors, according to the congressional General
Accounting Office. It also proposes a series of changes designed to
prevent the most serious financial crisis since the Depression from
recurring.
   In addition to requiring S&amp;Ls to risk more capital, the bill
reorganizes the regulatory bureaucracy to give the administration
greater control over S&amp;Ls and it provides money to the Justice
Department to prosecute fraud at thrift institutions.
   The Senate passed its own version of the bill in April and
congressional aides expect a conference committee to take at least
until mid-July to resolve differences between the two chambers.
   On Wednesday, the House voted 330-95 to adopt procedures limiting
debate on the bill to 15 amendments, including measures that would:
   _Forbid S&amp;Ls from investing in junk bonds.
   _Strengthen the law prohibiting banks and S&amp;Ls from
discriminating against poor and minority neighborhoods.
   _Delete a provision requiring the industry-owned Federal Home
Loan Banks to subsidize housing for poor people.
   A few members objected to the decision by the
Democratic-controlled Rules Committee to prohibit a vote on an
amendment offered by Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who wants to delete
provisions granting special exemptions to individual institutions
and companies.
   ``There's pork in there,'' warned Rep. Robert Walker, R-Pa.,
ticking off a list of companies that succeeded in winning
concessions, including such well-known names as Sears, Roebuck &amp;
Co.; Merrill Lynch; and Chemical Bank.
   ``This is wrong,'' agreed Rep. Tim Valentine, D-N.C. ``This is
the Congress of the United States at its worst.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0265 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Cable-Foreign     06-15 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable-Foreign,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Back Bill to Limit Foreign Ownership of Cable Companies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese governmental action to control
television coverage of citizen protests in China was raised Thursday
as a reason to limit foreign ownership of cable companies in the
United States.
   ``I am not troubled to know that, here in our nation's capital,
the Chinese government could continue its control of a fashionable
restaurant,'' Andrew Jay Schwartzman, executive director of Media
Access Project, told a House subcommittee. ``I would be troubled if
that regime, or persons subject to its domination, owned and
operated Channel 4 or D.C. Cable.''
   His opinion was echoed by witnesses supporting legislation
sponsored by Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., that would limit foreign
ownership of cable companies in this country to 20 percent.
   Such restrictions already exist in other facets of the industry,
such as broadcast stations and common carrier properties.
   Markey said his bill would close a loophole opened when cable
television grew into the method by which 80 percent of American
homes receive TV programs.
   ``This is not a question of protectionism, but of national
interest and national security,'' he said.
   ``The recent Chinese experience most clearly illustrates the
power television has in informing and educating a nation, and the
important role of the electronic media serve in facilitating the
free flow of information,'' he said.
   Those opposed to the bill said it was unnecessary and would not
only hurt foreign cable companies already operating here but also
encourage retaliation against U.S. business abroad.
   Former Federal Communications Commissioner Robert E. Lee said
there was ample authority in federal law to seize property of aliens
in time of war.
   ``Also consider the two biggest issues facing our economy today _
the twin deficits of budget and trade,'' he said. ``The complicated
trade deficit appears to have shown some slight improvement recently
but every foreign investment that is made in this country helps to
ease that problem.''
   In opposition to the bill, a letter from former Secretary of
Commerce Elliot Richardson, who now heads the Association for
Foreign Investment in America, was submitted to the House Energy and
Commerce subcommittee on telecommunications and finance, which held
the hearings.
   ``Sectoral restrictions on foreign investment not only undermine
the traditional U.S. policy to reduce barriers to international
investment, but also encourage retaliation against United States
business abroad,'' he said.
   Markey, who introduced the bill Wednesday, said additional views
would be gathered before action is taken on the measure.
   ``My view is that we can construct something that makes some
sense,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
