<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved sharply lower today,
weighed down by weakness in bond prices and futures-related selling.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 32.84 to 2,470.52
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Declining issues outpaced advances by a wide margin, with 1,079
down, 337 up and 487 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 129.73 million shares with two
hours left to go in the session.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks slid
1.89 to 178.94.
   A downturn in bond prices spilled over into the stock market,
analysts said. Today's weakness in the credit market, which recently
has rallied on rising optimism that a robust dollar would attract
foreign investors, coincided with a decline in the dollar.
   Wall Street analysts also said trading maneuvers related to
stock-index futures contributed to the selloff. Stocks are being
sold ahead of Friday's ``triple witching hour'' when stock-index
futures, index options and options on individual stocks expire.
   Takeover stocks continued to figure on the list of actively
traded NYSE-listed issues.
   Warner Communications was the most heavily traded stock on volume
of nearly 2.3 million shares and was up 1\ to 56\. Paramount
Communications, the second most heavily traded stock, fell | to 58~
while Time declined 2[ to 173.
   Monsanto rose 2 to 106. The company announced settlement of a
dispute involving an intrauterine device.
