<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: new throughout with closing index, comments, no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices finished mostly lower Thursday on the
back of early losses on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index lost 4.0
points, or 0.2 percent, to close at 2,129.6. The index spent most of
the day in positive territory, rising a maximum 9.6 points shortly
after the opening.
   The Financial Times 30-share index also was down 4.0 points at
1,758.9 at the close. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 2.07
points to close at 1,214.00.
   Volume picked up sharply to 593.4 million shares, boosted by a
moderately large program trade early in the day. By comparison,
there were 467.6 million shares traded Wednesday.
   The market opened on a buoyant note, with continued buying
interest with speculation running high that U.S. trade figures would
show a narrowing of the trade deficit.
   The U.S. trade deficit did narrow in April _ to $8.26 billion
from $9.54 billion in March. But since the figures, announced at
midday local time, were in line with economists' forecasts, equities
showed little response.
   What pulled support out from under the market was a disheartening
performance on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average
was down nearly 20 points as London trading came to a close.
</TEXT>
