<FIRST>r f BC-AppleCode     06-15 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Apple Code,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Code Theft Under Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The theft of an ultra-secret computer
code used to design Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh is being
investigated by federal authorities and the Santa Clara County
district attorney's office, it was reported Thursday.
   The San Francisco Examiner quoted an unidentified source close to
Apple as saying federal officials had joined the probe, but Apple
spokeswoman Carleen LeVasseur confirmed only that local prosecutors
were involved in the case.
   ``Any details regarding the investigation are confidential until
we have identified an individual,'' she said.
   Floppy disks with the code, which is supposed to be restricted to
a small number of Apple employees, have been sent to various people
along with a letter signed by the ``New Prometheus League.''
   The name stems from the Greek Titan who stole fire from heaven
and gave it to man. Prometheus was later chained and tortured by
Zeus for the theft.
   Apple officials have said the code is the basis of the company's
``intellectual property,'' and they will seek to have the pirates
prosecuted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890615-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1541EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Superfund     06-15 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Superfund,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reilly Predicts Long, Expensive Effort to Clean Toxic Waste Dumps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Environmental Protection Agency
predicted on Thursday that a long, expensive effort will be needed
to clean the nation's toxic waste dumps and he suggested the public
may have expected too much of the cleanup drive begun nine years ago.
   ``There's no magic wand that I can wave to make this problem go
away,'' EPA Administrator William Reilly told a Senate subcommittee.
   Meanwhile, the Supreme Court ruled 5-4 that states may be
required through private lawsuits to help pay for cleaning up
hazardous waste sites targeted under the Superfund law.
   The justices decided that the Constitution gives Congress the
power to strip state governments of their immunity from private
lawsuits. The decision will force Pennsylvania to defend itself
against a suit by Union Gas Co. aimed at recovering cleanup costs
the company owes the federal government.
   In his testimony to a Senate panel dealing with Superfund
matters, Reilly outlined an internal EPA report that suggested
cleaning up the nearly 1,200 toxic sites on the current cleanup
schedule will cost at least $30 billion and not be completed until
into the next century. By then, another 1,000 sites are expected to
be singled out for decontamination, possibly costing just as much,
according to EPA estimates.
   Reilly listed changes he plans for his agency's toxic cleanup
program, including giving more emphasis on increased enforcement to
force polluters _ and not the government _ to clean the waste dumps.
   Reilly noted that Congress so far has provided nearly $10 billion
for the Superfund program but that cleanup has been completed in
only a handful of sites.
   In separate testimony, the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, said the latest EPA figues show that
of the nearly 1,200 toxic dumps on the decontamination list, actual
cleanup has been completed on only 41 sites and begun on another 204.
   Reilly said that, because of money and manpower shortages, often
a choice must be made between ``either complete cleanup at some
sites, or incremental cleanup at many sites.''
   ``Even if more funds were available ... EPA lacks sufficient
expert staff and the nation doesn't have enough qualified engineers
to take on a full-scale effort at all sites simultaneously,'' Reilly
continued.
   Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., subcommittee chairman, lauded
Reilly for some of the changes he envisions in the Superfund
program, including focusing more on taking polluters to court to
force them to clean up contaminated sites.
   As part of new emphasis on enforcement against polluters, the EPA
will shift $75 million from accounts used to hire outside cleanup
contractors and use it to hire 500 additional lawyers and cleanup
site supervisers.
   The EPA chief promised the agency would use ``all the enforcement
tools at its disposal'' in the enforcement actions including the
threat of seeking treble civil damages from polluters. The clear
threat of legal action ``will create a better environment for
settlement,'' he said.
   At the Supreme Court, Justice William J. Brennan, writing the
court's main opinion, said the Superfund law ``renders states liable
in money damages in federal court,'' and added that ``Congress has
the authority to render them so liable when legislating pursuant to
the (Constitution's) Commerce Clause.''
   He was joined fully by Justices Thurgood Marshall, Harry A.
Blackmun and John Paul Stevens and, in part, by Justice Byron R.
White.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Antonin Scalia,
Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy voted to dismiss the suit
against Pennsylvania. They said the state's immunity should prevail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
