<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-USTrade     06-15 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Japanese Officials Discussing Trade Barriers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Japanese officials disagreed Thursday on
whether their talks on elimination of Japanese market barriers this
week fell under the ``Super 301'' clause of the 1988 trade act.
   Japanese officials said they repeated to their American
counterparts their refusal to negotiate under the clause, which
provides for penalties for nations that do not agree to open their
markets within 18 months.
   The high-level trade talks, which ended Wednesday, were the first
since Japan was named a ``priority'' nation last month under the
trade act because of its alleged restrictions on U.S. satellites,
supercomputers and forestry products.
   U.S. and Japanese officials said they had agreed in the talks to
focus in the future on eliminating ``structural'' barriers, such as
Japan's complex distribution system and the United States' low
savings rate, that thwarted attempts to reduce the huge bilateral
trade imbalance.
   ``We have a large trade deficit with Japan that has not responded
to the dollar-yen changes in ways that we thought were
appropriate,'' said Undersecretary of State Richard McCormack, who
led the U.S. delegation.
   ``It is very important that we seek ways to increase American
exports to this country and deal with some of the structural
impediments that we feel are hindering those exports.''
   Trade friction between the two nations flared last month after
the United States charged Japan with unfair trading practices. But
officials from both sides, in separate briefings for reporters
Thursday, said this week's talks emphasized cooperation.
   ``We will not go into negotiations with the understanding there
will be retaliation if no successful resolution can be found,'' said
Mitoji Yabunaka, director of the Foreign Ministry's Second North
American Division. ``It's their law, and doesn't bind Japan at all.''
   But U.S. officials said they interpreted this week's trade talks
as a first step in the negotiations required under the ``Super 301''
provision.
   ``We do consider the discussions ... to be consultations within
the context of our Trade Act,'' said Deputy U.S. Trade
Representative Linn Williams.
   Meanwhile, U.S. Ambassador Michael Armacost met Thursday with
Ryutaro Hashimoto, secretary general of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party.
   Hashimoto pledged Japan would do its best to solve trade problems
but criticized the U.S. decision to invoke the ``Super 301'' clause
against Japan, saying, ``We don't like to negotiate with a pistol
pointed at us,'' Kyodo News Service reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
