<DOCNO> AP890615-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Goldome-Severance     06-15 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Goldome-Severance,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Thrift Demands Silence of Former Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual move that has embittered
current and former employees, Goldome bank has threatened to cut the
severance pay of laid-off workers if they talk to the media about
losing their jobs.
   As many as 150 people have been terminated in recent weeks and
asked to sign a ``Release and Confidentiality Agreement,'' according
to sources within the company.
   The agreement prevents ex-workers from suing Goldome or
discussing their layoff with anyone except ``counsel, personal tax
advisor, immediate family or as required by law.''
   If laid-off employees refuse to sign, their severance benefits
will be cut to two weeks pay from a maximum of six.
   Although many companies require new employees to sign
confidentiality agreements, it is highly unusual for a company to
require terminated employees to sign such an agreement as a
condition of receiving severance pay.
   ``It's not illegal, but I wouldn't consider it morally right,''
said an analyst with Mercer, Meidinger and Hansen, a leading human
resources consulting firm in Washington.
   Nearly all of Goldome's laid-off workers have signed the
agreement, sources said.
   Goldome, one of the nation's leading thrifts, lost $119 million
last year and is in the middle of a restructuring effort led by new
chief executive officer Thomas Cooper.
   Goldome officials have refused to discuss the layoffs or the
confidentiality agreement. A bank spokeswoman said Thursday the
company had a longstanding policy of not discussing employee matters.
   Sources within the company said management thinks news of
Goldome's layoffs could cause customers to withdraw money from the
bank.
   The new confidentiality requirement comes after the company
reduced its severance policy May 1. Companies are not required by
law to provide any severance pay, but most offer it as part of a
benefits package to attract qualified employees and as a
humanitarian gesture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
