<FILEID>AP-NR-06-15-89 2014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Europe-DebtPlan     06-15 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europe-Debt Plan,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Chief Says European Nations Split On U.S. Debt Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe's leaders are divided over whether to
endorse a U.S. plan for easing the debt of Third World Countries, a
top European trade official said Thursday.
   Failure by prosperous European nations to support the plan could
undermine the package proposed last March by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady for reducing by 20 percent the debt owed by the 39
largest debtor nations.
   The U.S. plan will be one of several major topics of conversation
at the summit of the world's seven leading industrialized nations to
be held in Paris next month, said Jacques Delors, President of the
Commission of the European Communities.
   President George Bush is hoping to win approval for the package
and consolidate the success of his new administration's other major
foreign policy initiative _ the proposal adopted earlier this month
by NATO to reduce superpower troops and weapons in Europe.
   Delors, who met with Bush on Wednesday, said the 12-nation
European organization is trying to reach agreement on its position
so that it can present a united front at the Paris summit. The EEC
takes part in the annual summits as the eighth participant, and four
of its members _ Britain, France, Italy and West Germany _ also take
part individually.
   ``There is a different approach'' among the EEC members, Delors
told reporters. ``I'm not sure we'll succeed'' in reaching a
consensus, he added.
   The leaders of the EEC are meeting in Madrid later this month to
discuss a compromise being fashioned by the host nation, Spain,
other EEC officials said.
   Chief among the European detractors of the Brady plan appear to
be Britain and West Germany, whose approach is ``more
conservative,'' said an EEC official who spoke on condition he not
be named.
   The British and Germans are concerned about the plan because they
view it as a bailout of the large commercial banks which hold much
of the estimated $370 billion debt, said the official.
   The U.S. proposal encourages the banks to voluntarily forgive a
portion of the debt burden in return for guarantees that the rest of
the money will be repaid. Those guarantees are to be provided by the
151-nation International Monetary Fund and its sister organization,
the World Bank.
   Banks have so far been lukewarm to the plan, saying the
guarantees offered by the World Bank and IMF are insufficient.
Critics of the plan say wealthy governments should offer additional
guarantees.
   Brady was in Europe earlier this month, seeking to enlist the
support of governments and international bankers.
   The Brady plan could suffer another setback if its first phase _
negotiations under way in New York between Mexico and its debtor
banks _ remain deadlocked. Bush had hoped to have the agreement
ready as a model to be presented to his fellow leaders in Paris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
