<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-15 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0707</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hog Futures Climb On Hopes For Stronger Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hog futures prices climbed Thursday on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange amid expectations for stronger pork demand late this summer
due to an anticipated tightening of beef supplies.
   On other markets, oil futures prices rose; precious metals were
higher; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Hog futures settled .05 cent to .90 cent higher with the contract
for delivery in June at 47.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .10 cent to 1.50 cents higher with July at 34.30 cents a pound;
live cattle were .15 cent to .35 cents higher with June at 71.42
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent to .52 cent higher with
August at 80.97 cents a pound.
   The contract for August delivery of hogs posted the sharpest
gain, .90 cent, at least partly on expectations that consumers will
be looking to buy more pork in August because beef prices are likely
to rise.
   The prediction is based on anticipation that Friday's 7-state
cattle-on-feed report from the Agriculture Department _ a monthly
tally of the cattle being fattened for slaughter in the seven
largest producer states _ will show about a 15 percent decline in
May feedlot placements compared to last year.
   If a smaller number of cattle were placed on feedlots this past
May than were placed a year earlier, the number of cattle ready for
slaughter by mid-summer will also be smaller than the previous year.
   Analysts expect Friday's report to show fewer placements because
of relatively large placements earlier this year due to dry pasture
conditions in the West.
   ``We're looking for tighter supplies of beef down the road, and
that creates demand for competitive meats, such as pork,'' said Paul
Georgy, president of Allendale Inc., a futures brokerage firm in
Crystal Lake, Ill.
   Cattle futures prices advanced moderately in line with firmer
cash prices in cautious trading ahead of Friday's cattle-on-feed
report.
   Crude-oil futures finished higher but well below the day's highs
on the New York Mercantile Exchange on signs of tightening supplies
of the U.S.-produced crudes that give the highest gasoline yields.
   ``Each day there is becoming less and less of the light, sweet
crude oil in the mid-continent,'' said Peter Beutel, an energy
analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   Beutel said the low oil prices of the mid-1980s discouraged
domestic oil exploration, so supplies of popular domestic crudes
such as West Texas Intermediate are relatively low.
   West Texas crude for July delivery climbed as high as $21 a
barrel Thursday but settled at $20.57, a gain of 34 cents from the
previous session. Other crude contracts settled 17 cents to 26 cents
higher. Heating oil was .36 cent to .70 cent higher with July at
46.26 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .12 cent to .48 cent
lower with July at 59.44 cents a gallon.
   A sharp drop in the dollar's value against major foreign
currencies gave precious-metals prices a boost on New York's
Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled $3.20 to $4.10 higher with August at $370.70 a troy
ounce; silver was 5 cents to 6.1 cents higher with July at $5.33 a
troy ounce.
   Wheat futures prices slipped on the Chicago Board of Trade while
corn and soybeans finished mixed on profit-taking after two straight
days of sharp gains.
   Slack export demand and expectations for a weekend of good
harvest weather in the Great Plains weighed on the wheat market.
   Selling in both the corn and soybean markets was offset by buying
linked to Wednesday's National Weather Service six-to-10-day
outlook, which predicted warmer, drier weather in the Corn Belt next
week, and to weakness in the dollar, which could encourage foreign
purchases of U.S. grain.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 5\ cents lower with July at $3.94\ a
bushel; corn was unchanged to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.59\ a
bushel; oats were \ cent to } cent lower with July at $1.66{ a
bushel; soybeans were 2 cents lower to 9 cents higher with July at
$7.34 a bushel.
</TEXT>
