</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eastern Flight Riddled with Safety Problems, Pilots Say</NOTE>
<NOTE>With BC-Eastern-Maintenance</NOTE>
<NOTE>By MARCY GORDON</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Business Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``I have thanked God that I am alive today. If
air crew members cannot get better support than we had on this
flight, I feel we should tender our operating certificate to the
FAA.''
   That was the verdict of John Rosser, second officer on Eastern
Airlines' Flight 9 from Miami to Guayaquil, Ecuador, on Aug. 4, 1988
_ a flight pilots describe as a brush with death of which the 295
passengers were unaware.
   The regularly scheduled three-hour trip in a Lockheed L-1011
TriStar illustrates what many Eastern pilots call the range of
maintenance problems that have plagued the airline. The safety
question has emerged as an element in the pilots' union decision to
honor a strike by mechanics that began March 4.
   A copy of the Flight 9 pilots' report, an internal document of
the Air Line Pilots Association, was obtained by the Associated
Press. The report gives the impression that nearly everything that
could go wrong did.
   Eastern declined to comment on the Flight 9 report. The FAA,
which is monitoring Eastern's compliance with maintenance
procedures, also declined to comment. Officials at both the airline
and the federal agency had been informed of the incident, the pilots
say.
   As outlined in the pilots' account, one of three electrical
generators on Flight 9 wasn't working. One of three air conditioners
was defective, creating cabin temperatures near 100 degrees
Fahrenheit. The temperature gauge for one engine turbine had been
reported as inoperative several times over the previous four months.
   The Omega long-range navigation system, required by federal
regulations for flying over water, was found unreliable when checked
against other navigating devices aboard. The flight recorder, or
``black box,'' was inoperative. The fuel gauge was inaccurate.
   Those deficiencies, the pilots contended, should have been
corrected before the flight but were superficially patched or passed
over in a rush to get off the ground.
   In addition, human error saddled the plane with around 15,000
pounds of extra fuel in the wing tanks, making the right wing
heavier than the left, the report charged.
   A faulty count recorded 200 passengers instead of 295, and the
crew was short 50 meals.
   According to the Flight 9 report entry by Bill Homer, 53, a
30-year Eastern veteran who captained the plane, his inspection of
the maintenance log before takeoff from Miami showed the turbine gas
temperature system hadn't been repaired despite several reports.
   Homer told his supervisor Mike Vaughn, Eastern's chief pilot,
that he wouldn't fly the aircraft because he considered it unsafe.
   Homer quoted Vaughn as responding that he ``didn't like his
attitude''.
   The first officer on the flight, Glyn Taylor, also told Vaughn he
felt the plane was unsafe and would put the crew under too much
stress to fly. Taylor said he was suffering from stress and high
blood pressure because of the situation.
   Vaughn ordered Taylor to report to Eastern's medical facility for
a psychiatric evaluation. He later took medical leave, according to
Homer's report.
   Another first officer was called to replace Taylor. Meanwhile,
the flight had been scheduled to leave Miami at 1:15 p.m. EDT but
was delayed for hours by the inspection check and the encounters
between the pilots. The new first officer arrived at around 7 p.m.
and the flight departed around 7:30.
   Fifteen minutes later, Homer recounted in the report, he realized
the fuel gauge was inaccurate and the plane was carrying 15,000
pounds of extra fuel because of a faulty calculation by ground
staff. At that point, a flight attendant entered the cockpit and
informed Homer that they were 50 meals short. When Homer replied
that there were only 200 passengers aboard, the attendant said there
were 295.
   The extra fuel and 95 passengers created a weight problem for the
TriStar. Homer decided he must make a careful, overweight landing in
Guayaquil and ruled out the options of dumping fuel or returning to
Miami.
   An overweight landing involves increased landing speeds with
unusual stress on the landing gear and tires, the report notes.
   After delicate procedures and visual checks of the wing flaps,
Homer landed safely in Guayaquil. He refused to fly the next
scheduled leg of the flight to Quito.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday June 18</NOTE>
