<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   06-15 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took a pounding Thursday, hit by
futures-related selling programs plus plunges in bond prices and the
dollar.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 28.36 to 2,475.00.
   Losers swamped gainers in nationwide trading of New York Stock
Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,078 issues down, 444 up and 466
unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 179.48 million
shares, up from 170.54 million in the previous session.
   Larry Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., said computer-driven program trading manuevers ahead of
Friday's ``triple witching hour'' accentuated the selloff.
   Stocks were sold in preparation for the so-called triple witching
hour, something that occurs once each quarter when stock-index
futures, index options and options on individual stocks expire. Wall
Streeters expect trading volume to be heavy Friday as investors
adjust their positions in stocks and futures.
   A setback in the credit market acted as a catalyst for the stock
selling. The 30-year Treasury bond dropped about 1{ points, or $15
for every $1,000 in value. The bond's decline coincided with a steep
slide in the dollar.
   Bond traders previously had been buying amid optimism that the
dollar's recent strength would draw foreign money into U.S.
investments.
   Wachtel said the market declines were unsurprising.
   ``I guess we just got a case of tired blood,'' he said. ``The
bond market, the stock market and the dollar have all moved to
excess.''
   ``When you begin to see days when you have over 1,000 declines,
you know you're tuckered out,'' he said in reference to the number
of shares that lost value on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday.
   Stock analysts detected little direct reaction to a Commerce
Department report showing the country's merchandise trade deficit
fell to $8.26 billion in April from March's deficit of $9.54 billion.
   Evidence of slower economic growth didn't evoke much of a
response in the stock market either.
   The Federal Reserve reported that the operating rate for U.S.
factories, mines and utilities dropped in May to 83.8 percent, down
0.3 percentage point from the previous month. The Fed also reported
that the pace of industrial production held steady in May.
   Takeover stocks continued to command investors' attention.
   Paramount Communications finished unchanged at 59{ and was the
most heavily traded NYSE-listed issue on volume of nearly 2.8
million shares.
   Warner Communications rose | to 55| and Time slid 3| to 171{.
   Few blue chips bucked the downtrend. International Business
Machines fell 1 to 109], American Telephone &amp; Telegraph fell | to
35\ and Merck dipped \ to 68. USX, however, rose | to 37}.
   Integrated Resources sank 5} to 6\ as more than 1.6 million
shares changed hands.
   Monsanto pushed ahead 2} to 106} on news that the company and its
G.D. Searle unit have agreed to settle a dispute involving an
intrauterine device.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 210.32 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $32.78 billion, or 1.02
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.86 to 178.97.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index dropped 4.20 to 366.20, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index declined 3.75 to 320.08.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market fell
3.54 to 447.10. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 361.00, off 2.83.
</TEXT>
