<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-15 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude futures prices rose in active trading
Thursday, while refined petroleum products turned in a mixed
performance.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, advanced 34
cents to close at $20.57 a barrel after trading as high as $21 a
barrel. Contracts for delivery later in the year showed more modest
gains.
   Among refined oil products, unleaded gasoline prices fell on what
analysts said was a late bout of profit-taking. Unleaded gasoline
for July delivery fell 0.48 cent to finish at 59.44 cents a gallon,
while contracts for later delivery also declined.
   July heating oil rose 0.61 cent to 46.26 cents a gallon, pulled
up by crude prices, energy brokers said. The contract rose 1.07
cents in Wednesday's session.
   Analysts said there was little economic news to drive crude
prices higher. However, a change in the method of delivery of crude
oil to various customers had some investors worried.
   Traders said some customers who had been receiving WTI were
getting similar light, sweet crude that met their specifications but
was not WTI.
   ``What we're seeing is for some reason a bit of a panic on
delivery of spot crude,'' said Greg Dreis, a broker with Merrill
Lynch Energy Futures. ``The contract just says it must be a sweet,
light crude, and some WTI is being replaced with foreign and other
oil.''
   Observers said that in some cases buyers who want only WTI are
being asked to pay extra for delivery.
   Analysts said July crude prices also were pushed higher by
investors buying before the contract expires on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
