<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Economy Bjt   06-15 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Economy, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Dollar: Possibly Good For Toyota Buyers, Bad For Kodak Employees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong dollar is good for buyers of Toyota
Camrys but bad for the people who make film for Eastman Kodak Co.
It's bad for foresters in the Northwest but good for wine buyers on
Park Avenue.
   For the nation as a whole, a strong dollar raises the likelihood
of a recession, economists say.
   The dollar has soared this year, causing reappraisals by everyone
from car-buying consumers to chief executives of the Fortune 500. A
rising dollar increases American buying power abroad and at home for
foreign-made goods, but also makes U.S. exports more expensive and
therefore less competitive.
   What's not clear is how long the dollar's rally will last. It
suffered a sharp setback on Thursday when a round of panicky selling
drove the currency down 2.5 percent against the British pound, West
German mark and Japanese yen.
   Thursday's steep drop raised the possibility that the long-term
downtrend in the dollar that began in early 1985 was reasserting
itself.
   ``If the downward trend were to be reestablished, this rally
would look like a little wart, or a bump on the side of a hill,''
said Christopher Probyn, a financial economist at DRI-McGraw-Hill
Inc.
   Before Thursday's drop the dollar had reached heights not seen
against various major currencies since 1987 or late 1986.
   If vacationers are any measure, most Americans have not changed
their behavior much yet in response to the dollar's rise. The
nation's biggest chain of travel agencies, Ask Mr. Foster Travel,
says the increase in bookings to foreign destinations has been
negligible.
   Buyers of imported cars are not seeing the benefit of the
dollar's strength yet, although Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. says it
will take the rise into account in August when it makes pricing
decisions on its 1990 models.
   ``It certainly takes the pressure off'' the need for price hikes,
said J.R. Olson, a Toyota spokesman. But he added, ``There's no
telling where the yen is going to be two months from now.''
   A bottle of white wine from Australia _ say, a Sutherland
semillon _ costs $9 now compared to $10 in early 1988 at Acker
Merrall &amp; Condit Co. in Manhattan.
   Employees and stockholders of companies such as Kodak and
Weyerhaeuser Co. that rely on exports are concerned about the
dollar's strength.
   Weyerhaeuser said the combination of the strong dollar and strong
customer demand in the past year has driven to $840 from $725 the
price per metric ton it charges in Europe for its Northern bleached
kraft pulp, which is used in making paper products.
   That could make it tougher to compete against rival Scandinavian
producers.
   For Kodak, ``We are concerned, let me put it that way,''
spokesman Henry Kaska said. ``It can affect our competitive
position.''
   ``There is a lag time of about a year before this starts catching
up with you. But we're concerned and we'll be increasingly concerned
if this upward trend doesn't reverse itself,'' he said.
   Thirty-four of 52 economists surveyed in early May by Blue Chip
Economic Indicators of Sedona, Ariz., were counting on the dollar to
decline into 1990, helping the economy.
   In spite of that, two-thirds expected a recession later this year
or next year. If the dollar rises, that would increase the chance of
a recession, said Bob Eggert, editor of the survey.
   ``It is weakening the one area of the economy, trade, which has
the kind of strength necessary to keep the economy out of a
recession. So it's serious,'' said DRI's Probyn.
   At a time when the economy already is slowing, the dollar's
strength could be the fatal blow to the longest peacetime expansion
in U.S. history, one that dates to the fall of 1982.
</TEXT>
