<FIRST>u f AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0128 06-15 0868</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0128,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Narrows in April; Strong Dollar Still a Concern</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4 grafs for 7th graf pvs with dollar down Thursday; PICKS
UP 8th graf pvs, `So far...; Also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Thursday that the U.S trade
deficit narrowed dramatically to $8.26 billion in April, its lowest
level in nine months, but even the Bush administration is concerned
that the strong dollar could stunt future progress.
   April's deficit was down 13.4 percent from a revised March trade
gap of $9.54 billion, the Commerce Department reported. The
improvement reflected a 0.8 percent increase in exports, to a record
$30.57 billion, and a 2.6 percent drop in imports, to $38.84
billion, despite rising prices for foreign oil.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher hailed the report as evidence
of ``continued improvement in U.S. trade performance'' but he added
a note of caution.
   ``While the April data are encouraging, it is always unwise to
put too much weight on any one or two months' figures in these
volatile statitics,'' he said. ``The recent strength of the dollar
leads us to be concerned about the economy's ability to sustain the
excellent trends seen so far.''
   The Bush administration has been hoping for continued progress on
narrowing the trade gap to spur economic growth. Last year's big 21
percent drop in the trade deficit from an all-time high of $152.1
billion in 1987 accounted for nearly half of all U.S. economic
growth.
   Many analysts are concerned that the trade gap could start to
widen again due to the recent strength of the dollar, which makes
U.S. goods more expensive on overseas markets and imports cheaper
for American consumers.
   The dollar reversed path Thursday as traders who had been
boosting the currency started selling it heavily. The U.S. currency
dropped 2.5 percent or more against the British pound, West German
Mark and the Japanese yen.
   Traders said there was no fundamental news to account for the
drop and that it appeared instead the dollar's quick rise may have
made it ripe for a selloff by speculators anxious to cash in their
gains.
   ``It was just inevitable we would reach some level where there
were just no more buyers and the sellers would gain the advantage,''
said Bob Giordano, chief dealer at Bank Leumi Trust Co. in New York.
   For the first four months of the year, the trade deficit was
running at an annual rate of $109.4 billion, well below last year's
actual deficit of $119.76 billion. April's trade gap was the
smallest since an $8.02 billion deficit last July.
   ``So far this year we're going great guns,'' said economist Maury
Harris of PaineWebber Inc. in New York. ``But eventually, this
higher dollar's going to eat into exports.''
   Economist Cynthia Latta of Data Resources Inc. in Lexington,
Mass., said that while U.S. businesses have improved their
competitive position in the world marketplace, ``we're not going to
hold on to that competitive position if the dollar continues to
rise.''
   However, William T. Archey, vice president of the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said that with April's favorable report, worries about the
impact of the dollar on the trade deficit ``have been revealed as
exaggerations.''
   Analysts said the narrowing of the deficit so far this year, even
as foreign oil prices have marched upward, has been partly a
reflection of a general slowdown in an economy that is sucking in
fewer foreign goods.
   In another sign of a slowing economy, the Federal Reserve
reported Thursday that the operating rate for U.S. factories dropped
in May to 83.8 percent, down 0.3 percentage point from the previous
month. The Fed also reported that the pace of industrial production
held steady in May.
   Analysts said the easing of factory use could help relieve
inflationary pressures in the economy.
   On the trade front, imports fell in April to a seasonally
adjusted $38.84 billion, reflecting declines in sales of foreign
cars, manufactured capital goods and agricultural products.
   The dip occurred even though the bill for foreign oil jumped 9.9
percent to $4.05 billion. The average price of a barrel of oil shot
up 11.6 percent to $17.83 in April, the fifth straight monthly
increase.
   U.S. exports, meanwhile, hit a record $30.57 billion in April as
foreign sales of American-made industrial supplies, manufactured
capital goods and consumer goods all increased.
   As usual, the United States posted its largest trade deficit in
April with Japan. But the $3.89 billion gap was down sharply from
$4.22 billion in March.
   Other large deficits were recorded with Taiwan, $840 million;
South Korea, $545 million; Canada, $477 million; and Brazil, $365
million.
   The nation's trade picture was helped by a second straight
surplus with Western Europe. The surplus registered $232 million in
April and $397 million in March.
   On Tuesday, the government reported that a broader measure of
U.S. trade worsened dramatically during the first three months of
the year. The Commerce Department said the deficit in the current
account was 7 percent larger than in the final three months of 1988.
That deficit figure reflected improvement in merchandise trade but a
widening of the deficit in the services category.
</TEXT>
