<FIRST>r f BC-LTVSteel-Workers     06-15 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-LTV Steel-Workers,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Sale of LTV Steel's Bar Division to Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday approved the
sale of LTV Corp.'s Ohio-based steel bar division to workers, a
company official said.
   The sale for approximately $220 million to a new Employee Stock
Ownership Plan corporation with headquarters in Massillon, Ohio,
still must be ratified by employees who are members of the United
Steelworkers of America, LTV spokesman Charles Palmer said.
   A new labor agreement now must be worked out between the
steelworkers union and the employee group, Palmer added.
   The sale was approved by Judge Burton R. Lifland of U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York, Palmer said.
   The sale agreement was announced May 30. Russell W. Maier,
current president of the bar operations, is to be the new company's
chief executive.
   At the time of the May 30 announcement, LTV Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Raymond A. Hay, said:
   ``The sale of the bar division will complete the divestitute of
steel operations identified for disposition as part of LTV's
long-range plan to emerge from Chapter 11 with a profitable but
down-sized steel company, concentrating on the flat rolled and
tubular business.''
   LTV said then that the 4,700 salaried, hourly and senior
management employees in the bar division would be offered employment
with the new company, which is projected to produce about 1.2
million tons of steel a year.
   Dallas-based LTV is a diversified manufacturing company involved
in steel, aerospace, defense and energy products.
   The division's steelmaking facilities in Canton, Ohio, provide
continuously cast and ingot-poured billets for hot rolling mills in
Canton and Massillon, Ohio, and Chicago.
   The Canton plant also provides steel to the division's cold
finished bar plants in Massillon; Gary, Ind.; Willimantic, Conn.;
and Beaver Falls, Pa.; as well as the division's special metals
plant in Canton, which produces alloy steel for aerospace and
defense applications.
</TEXT>
