<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets     06-15 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Share Prices Rise Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened sharply lower against the
Japanese yen Friday morning, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rebounded strongly.
   The dollar started trading at 146.00 yen, down 5.30 yen from
Thursday's 151.30-yen close, the highest since mid-August 1987.
   Traders attributed the dollar's plunge to concerted
dollar-selling intervention by the U.S. and European central banks
overnight.
   The dollar surged shortly after the U.S. Commerce Department's
announcement Thursday morning that the nation's April trade deficit
was $8.26 billion, down from $8.9 billion in March. But then it
plunged in trading analysts said was driven by a lack of confidence
among investors.
   An analyst at the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar-yen rate was
fluctuating wildly, making it difficult to predict which direction
the trading would turn.
   ``The volatility is in part because of the Bank of Japan's
dollar-selling intervention,'' he added, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   The amount of dollars the central bank sold was unknown, he said.
The Bank of Japan makes no comments on its monetary activities.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, which shed 489.90 points Thursday, its largest one-day loss
this year, quickly picked up 267.17 points, or 0.82 percent,
rebounding to 33,180.26 within the first 15 minutes of trading.
   Stock dealers said the yen's surge in currency markets overnight
had reassured Japanese investors.
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average of 30 major issues
lost 28.36 points overnight following the dollar's plunge agaist
other major currencies.
</TEXT>
